{"title_page": "Event Horizon (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 UK-US science fiction horror movie directed by Paul W. S. Anderson}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Event Horizon\n| image          = Event horizon ver1.jpg\n| alt            = Picture of spacecraft with text \"Infinite size, Infinite Terror\"\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Paul W. S. Anderson]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n* [[Lloyd Levin]]\n* [[Jeremy Bolt]]\n}}\n| writer         = [[Philip Eisner]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]] \n* [[Sam Neill]] \n* [[Kathleen Quinlan]] \n* [[Joely Richardson]] \n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Kamen]]\n}} <!-- Orbital received \"additional music\" credit, Kamen was the lead composer -->\n| cinematography = [[Adrian Biddle]]\n| editing        = Martin Hunter<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n| production companies = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]\n* Golar Productions\n* [[Impact Pictures]]<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1997|08|15|U.S.|df=y|1997|08|22|U.K.}}\n| runtime        = 96 min.<ref>{{cite web|title=''EVENT HORIZON'' (18)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/event-horizon-film|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = U.K.<ref name=\"bfi\">{{cite web|title=Event Horizon (1997)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b7fd8d4ad|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref><br />U.S.<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |title= Event Horizon (1997) | url = http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1997/EVENT.php |work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate = 18 August 2011}}</ref>\n| gross          = $26.7 million (US)<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=eventhorizon.htm|title=Event Horizon (1997)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Event Horizon''''' is a 1997 [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[horror film]] directed by [[Paul W. S. Anderson]] and written by [[Philip Eisner]]. It stars [[Laurence Fishburne]], [[Sam Neill]], [[Kathleen Quinlan]] and [[Joely Richardson]]. Set in 2047, it follows a crew of astronauts sent on a rescue mission after a missing spaceship, the ''Event Horizon'', which spontaneously appears in orbit around [[Neptune]], seven years after it's disappearance. Searching the ship for signs of life, the rescue crew learns that the ''Event Horizon'' was a test bed for an experimental engine that opened a rift in the [[Spacetime|space\u2013time continuum]] and had left our universe entirely, allowing a malevolent entity to possess the ship.\n\nThe film had a troubled production history, with filming and editing rushed by [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] when it became clear that ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' would not meet its projected release date. The original 130-minute cut of the film was heavily edited by demand of the studio, to the consternation of Director Anderson.\n\nUpon release, the film was a commercial and critical failure, grossing $26.7 million on a $60 million production budget. Even so, it began to sell well on [[home video]]; its initial DVD release sold so well that Paramount contacted Anderson shortly after its release to begin working on a restoration of the deleted footage.<ref name=\"Commentary\"/><ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TXL_CM4DXZ8|title=Paul W.S. Anderson Event Horizon Q&A|date=18 December 2011|publisher=[[YouTube]]|first=Jonny|last=Bunning|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">The Making of Event Horizon</ref> However, it turned out that the footage had either been lost or destroyed. In the years since, the film has slowly built a [[cult film|cult following]] and is often referenced and parodied in other works of popular culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/event-horizon/256807/event-horizon-from-doomed-ship-to-cult-gem |title=Event Horizon: From Doomed Ship to Cult Gem|work=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|accessdate=2 February 2017|first=Ryan|last=Lambie|date=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2047, a distress signal is received from the ''Event Horizon'', a [[starship]] that disappeared seven years prior during its maiden voyage to [[Proxima Centauri]]. It has mysteriously reappeared in a [[orbital decay|decaying orbit]] around [[Neptune]]. The rescue vessel ''Lewis and Clark'' is dispatched. Its crew \u2013 Captain Miller, second-in-command Lieutenant Starck, pilot Smith, medical technician Peters, engineer Ensign Justin, Doctor D.J. and rescue technician Cooper \u2013 is joined by Dr. William Weir, who originally designed the ''Event Horizon's'' engine. He briefs (but really teaches) in layman's terms  the crew on the ship's experimental [[Faster-than-light|gravity drive]]. Which generates an artificial [[black hole]] and uses it to [[Wormhole|bridge]] two points in [[spacetime]], reducing travel time over astronomical distances. The distress signal seems to consist of a series of screams and howls but D.J. believes he can discern the [[Latin]] phrase \"''Liberate me''\" (\"Save me\") being spoken.<!-- per transcript - see discussion at Talk -->\n\nUpon boarding the ''Event Horizon'', the crew finds evidences of a massacre. Running into floating discombobulated limbs and frozen corpses. As they continue searching for survivors, the ship's gravity drive suddenly activates, sucking Justin into the resulting portal and causing a giant shockwave that damages the ''Lewis and Clark'', forcing the entire crew to board the ''Event Horizon''. Cooper rescues Justin who emerges in a [[catatonia|catatonic state]]. While in the Med Bay Justin's going in and out of consciousness and is visually terrified by what he saw on the other side. He attempts suicide by decompression, but is saved by Miller in the nic of time, forcing the crew to place him in [[suspended animation|stasis]].\n\nThe team begins to experience [[Jump scare|jump scares]] of apparitions or visions of individuals from their past that only they can see.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Horror in Space: Critical Essays on a Film Subgenre|last=Brittany|first=Michele|publisher=McFarland|year=2017|isbn=978-14766-6405-7|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=3}}</ref> Hallucinations corresponding to their fears and/or regrets:  \n\nCapt. Miller sees Corrick, a subordinate whom Miller was forced to abandon to his death, in the engine room on fire. Peters sees her son with his legs covered in bloody lesions on a table in the medical b, D.J. appears behind her, and her son disappears. . While fixing a smoking circuit board, Dr. Weir starts hearing the voice of his deceased wife and by a sudden appearance of an eyeless, naked vision of his wife, urging him to join her. \n\nThe crew, mainly Peters, soon discover a video log of the ''Event Horizon''{{'}}s fornicating and mutilating each other shortly after first engaging the gravity drive. The video log ends with a shot of the ''Event Horizon''{{'}}s captain speaking the complete Latin phrase from the earlier distress call, which D.J. translates \"''Liberate tutemet ex inferis<!-- per transcript - see discussion at Talk -->''\" \"Save ''yourself'' from hell\".\n\nDeducing that the ''Event Horizon''<nowiki/>'s gravity drive opened a gateway to a hellish dimension outside the [[universe|known universe]], and that the ship itself has somehow attained \ufffc\ufffc[[sentience]]\ufffc\ufffc. Miller decides to destroy the ''Event Horizon'' and orders an evacuation. Peters is lured to her death by a hallucination of her son. Weir, who has gouged his own eyes out and is now possessed by the evil presence, uses an explosive device to destroy the ''Lewis and Clark''. The explosion kills Smith and blasts Cooper off into space. Weir kills D.J. by [[Vivisection|vivisecting]] him and corners Starck on the [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]]. Miller confronts Weir, who overpowers him and initiates a 10-minute countdown until the ''Event Horizon'' will return to the other dimension.\n\nCooper, having used his space suit's oxygen supply to propel himself back to the ship, appears at the bridge window. Weir shoots at him through the window and is blown into space by the ensuing decompression. Miller, Starck, and Cooper survive and manage to seal off the ship's bridge. With their own ship destroyed, Miller plans to split the ''Event Horizon'' into two, from the midsection between aft to stern, and uses the forward section of the ship as a lifeboat. He's attacked by manifestations of Corrick and a resurrected Weir. Miller fights them off and detonates the explosives, sacrificing himself.\n\nThe gravity drive activates, pulling the ship's stern section into a black hole. Starck and Cooper enter stasis beside a comatose Justin, and wait to be rescued. 72 days later, the wreckage of the ''Event Horizon'' is boarded by a rescue party, who discover the remaining crew still in stasis. Starck sees Weir posing as one of the rescuers and screams in terror; this is revealed to be a [[nightmare]] with Starck waking up moments later. However, as Cooper and the rescue team comfort the newly-awakened and terrified Starck, the doors unexpectedly close.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}* [[Laurence Fishburne]] as Captain Miller, Commanding Officer\n* [[Sam Neill]] as Dr. William 'Billy' Weir, Designer of  ''Event Horizon''\n* [[Kathleen Quinlan]] as Peters 'Mama Bear,' Medical Technician\n* [[Joely Richardson]] as Lt. Starck, Communications & Executive Officer\n* [[Richard T. Jones]] as Cooper, Rescue Technician\n* [[Jack Noseworthy]] as Ensign Justin 'Baby Bear,' Chief Engineer\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as D.J., Medical Doctor\n* [[Sean Pertwee]] as Smith 'Smitty', Pilot\n* [[Peter Marinker]] as Captain John Kilpack, Commanding Officer\n* Holley Chant as Claire Weir, Dr. Weir's wife\n* Barclay Wright as Denny Peters, son of Technician Peters\n* [[Noah Huntley]] as Edmund Corrick, Miller's former shipmate from the ''Goliath''\n* [[Robert Jezek]] as Rescue Technician, rescues survivors of the ''Lewis & Clark''{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nAfter ''[[Mortal Kombat (1995 film)|Mortal Kombat]]'' (1995) had become a commercial success in the United States, English director [[Paul W. S. Anderson]] was inundated with screenplay offers, as well as the opportunity to direct the ''Mortal Kombat'' sequel ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]]'' (1997),<ref name=\"fangoria\">{{cite magazine|last=Hughes|first=David|date=August 1997|title=Terrors Beyond the ''Event Horizon''|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_165_1997_Event_Horizon_HQS_c2c/page/n29|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|issue=165|pages=30\u201335|doi=|issn=0164-2111|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> and the upcoming ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]'' (2000).<ref name=\"Commentary\">{{cite AV media | people=[[Paul W. S. Anderson]] (Director), [[Jeremy Bolt]] (Producer) | year=2006 | title=Event Horizon | medium=Audio commentary | publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Anderson turned the offers down in favor of making an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R-rated]] horror film, hoping to shift away from making another [[PG-13]] film.<ref name=\"Commentary\"/> [[Paramount Pictures]] then sent [[Philip Eisner]]'s original script for ''Event Horizon'', which they had been trying to develop with producers [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]] and [[Lloyd Levin]].<ref name=\"makingof\">{{cite AV media | people=[[Paul W. S. Anderson]] (Director), [[Jeremy Bolt]] (Producer) | year=2006 | title=The Making of Event Horizon | medium=Documentary | publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Accordingng to Eisner, he first [[pitch (filmmaking)|pitched]] its concept to Gordon as a \"haunted house story in space\", which the producer thought had the potential to become a motion picture: \"''Luckily'',\" said Eisner, \"''he liked the idea enough to trust me to do it''.\"<ref name=\"fangoria\"/>\n\nAnderson's initial reaction to the script, which involved the cruise ship ''Event Horizon'' experiencing a series of hauntings by \"tentacular\" aliens having crossed the threshold of their planet or \"dimension\", was that it bore striking resemblance to ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]'' (1979), while producer and longtime collaborator [[Jeremy Bolt]] felt it was a \"terrific concept\" but was \"very dense\" in terms of length and the storyline was \"a bit lost.\"<ref name=\"makingof\" /> Anderson disliked directing a mimicry of ''Alien'' so he gave the script a major rewrite. Anderson had in mind a \"classic haunted house movie,\" incorporating significant influences to moderately successful horror films such as [[Robert Wise]]'s ''[[The Haunting (1963 film)|The Haunting]]'' (1963) and [[Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980). Because they enforce suspense from the unknown, meaning the ghost and/or creature was hidden from the viewer, and their endings induced ambiguities of perception in the audience.<ref name=\"makingof\" /> He was also interested in the concept of [[Hell]], as well as the idea of \"''the ship itself being possessed rather than going 'Oh, it's an alien consciousness that is doing this'','\" and added these in the script.<ref name=\"makingof\" />\n\nScreenwriter [[Philip Eisner]] acknowledged ''[[Warhammer 40,000]]'' as a major inspiration for the plot.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=phubar |author-link=Philip Eisner |number=860129292151214082 |date=May 4, 2017 |title=I played the shit out of 40K, so it was definitely an influence, conscious or otherwise.}}</ref> In the fictional setting of ''Warhammer 40,000'', starships travel the galaxy by passing through \"the Warp,\" which is a parallel dimension where faster-than-light travel is possible, similar to \"[[hyperspace]]\" in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' and [[Star Trek|''Star Trek'']] settings, but also infested with daemons that are liable to infiltrate the ship and possess the crew. Many fans of ''Warhammer 40,000'' consider ''Event Horizon'' to be an unofficial prequel to the former, when humankind discovers the Warp drive and learns of its dangers the hard way.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geek.com/tech/is-the-1997-movie-event-horizon-a-secret-warhammer-40k-prequel-1658234/ |title=Is the 1997 movie Event Horizon a secret Warhammer 40k prequel? |author=Ryan Whitwam |date=15 June 2016 |website=Geek.com |access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Editing===\nAs Anderson explains, directors usually have a standard 10-week editing period to produce the first cut of a film, as guaranteed by the [[Directors Guild of America]]. However, due to the short production schedule of the film, the rapidly approaching release date, and the fact that principal photography had not yet finished, Anderson agreed with the [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] studio to an editing period of 6 weeks and promised to deliver the film by August 1997, as Paramount wanted to have a hit film before ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic's]]'' planned September release date. When the main unit wrapped, Anderson was supposed to start editing the film, but he still had to shoot 2 weeks with the [[second unit]], effectively shortening the time he could spend in post-production to just 4 weeks. In that short amount of time, only a rough cut of the film could be assembled. Anderson notes that at 2 hrs 10 min., it was overly long, with weak directing and acting that could have used another editing pass, unfinished special effects, and a poor sound mix.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nIn [[test screening]]s, the cut was poorly received. There were complaints about the extreme amount of gore,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and Anderson and producer [[Jeremy Bolt]] claim members of the test audience fainted during the screening.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> Paramount, which had stopped watching the [[dailies]] before any of the gore was shot and were seeing the completed film for the first time along with the audience, were similarly shocked by how gruesome it was and demanded a shorter runtime with less gore. Anderson believes that while his first cut was justifiably considered too long, Paramount forced him to make a cut that was instead too short, and that the film would benefit by the restoration of around 10 minutes of footage, including some of the deleted gore.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> \n\n===Missing Footage===\nAfter the initial [[DVD]] release became a surprise hit, the studio and Anderson became interested in assembling a [[director's cut]], but they quickly discovered that the excised footage had not been carefully stored and much of it had gone missing. The plan to assemble a director's cut was abandoned and instead a special-edition two-DVD set was released, featuring one deleted scene, two extended scenes, and a few shots of deleted material in the included [[making-of]] featurette. The footage is of \"[[Videotape|video]]\" quality.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\nKnown deleted scenes include a meeting scene between Weir and people in charge of the mission in which they discuss ''Event Horizon'', some dialogue of which remained present in the theatrical trailer;<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ocQvTGLuBY8|title=Event Horizon deleted scene|date=8 October 2010|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=TheDronemaster}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pugTKXUUlGk|title=Event Horizon (1997) Trailer|date=13 February 2009|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=HorrorMoviesBlog}}</ref> more backstory for Cooper and Justin, including a stronger explanation for Justin entering the black hole; a deleted backstory of the relationship between Starck and Miller; additional scenes explaining what the gateway to hell/black hole is;<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Anthony C.|last=Ferrante|title=The Cutting Room: Event Horizon|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|issue=170|page=12|accessdate=16 July 2018|url=http://www.oocities.org/hollywood/Cinema/3615/mag/mag3.html |issn=0164-2111}}</ref> Miller finding a tooth floating in ''Event Horizon'';<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> a longer version of the scene in which Peters hallucinates that her son's mangled legs are covered in maggots;<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> a scene in which Weir hallucinates that Justin turns into his wife Claire;<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n4Z6ln27_cE|title=Behind The Scenes \"Event Horizon\" part 4\\9. \u0417\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043d\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u0439\" \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c 4\\9|date=13 May 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=Simbacool69}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RzccmgGMcs|title=Behind The Scenes \"Event Horizon\" part 7\\9. \u0417\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043d\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u0439\" \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c 7\\9|date=13 May 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=Simbacool69}}</ref> a bloodier version of Weir's wife Claire's suicide; a longer version of the scene where Miller finds D.J.'s dead body with his guts on the table; and a longer version of the \"Visions From Hell\" scene during Miller's final fight with Weir with more shots of ''Event Horizon'' crew being tortured.{{better source|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe \"bloody orgy\" video was also longer. As Anderson was sometimes too busy filming other scenes, second-unit director Vadim Jean filmed some parts of this scene.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Real-life amputees were used for special effects scenes in which ''Event Horizon'' crew members were mutilated, and [[pornographic film]] actors were hired to make the sex and rape scenes more realistic and graphic.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\nThe film's final ending was a combination of two unused alternate endings that were filmed. The first ending didn't have a jump scare at the end when the last two survivors are found by another rescue crew and Starck hallucinates that she sees Weir. Although there was a similar version of the scene included in this ending where she hears screams of ''Event Horizon'' crew and screams in fear before Cooper wakes her up. This was the original ending of the film included in the shooting script.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsdb.com/scripts/Event-Horizon.html|title=Event Horizon|work=Internet Movie Script Database|accessdate=16 July 2018|first=Philip|last=Eisner}}</ref> The second ending had Miller fighting with the burned man from his visions at the core instead of with Weir, but this was changed due to the negative test screening.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nIn an ''Event Horizon'' ''Q&A'' in 2011, Anderson was asked when extra footage will be made available. He responded with \"never,\" explaining that much of its gone forever.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> However, in a 2012 interview, he announced that producer [[Lloyd Levin]] had found a [[VHS]] tape with his original rough cut. Anderson said that after finishing ''[[Resident Evil: Retribution]]'', he planned to watch it for the first time since assembling the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/paul-w-s-anderson-resident-evil-5-retribution-interview/|title=Paul W.S. Anderson Talks RESIDENT EVIL 5 RETRIBUTION, EVENT HORIZON, DEATH RACE: INFERNO|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex Media]]|first=Steve|last=Weintraub|date=17 July 2012|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref> In a January 2017 interview, Anderson reiterated a director's cut will never be released as the footage doesn't exist anymore. Asked about the VHS tape, he said neither he, nor Levin, had watched it yet, as Levin moved to Spain; however, he was still excited about watching it at some point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/2017/jan/25/screen-paul-ws-anderson-puts-end-resident-evil/?page=3|title=Paul W.S. Anderson puts an end to Resident Evil|work=[[San Diego Reader]]|date=25 January 2017|first=Scott|last=Marks|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Michael Kamen]] was hired to compose the score for the film. Director [[Paul W. S. Anderson]], a fan of hybrid genre music, invited the [[electronic dance music]] duo [[Orbital (band)|Orbital]] to collaborate with Kamen and to provide synthesizing sounds for the film's unsettling atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sAImDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Contemporary Film Music: Investigating Cinema Narratives and Composition|last=Coleman|first=Lindsay|last2=Tillman|first2=Joakim|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137573759|location=New York}}{{better source|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\nA soundtrack album was released which edited various cues from the score into four tracks of approximately ten minutes.\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on August 15, 1997 and was a box office failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.everthing.explained.today/Event_Horizon_(film)/|title=Event Horizon|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=January 4, 2020}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>  ''Event Horizon'' cost $60 million and only grossed $26,616,590 in the United States.<ref name=\"numbers\"/><ref name=\"BOM\"/>    The film did well on home DVD video release.\n\n==Reception==\nThe review-aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 27%, with an average rating of 4.75 out of 10, based on 74 reviews from critics. The website's \"Critics Consensus\" reads, \"Despite a strong opening that promises sci-fi thrills, ''Event Horizon'' quickly devolves into an exercise of style over substance whose flashy effects and gratuitous gore fail to mask its overreliance on horror clich\u00e9s.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/event_horizon/|title=Event Horizon (1997)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a weighted average score of 35 out of 100, based on 20 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/event-horizon|title=Event Horizon Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |website= [[CinemaScore]] |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Event Horizon |access-date= 9 November 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 20 December 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 2 stars out of 4, stating, \"The script creates a sense of foreboding and afterboding, but no actual boding.\"<ref>{{cite web | date = 15 August 1997 | authorlink = Roger Ebert |first=Roger |last=Ebert |publisher=Ebert Digtial LLC |accessdate=16 July 2018 | work = RogerEbert.com | title = Event Horizon (1997) | url = https://rogerebert.com/reviews/event-horizon-1997 }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' critic Stephen Hunter wrote, \"If you want to have that ''Event Horizon'' experience without spending the seven bucks, try this instead: Put a bucket on your head. Have a loved one beat on it vigorously with a wrench for 100 minutes. Same difference, and think of the gas you'll save\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/eventhorizonhunt.htm|title='Event Horizon': Blood Simple|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|first=Stephen |last=Hunter|accessdate=16 July 2018|date=15 August 1997}}</ref>\n\nThe film had some early supporters, with ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine awarding ''Event Horizon'' a 3 out of 5 stars rating, reporting: \"That the film never fulfils its promise is down to its over reliance on horror vagaries in a precision-built sci-fi milieu, ultimately leaving too many unanswered queries. A sharper script and a more credible solution could have turned this impressive hokum into a force to be reckoned with\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/review.asp?FID=13951|title=Empire's Event Horizon Movie Review|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|date=1 January 2000|first=Ian|last=Nathan}}</ref> Additionally, ''[[Total Film]]'' also gave it a score of 3 out of 5 stars, stating that \"Excellent special effects and an ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]''-esque feel make this supernatural horror film ('''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' in space,' as most critics have called it, pretty accurately) well worth a look. There are certainly plenty of jumps on offer as a possessed ship torments and tortures any humans it can find. Well worth a look.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/event-horizon-review/|title=Event Horizon review|author=Total Film|date=22 August 1997|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|publisher=Future Publishing}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a B-, stating, \"Just when you've written off this deep-space nightmare as a late-summer melange of ''Alien'', ''Fantastic Voyage'', ''The Shining'', and a dozen more forgettable otherworldly thrillers, it unleashes some of the most unsettling horror imagery in years\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1997/09/05/event-horizon-2/|title=Event Horizon|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|date=5 September 1997|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> whereas the ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine mentioned that \"despite its shortcomings, this is never dull. The movie avoids Alien space monster clich\u00e9s brilliantly and the soundtrack contains more of the 'Boo!' effects than I've heard since ''Halloween''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/event-horizon|title=Event Horizon|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]|publisher=Time Out Group|date=|author=NKE|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television series==\nIn August 2019, it was reported that [[Paramount Television]]  and [[Amazon Studios]] were developing a television series based on ''Event Horizon''. Horror filmmaker [[Adam Wingard]] is set to executive produce the series and possibly direct the series. Lawrence Gordon and Lloyd Levin, who produced the original film, are also involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/event-horizon-series-amazon-1203291883/|title='Event Horizon' Series in Development at Amazon (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variet Media, LLC|date=5 August 2019|first=Joe|last=Otterson}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1990s|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror|Science fiction}}\n* [[1997 in film]]\n* [[List of American films of 1997]]\n* [[List of horror films of 1997]]\n* [[List of incomplete or partially lost films]]\n* [[List of films featuring space stations]]\n* [[List of science fiction horror films]]\n* [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]]\n* ''[[Satan's Triangle]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Event Horizon}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119081|Event Horizon}}\n* {{Amg title|158616|Event Horizon}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes}} \n* {{Mojo title}}\n\n{{Paul W. S. Anderson}}\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1997 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Kamen]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Orbital (band)]]\n[[Category:Films about astronauts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul W. S. Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2047]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Wormholes in fiction]]\n[[Category:Neptune in film]]\n[[Category:Films about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Proxima Centauri in fiction]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 UK-US science fiction horror movie directed by Paul W. S. Anderson}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Event Horizon\n| image          = Event horizon ver1.jpg\n| alt            = Picture of spacecraft with the text \"Infinite size, Infinite Terror\"\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Paul W. S. Anderson]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]]\n* [[Lloyd Levin]]\n* [[Jeremy Bolt]]\n}}\n| writer         = [[Philip Eisner]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]] \n* [[Sam Neill]] \n* [[Kathleen Quinlan]] \n* [[Joely Richardson]] \n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Kamen]]\n}} <!-- Orbital received \"additional music\" credit, Kamen was the lead composer -->\n| cinematography = [[Adrian Biddle]]\n| editing        = Martin Hunter<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n| production companies  = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]\n* Golar Productions\n* [[Impact Pictures]]<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1997|08|15|United States|df=y|1997|08|22|United Kingdom}}\n| runtime        = 96 minutes<ref>{{cite web|title=''EVENT HORIZON'' (18)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/event-horizon-film|publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n| country        = United Kingdom<ref name=\"bfi\">{{cite web|title=Event Horizon (1997)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b7fd8d4ad|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref><br />United States<ref name=\"bfi\"/>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million<ref name=\"numbers\">{{cite web |title= Event Horizon (1997) | url = http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1997/EVENT.php |work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate = 18 August 2011}}</ref> \n| gross          = $26.7 million (US)<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=eventhorizon.htm|title=Event Horizon (1997)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Event Horizon''''' is a 1997 [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[horror film]] directed by [[Paul W. S. Anderson]] and written by [[Philip Eisner]]. It stars [[Laurence Fishburne]], [[Sam Neill]], [[Kathleen Quinlan]] and [[Joely Richardson]]. Set in 2047, it follows a crew of astronauts sent on a rescue mission after a missing spaceship, the ''Event Horizon'', spontaneously appears in orbit around [[Neptune]]. Searching the ship for signs of life, the rescue crew learns that the ''Event Horizon'' was a test bed for an experimental engine that opened a rift in the [[Spacetime|space\u2013time continuum]] and left our universe entirely, allowing a malevolent entity to possess the ship.\n\nThe film had a troubled production history, with filming and editing rushed by [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] when it became clear that ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic]]'' would not meet its projected release date. The original 130-minute cut of the film was heavily edited by demand of the studio, to the consternation of director Paul W. S. Anderson.\n\nUpon release, the film was a commercial and critical failure, grossing $26.7 million on a $60 million production budget. Even so, it began to sell well on [[home video]]; its initial DVD release sold so well that Paramount contacted Anderson shortly after its release to begin working on a restoration of the deleted footage.<ref name=\"Commentary\"/><ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TXL_CM4DXZ8|title=Paul W.S. Anderson Event Horizon Q&A|date=18 December 2011|publisher=[[YouTube]]|first=Jonny|last=Bunning|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">The Making of Event Horizon</ref> However, it turned out that the footage had either been lost or destroyed. In the years since, the film has slowly built a [[cult film|cult following]] and is often referenced and parodied in other works of popular culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/event-horizon/256807/event-horizon-from-doomed-ship-to-cult-gem |title=Event Horizon: From Doomed Ship to Cult Gem|work=Den of Geek!|publisher=[[Dennis Publishing]]|accessdate=2 February 2017|first=Ryan|last=Lambie|date=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 2047, a distress signal is received from the ''Event Horizon'', a [[starship]] that disappeared during its maiden voyage to [[Proxima Centauri]] seven years previously that has mysteriously reappeared in a [[orbital decay|decaying orbit]] around [[Neptune]]. The rescue vessel ''Lewis and Clark'' is dispatched. Its crew \u2013 Captain Miller, second-in-command Lieutenant Starck, pilot Smith, medical technician Peters, engineer Ensign Justin, Doctor D.J. and rescue technician Cooper \u2013 is joined by Dr. William Weir, who designed the ''Event Horizon''. He briefs the crew on the ship's experimental [[Faster-than-light|gravity drive]], which generates an artificial [[black hole]] and uses it to [[Wormhole|bridge]] two points in [[spacetime]], reducing travel time over astronomical distances. The distress signal seems to consist of a series of screams and howls but D.J. believes he can discern the [[Latin]] phrase \"''Liberate me''\" (\"Save me\") being spoken.<!-- per transcript - see discussion at Talk -->\n\nUpon boarding the ''Event Horizon'', the crew finds evidence of a massacre. As they search for survivors, the ship's gravity drive activates, briefly pulling Justin into the resulting portal and causing a shock wave that damages the ''Lewis and Clark'', forcing the entire crew to board the ''Event Horizon''. Justin emerges in a [[catatonia|catatonic state]], terrified by what he saw on the other side. He attempts suicide by decompression, but is saved by Miller, forcing the crew to place him in [[suspended animation|stasis]].\n\nThe team begins to experience apparitions of individuals from their past that only they can see,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Horror in Space: Critical Essays on a Film Subgenre|last=Brittany|first=Michele|publisher=McFarland|year=2017|isbn=978-14766-6405-7|location=Jefferson, North Carolina|pages=3}}</ref> hallucinations corresponding to their fears and regrets: Miller sees Corrick, a subordinate he was forced to abandon to his death, Peters sees her son with his legs covered in bloody lesions and Weir sees an eyeless vision of his late wife, who committed suicide, urging him to join her. The crew soon discover a video log of the ''Event Horizon''{{'}}s crew fornicating and mutilating each other shortly after first engaging the gravity drive. The video log ends with a shot of the ''Event Horizon''{{'}}s captain speaking the complete Latin phrase from the earlier distress call, which D.J. translates \"''Liberate tutemet ex inferis<!-- per transcript - see discussion at Talk -->''\" (\"Save ''yourself'' from hell\").\n\nDeducing that the ship's gravity drive opened a gateway to a hellish dimension outside the [[universe|known universe]], and that the ''Event Horizon'' has somehow attained [[sentience]], Miller decides to destroy the ''Event Horizon'' and orders an evacuation. Peters is lured to her death by a hallucination of her son. Weir, who has gouged his own eyes out and is now possessed by the evil presence, uses an explosive device to destroy the ''Lewis and Clark''. The explosion kills Smith and blasts Cooper off into space. Weir kills D.J. by [[Vivisection|vivisecting]] him and corners Starck on the [[bridge (nautical)|bridge]]. Miller confronts Weir, who overpowers him and initiates a 10-minute countdown until the ''Event Horizon'' will return to the other dimension.\n\nCooper, having used his space suit's oxygen supply to propel himself back to the ship, appears at the bridge window. Weir shoots at him and is blown into space by the ensuing decompression. Miller, Starck, and Cooper survive and manage to seal off the ship's bridge. With their own ship destroyed, Miller plans to split the ''Event Horizon'' in two and use the forward section of the ship as a lifeboat. He is attacked by manifestations of Corrick and a resurrected Weir. Miller fights them off and detonates the explosives, sacrificing himself.\n\nThe gravity drive activates, pulling the ship's stern section into a black hole. Starck and Cooper enter stasis beside a comatose Justin, and wait to be rescued. Seventy-two days later, the wreckage of the ''Event Horizon'' is boarded by a rescue party, who discover the remaining crew still in stasis. Starck sees Weir posing as one of the rescuers and screams in terror; this is revealed to be a [[nightmare]] with Starck waking up moments later.  However, as Cooper and the rescue team comfort the newly-awakened and terrified Starck, the doors unexpectedly close.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]] as Captain Miller, Commanding Officer of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Sam Neill]] as Dr. William 'Billy' Weir, designer of the ''Event Horizon''\n* [[Kathleen Quinlan]] as Peters, Medical Technician of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Joely Richardson]] as Lieutenant Starck, Communications and Executive Officer of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Richard T. Jones]] as Cooper, Rescue Technician of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Jack Noseworthy]] as Ensign Justin, Chief Engineer of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Jason Isaacs]] as D.J., Medical Doctor of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Sean Pertwee]] as Smith 'Smitty', Pilot of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n* [[Peter Marinker]] as Captain John Kilpack, Commanding Officer of the ''Event Horizon''\n* Holley Chant as Claire Weir, Dr. Weir's wife\n* Barclay Wright as Denny Peters, son of Technician Peters\n* [[Noah Huntley]] as Edmund Corrick, Miller's former shipmate from the ''Goliath''\n* [[Robert Jezek]] as Rescue Technician, rescues the survivors of the ''Lewis and Clark''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nAfter ''[[Mortal Kombat (1995 film)|Mortal Kombat]]'' (1995) had become a commercial success in the United States, English director [[Paul W. S. Anderson]] was inundated with screenplay offers, as well as the opportunity to direct the ''Mortal Kombat'' sequel ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]]'' (1997),<ref name=\"fangoria\">{{cite magazine|last=Hughes|first=David|date=August 1997|title=Terrors Beyond the ''Event Horizon''|url=https://archive.org/details/Fangoria_165_1997_Event_Horizon_HQS_c2c/page/n29|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|issue=165|pages=30\u201335|doi=|issn=0164-2111|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> and the upcoming ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]'' (2000).<ref name=\"Commentary\">{{cite AV media | people=[[Paul W. S. Anderson]] (Director), [[Jeremy Bolt]] (Producer) | year=2006 | title=Event Horizon | medium=Audio commentary | publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Anderson turned the offers down in favor of making an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R-rated]] horror film, hoping to shift away from making another [[PG-13]] film.<ref name=\"Commentary\"/> [[Paramount Pictures]] then sent [[Philip Eisner]]'s original script for ''Event Horizon'', which they had been trying to develop with producers [[Lawrence Gordon (producer)|Lawrence Gordon]] and [[Lloyd Levin]].<ref name=\"makingof\">{{cite AV media | people=[[Paul W. S. Anderson]] (Director), [[Jeremy Bolt]] (Producer) | year=2006 | title=The Making of Event Horizon | medium=Documentary | publisher=[[Paramount Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> According to Eisner, he first [[pitch (filmmaking)|pitched]] its concept to Gordon as a \"haunted house story in space\", which the producer thought had the potential to become a motion picture: \"Luckily\", said Eisner, \"he liked the idea enough to trust me to do it.\"<ref name=\"fangoria\"/> Anderson's initial reaction to the script, which involved the cruise ship ''Event Horizon'' experiencing a series of hauntings by \"tentacular\" aliens having crossed the threshold of their planet or \"dimension\", was that it bore striking resemblance to ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]'' (1979), while producer and longtime collaborator [[Jeremy Bolt]] felt it was a \"terrific concept\" but was \"very dense\" in terms of length and the storyline was \"a bit lost.\"<ref name=\"makingof\"/> Anderson disliked directing a mimicry of ''Alien'' so he gave the script a major rewrite. Anderson had in mind a \"classic haunted house movie\", incorporating significant influences to moderately successful horror films such as [[Robert Wise]]'s ''[[The Haunting (1963 film)|The Haunting]]'' (1963) and [[Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' (1980) because they enforce suspense from the unknown, meaning the ghost or creature was hidden from the viewer, and their endings induced ambiguities of perception in the audience.<ref name=\"makingof\"/> Anderson, too, said he was interested in the concept of [[Hell]], as well as the idea of \"the ship itself being possessed rather than going 'Oh, it's an alien consciousness that is doing this,'\" and added these in the script.<ref name=\"makingof\"/>\n\nScreenwriter [[Philip Eisner]] acknowledged ''[[Warhammer 40,000]]'' as a major inspiration for the plot.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=phubar |author-link=Philip Eisner |number=860129292151214082 |date=May 4, 2017 |title=I played the shit out of 40K, so it was definitely an influence, conscious or otherwise.}}</ref> In the fictional setting of ''Warhammer 40,000'', starships travel the galaxy by passing through \"the Warp\", which is a parallel dimension where faster-than-light travel is possible, similar to \"[[hyperspace]]\" in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' setting, but also infested with daemons that are liable to infiltrate the ship and possess the crew. Many fans of ''Warhammer 40,000'' consider ''Event Horizon'' to be an unofficial prequel to the former, when humankind discovers the Warp and learns of its dangers the hard way.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geek.com/tech/is-the-1997-movie-event-horizon-a-secret-warhammer-40k-prequel-1658234/ |title=Is the 1997 movie Event Horizon a secret Warhammer 40k prequel? |author=Ryan Whitwam |date=15 June 2016 |website=Geek.com |access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Editing===\nAs Anderson explains, directors usually have a standard 10-week editing period to produce the first cut of a film, as guaranteed by the [[Directors Guild of America]]. However, due to the short production schedule of the film, the rapidly approaching release date, and the fact that principal photography had not yet finished, Anderson agreed with the Paramount studio to an editing period of six weeks and promised to deliver the film by August 1997, as Paramount wanted to have a hit film before ''[[Titanic (1997 film)|Titanic's]]'' planned September release date. When the main unit wrapped, Anderson was supposed to start editing the film, but he still had to shoot two weeks with the [[second unit]], effectively shortening the time he could spend in post-production to just four weeks. In that short amount of time, only a rough cut of the film could be assembled. Anderson notes that at two hours and 10 minutes, it was overly long, with weak directing and acting that could have used another editing pass, unfinished special effects, and a poor sound mix.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nIn [[test screening]]s, the cut was poorly received. There were complaints about the extreme amount of gore,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> and Anderson and producer [[Jeremy Bolt]] claim members of the test audience fainted during the screening.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> Paramount, which had stopped watching the [[dailies]] before any of the gore was shot and were seeing the completed film for the first time along with the audience, were similarly shocked by how gruesome it was and demanded a shorter runtime with less gore. Anderson believes that while his first cut was justifiably considered too long, Paramount forced him to make a cut that was instead too short, and that the film would benefit by the restoration of around 10 minutes of footage, including some of the deleted gore.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> \n\n===Missing footage===\nAfter the initial [[DVD]] release became a surprise hit, the studio and Anderson became interested in assembling a [[director's cut]], but they quickly discovered that the excised footage had not been carefully stored and much of it had gone missing. The plan to assemble a director's cut was abandoned and instead a special-edition two-DVD set was released, featuring one deleted scene, two extended scenes, and a few shots of deleted material in the included [[making-of]] featurette. The footage is of \"[[Videotape|video]]\" quality.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\nKnown deleted scenes include a meeting scene between Weir and people in charge of the mission in which they discuss ''Event Horizon'', some dialogue of which remained present in the theatrical trailer;<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ocQvTGLuBY8|title=Event Horizon deleted scene|date=8 October 2010|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=TheDronemaster}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pugTKXUUlGk|title=Event Horizon (1997) Trailer|date=13 February 2009|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=HorrorMoviesBlog}}</ref> more backstory for Cooper and Justin, including a stronger explanation for Justin entering the black hole; a deleted backstory of the relationship between Starck and Miller; additional scenes explaining what the gateway to hell/black hole is;<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Anthony C.|last=Ferrante|title=The Cutting Room: Event Horizon|magazine=[[Fangoria]]|issue=170|page=12|accessdate=16 July 2018|url=http://www.oocities.org/hollywood/Cinema/3615/mag/mag3.html |issn=0164-2111}}</ref> Miller finding a tooth floating in ''Event Horizon'';<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> a longer version of the scene in which Peters hallucinates that her son's mangled legs are covered in maggots;<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> a scene in which Weir hallucinates that Justin turns into his wife Claire;<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n4Z6ln27_cE|title=Behind The Scenes \"Event Horizon\" part 4\\9. \u0417\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043d\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u0439\" \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c 4\\9|date=13 May 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=Simbacool69}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5RzccmgGMcs|title=Behind The Scenes \"Event Horizon\" part 7\\9. \u0417\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e \"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043e\u043d\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u0439\" \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c 7\\9|date=13 May 2013|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|author=Simbacool69}}</ref> a bloodier version of Weir's wife Claire's suicide; a longer version of the scene where Miller finds D.J.'s dead body with his guts on the table; and a longer version of the \"Visions From Hell\" scene during Miller's final fight with Weir with more shots of ''Event Horizon'' crew being tortured.{{better source|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe \"bloody orgy\" video was also longer. As Anderson was sometimes too busy filming other scenes, second-unit director Vadim Jean filmed some parts of this scene.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> Real-life amputees were used for special effects scenes in which ''Event Horizon'' crew members were mutilated, and [[pornographic film]] actors were hired to make the sex and rape scenes more realistic and graphic.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/>\n\nThe film's final ending was a combination of two unused alternate endings that were filmed. One did not have a jump scare at the end when the last two survivors are found by another rescue crew and Starck hallucinates that she sees Weir, although there was a similar version of the scene included in this ending where she hears screams of ''Event Horizon'' crew and screams in fear before Cooper wakes her up. This was the original ending of the film included in the shooting script.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsdb.com/scripts/Event-Horizon.html|title=Event Horizon|work=Internet Movie Script Database|accessdate=16 July 2018|first=Philip|last=Eisner}}</ref> The second ending had Miller fighting with the burned man from his visions at the core instead of with Weir, but this was changed due to the negative test screening.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nIn an ''Event Horizon'' Q&A in 2011, Anderson was asked when extra footage will be made available. He responded \"never\", explaining that much of it is gone forever.<ref name=\"youtube.com\"/> However, in a 2012 interview, he announced that producer [[Lloyd Levin]] had found a [[VHS]] tape with his original rough cut. Anderson said that after finishing ''[[Resident Evil: Retribution]]'', he planned to watch it for the first time since assembling the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/paul-w-s-anderson-resident-evil-5-retribution-interview/|title=Paul W.S. Anderson Talks RESIDENT EVIL 5 RETRIBUTION, EVENT HORIZON, DEATH RACE: INFERNO|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex Media]]|first=Steve|last=Weintraub|date=17 July 2012|accessdate=4 August 2015}}</ref> In a January 2017 interview, Anderson reiterated a director's cut will never be released as the footage doesn't exist anymore. Asked about the VHS tape, he said neither he, nor Levin, had watched it yet, as Levin moved to Spain; however, he was still excited about watching it at some point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/2017/jan/25/screen-paul-ws-anderson-puts-end-resident-evil/?page=3|title=Paul W.S. Anderson puts an end to Resident Evil|work=[[San Diego Reader]]|date=25 January 2017|first=Scott|last=Marks|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n[[Michael Kamen]] was hired to compose the score for the film. Director [[Paul W. S. Anderson]], a fan of hybrid genre music, invited the [[electronic dance music]] duo [[Orbital (band)|Orbital]] to collaborate with Kamen and to provide synthesizing sounds for the film's unsettling atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sAImDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Contemporary Film Music: Investigating Cinema Narratives and Composition|last=Coleman|first=Lindsay|last2=Tillman|first2=Joakim|year=2017|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137573759|location=New York}}{{better source|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\nA soundtrack album was released which edited various cues from the score into four tracks of approximately ten minutes.\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released on August 15, 1997 and was a box office failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.everthing.explained.today/Event_Horizon_(film)/|title=Event Horizon|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=January 4, 2020}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>  ''Event Horizon'' cost $60 million and only grossed $26,616,590 in the United States.<ref name=\"numbers\"/><ref name=\"BOM\"/>    The film did well on home DVD video release.\n\n==Reception==\nThe review-aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a rating of 27%, with an average rating of 4.75 out of 10, based on 74 reviews from critics. The website's \"Critics Consensus\" reads, \"Despite a strong opening that promises sci-fi thrills, ''Event Horizon'' quickly devolves into an exercise of style over substance whose flashy effects and gratuitous gore fail to mask its overreliance on horror clich\u00e9s.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/event_horizon/|title=Event Horizon (1997)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a weighted average score of 35 out of 100, based on 20 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/event-horizon|title=Event Horizon Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"D+\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |website= [[CinemaScore]] |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Event Horizon |access-date= 9 November 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= 20 December 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 2 stars out of 4, stating, \"The script creates a sense of foreboding and afterboding, but no actual boding.\"<ref>{{cite web | date = 15 August 1997 | authorlink = Roger Ebert |first=Roger |last=Ebert |publisher=Ebert Digtial LLC |accessdate=16 July 2018 | work = RogerEbert.com | title = Event Horizon (1997) | url = https://rogerebert.com/reviews/event-horizon-1997 }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' critic Stephen Hunter wrote, \"If you want to have that ''Event Horizon'' experience without spending the seven bucks, try this instead: Put a bucket on your head. Have a loved one beat on it vigorously with a wrench for 100 minutes. Same difference, and think of the gas you'll save\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/review97/eventhorizonhunt.htm|title='Event Horizon': Blood Simple|work=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|first=Stephen |last=Hunter|accessdate=16 July 2018|date=15 August 1997}}</ref>\n\nThe film had some early supporters, with ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine awarding ''Event Horizon'' a 3 out of 5 stars rating, reporting: \"That the film never fulfils its promise is down to its over reliance on horror vagaries in a precision-built sci-fi milieu, ultimately leaving too many unanswered queries. A sharper script and a more credible solution could have turned this impressive hokum into a force to be reckoned with\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/review.asp?FID=13951|title=Empire's Event Horizon Movie Review|work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|date=1 January 2000|first=Ian|last=Nathan}}</ref> Additionally, ''[[Total Film]]'' also gave it a score of 3 out of 5 stars, stating that \"Excellent special effects and an ''[[Alien (film)|Alien]]''-esque feel make this supernatural horror film ('''[[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]'' in space,' as most critics have called it, pretty accurately) well worth a look. There are certainly plenty of jumps on offer as a possessed ship torments and tortures any humans it can find. Well worth a look.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/event-horizon-review/|title=Event Horizon review|author=Total Film|date=22 August 1997|work=[[GamesRadar+]]|accessdate=16 July 2018|publisher=Future Publishing}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave it a B-, stating, \"Just when you've written off this deep-space nightmare as a late-summer melange of ''Alien'', ''Fantastic Voyage'', ''The Shining'', and a dozen more forgettable otherworldly thrillers, it unleashes some of the most unsettling horror imagery in years\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/1997/09/05/event-horizon-2/|title=Event Horizon|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Owen|last=Gleiberman|date=5 September 1997|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> whereas the ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine mentioned that \"despite its shortcomings, this is never dull. The movie avoids Alien space monster clich\u00e9s brilliantly and the soundtrack contains more of the 'Boo!' effects than I've heard since ''Halloween''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/film/event-horizon|title=Event Horizon|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]|publisher=Time Out Group|date=|author=NKE|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television series==\nIn August 2019, it was reported that [[Paramount Television]]  and [[Amazon Studios]] were developing a television series based on ''Event Horizon''. Horror filmmaker [[Adam Wingard]] is set to executive produce the series and possibly direct the series. Lawrence Gordon and Lloyd Levin, who produced the original film, are also involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/event-horizon-series-amazon-1203291883/|title='Event Horizon' Series in Development at Amazon (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=Variet Media, LLC|date=5 August 2019|first=Joe|last=Otterson}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1990s|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror|Science fiction}}\n* [[1997 in film]]\n* [[List of American films of 1997]]\n* [[List of horror films of 1997]]\n* [[List of incomplete or partially lost films]]\n* [[List of films featuring space stations]]\n* [[List of science fiction horror films]]\n* [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]]\n* ''[[Satan's Triangle]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Event Horizon}}\n* {{IMDb title|0119081|Event Horizon}}\n* {{Amg title|158616|Event Horizon}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes}} \n* {{Mojo title}}\n\n{{Paul W. S. Anderson}}\n\n[[Category:1997 films]]\n[[Category:1997 horror films]]\n[[Category:1990s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Kamen]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Orbital (band)]]\n[[Category:Films about astronauts]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul W. S. Anderson]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2047]]\n[[Category:Films set in the future]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Wormholes in fiction]]\n[[Category:Neptune in film]]\n[[Category:Films about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Proxima Centauri in fiction]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "2601:19b:c701:9c10:4c9f:76e7:d1de:d1a1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Italicized qoutes and capitalized titles)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Event_Horizon_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Frank S. Black", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. He was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine|Limington, York County, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black. He graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, and taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]], from which he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875. While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal''. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and ardent follower of [[James G. Blaine]], also from Maine, Black changed the political stance of the paper while the Democratic owner was out of town, but was promptly dismissed upon the latter's return. He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], and worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and the ''Troy Times''. While working as a night reporter, he was a clerk in the Troy post office and [[reading law|studied law]] with the firm of Robertson & Foster. Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president. In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]]. In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican. Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted. McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as a result of the Ross murder case, in November 1894, Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]]. He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor. During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the Committee on Private Land Claims. He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898. A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.\n\nLater in his term, state officials were accused of squandering more than a million dollars on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs. Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]].<ref>Edmond Morris, ''The Rise of Theodore Roosevelt '' (1979) p 666</ref> Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]]. In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.\n\n==Later life==\nAfterwards he resumed his law practice. Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case. After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial. The case was the source of the well-known \"Molineux rule\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office. In 1904, he was a candidate for the Republican nomination for [[United States Senator]], but lost to incumbent [[Chauncey Depew]], who went on to win reelection. He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term. In 1908, Black supported William Howard Taft for president.\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/22/100612163.pdf \"Ex-Gov Black Dies at His Troy Home\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'' March 22, 1913</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47101597/frank-s-black-dies-of-disease-of-heart/ |title=Frank S. Black Dies of Disease of Heart |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Daily Post]] |agency=Associated Press |location=Troy, New York |page=1 |date=1913-03-22 |access-date=2020-03-21 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his farm outside [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school in Provincetown. They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** [[s:Harper's Weekly Editorials by Carl Schurz/Governor Black's Balance-Sheet|Governor Black's Balance-Sheet]]\n** [[s:Harper's Weekly Editorials by Carl Schurz/Our New Civil Service Law|Our New Civil Service Law]]\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]] |\n  after=[[Aaron V. S. Cochrane]] |\n  years=1895\u20131897\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Governor of New York]] | before = [[Levi P. Morton]] | after = [[Theodore Roosevelt]] | years = 1897\u20131898}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Frank Swett}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Limington, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:New York State College of Forestry]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician and governor}}\n{{redirect|Governor Black|the short-serving Governor of Kentucky|James D. Black}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Governor\n|name          = Frank Swett Black\n|image         = Frank S Black.jpg\n|order         = 32nd\n|office        = Governor of New York\n|term_start    = January 1, 1897\n|term_end      = December 31, 1898\n|lieutenant    = [[Timothy L. Woodruff]]\n|predecessor   = [[Levi P. Morton]]\n|successor     = [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|state2        =  [[New York (state)|New York]]\n|district2     =  {{ushr|New York|19|19th}}\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1895\n|term_end2     = January 7, 1897\n|predecessor2  = [[Charles D. Haines]]\n|successor2    = [[Aaron Van Schaick Cochrane]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|birth_place   = near [[Limington, Maine]], U.S. \n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1913|3|22|1853|3|8|mf=y}}\n|death_place   = [[Troy, New York]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Frank S. Black Farm, [[Freedom, New Hampshire]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education     = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|occupation    = Newspaper editor<br/>Attorney\n}}\n\n'''Frank Swett Black''' (March 8, 1853{{spnd}}March 22, 1913) was an American newspaper editor, lawyer and politician. He was a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1895 to 1897, and the [[List of Governors of New York|32nd Governor of New York]] from 1897 to 1898.\n\n==Early life==\nBlack was born near [[Limington, Maine|Limington, York County, Maine]] on March 8, 1853, one of eleven children born to farmer Jacob Black and Charlotte (Butters) Black. He graduated from [[Lebanon, Maine|Lebanon]] Academy in 1871, and taught school while attending [[Dartmouth College]], from which he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1875. While in college, Black joined the [[Delta Kappa Epsilon]] fraternity.\n\n==Start of career==\nAfter completing his education, Black moved to [[Johnstown (city), New York|Johnstown, New York]] to become editor of the ''Johnstown Journal''. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] and ardent follower of [[James G. Blaine]], also from Maine, Black changed the political stance of the paper while the Democratic owner was out of town, but was promptly dismissed upon the latter's return. He then moved to [[Troy, New York]], and worked for the ''Troy Whig'' and the ''Troy Times''. While working as a night reporter, he was a clerk in the Troy post office and [[reading law|studied law]] with the firm of Robertson & Foster. Black attained [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admission to the bar]] in 1879 and began to practice in Troy.\n\nIn 1888, Black campaigned for [[Benjamin Harrison]] for president. In 1892, he campaigned for Harrison's reelection, but Harrison was defeated by former President [[Grover Cleveland]]. In March 1894, an election day dispute between Republicans and Democrats in Troy culminated with the [[murder of Robert Ross]], a Republican. Black assisted in the prosecution of the defendants, Democrats Bartholomew \"Bat\" Shea and John McGough, who were convicted. McGough was sentenced to 20 years in prison, and Shea was executed.\n\n==U.S. House==\nLargely as a result of the Ross murder case, in November 1894, Black was elected to the [[54th United States Congress]], representing [[New York's 19th congressional district]]. He served from March 4, 1895 to January 7, 1897, when he resigned because he had been elected governor. During his House term, Black was a member of the Committee on Pacific Railroads and the Committee on Private Land Claims. He was a delegate to the [[1896 Republican National Convention]] and supported [[William McKinley]] for president.\n\n==Governor==\nBlack was elected governor [[New York state election, 1896|in 1896]] and served from January 1, 1897 to December 31, 1898. A highlight of his governorship was completion of construction on the [[New York State Capitol]], which had fallen far behind schedule and had been plagued with cost overruns.\n\nLater in his term, state officials were accused of squandering more than a million dollars on a project to expand the [[Erie Canal]], which had come to be regarded as a [[boondoggle]] because of delays and excessive costs. Black's chances for reelection were jeopardized, so Republicans replaced him as their 1898 gubernatorial nominee with [[Theodore Roosevelt]], who had recently attained hero status in Cuba during the [[Spanish-American War]].<ref>Edmond Morris, ''The Rise of Theodore Roosevelt '' (1979) p 666</ref> Roosevelt won the November general election by narrowly defeating Democratic nominee [[Augustus Van Wyck]]. In 1899, an investigating commission appointed by Black, in conjunction with two special counsels appointed by Roosevelt, exonerated those involved of criminal wrongdoing.\n\n==Later life==\nAfterwards he resumed his law practice. Among the noteworthy cases in which he was involved, Black took part in the defense of Roland B. Molineaux in the famed ''[[People v. Molineux]]'' case. After Molineaux was convicted of murder, the conviction was overturned and he won an acquittal at retrial. The case was the source of the well-known \"Molineux rule\" which limits the ability of prosecutors to use prior crimes as proof that a defendant committed the crime with which he is charged. Black also took part in the defense of [[Caleb Powers]] for the assassination of Kentucky governor [[William Goebel]].\n\nBlack maintained his interest in politics even after leaving office. He was a delegate to the [[1904 Republican National Convention]], and nominated President [[Theodore Roosevelt]] for election to a full term.\n\n==Death and burial==\nBlack died from heart disease at his home in Troy on March 22, 1913.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/03/22/100612163.pdf \"Ex-Gov Black Dies at His Troy Home\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'' March 22, 1913</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47101597/frank-s-black-dies-of-disease-of-heart/ |title=Frank S. Black Dies of Disease of Heart |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Daily Post]] |agency=Associated Press |location=Troy, New York |page=1 |date=1913-03-22 |access-date=2020-03-21 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> He was cremated and his ashes were buried at his farm outside [[Freedom, New Hampshire]].\n\n==Family==\nIn 1879, Black married Lois B. Hamlin (1858-1931) of [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]], whom he had met while teaching school in Provincetown. They were the parents of a son, Arthur (1880-1953).\n\n==Honors==\nIn 1898, Black received the [[honorary degree]] of [[Legum Doctor|LL.D.]] from Dartmouth College.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CongBio|B000496}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wikisource-inline|list=\n** [[s:Harper's Weekly Editorials by Carl Schurz/Governor Black's Balance-Sheet|Governor Black's Balance-Sheet]]\n** [[s:Harper's Weekly Editorials by Carl Schurz/Our New Civil Service Law|Our New Civil Service Law]]\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box |\n  state=New York |\n  district=19 |\n  before=[[Charles Delemere Haines|Charles D. Haines]] |\n  after=[[Aaron V. S. Cochrane]] |\n  years=1895\u20131897\n}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title = [[Governor of New York]] | before = [[Levi P. Morton]] | after = [[Theodore Roosevelt]] | years = 1897\u20131898}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of New York}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Black, Frank Swett}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Governors of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Limington, Maine]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Troy, New York]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:19th-century American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:New York State College of Forestry]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Billmckern", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_S._Black"}
{"title_page": "Chagrin Falls (waterfall)", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Places|date=January 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2019}}\n{{Underlinked|date=November 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Chagrin Falls\n|settlement_type          = [[Landmark]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 5.54\n|area_land_km2            = 5.39\n|area_water_km2           = 0.16\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 2.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 2.08\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.06\n}}\nThe '''Chagrin Falls''' waterfalls are [[waterfall]]s spouting off of the [[Chagrin River]] in the center of the village of [[Chagrin Falls, Ohio]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://gowaterfalling.com/waterfalls/chagrin.shtml|title=Chagrin Falls|website=gowaterfalling.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> At the waterfall base, a viewing area is available. The falls were one of the largest industrial centers in the 1800s and are responsible for the growth of the village around them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chagrinhistorical.org/history/|title=History|date=2017-09-07|work=Chagrin Falls Historical Society|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Chagrin Falls originally got their name from a French trader named Francois Seguin, who traded with [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] in the early 1700s. The river later adopted the name \"Chagrin\".<ref name=\":0\" /> At one point the Chagrin Falls was the industrial center of [[Northeast Ohio]] and powered 9 different mills at their peak.<ref name=\":0\"/>  The first settlers arrived in 1833 and they had previously been from New England.  With the profits they made from their mill work on the falls, they began to build their homes around the river and created the now current day Chagrin Falls village.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chagrinhistorical.org/history/|title=History|date=2017-09-07|work=Chagrin Falls Historical Society|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Chagrin river flows through the center of Chagrin Falls Village. The falls reach a height of 20 feet and a crest of 60 feet.<ref name=\":0\" /> The water at the bottom of the falls ranges from 2\u201315 feet.\n\n== Wildlife ==\nThe waterfalls and their surrounding are provided habitats for multiple types of Northeastern Ohio's native animals.  Some of these animals include [[Salamander|salamanders]], [[Squirrel|squirrels]], [[Groundhog|groundhogs]], [[coyote]], and other small animals. There is also a large fish population due to the location of the river.  Some of the species include [[Western_blacknose_dace|Western Blacknose Dace]], [[Semotilus|Creek Chub]], [[Bluegill|Bluegill Sunfish]], [[Largemouth_bass|Largemouth Bass]], [[Yellow_bullhead|Yellow Bullhead]].<ref>\u201cExporting PDF Content.\u201d ''Adobe\u00ae Acrobat\u00ae X PDF Bible'', 2011, pp. 253\u2013266., doi:10.1002/9781118255728.ch10.</ref>\n\n== Notable Events ==\n\n=== Blossom Time Festival ===\nOn [[Memorial Day]] weekend every year, the town holds a [http://www.cvjc.org/blossom-time-schedule Blossom time festival].  The festival features live music, carnival rides, games and a race.\n\n=== New Years Eve ===\nResidents gather in the park to watch a giant [[popcorn]] ball drop at midnight.  The popcorn ball is provided by the local [[Chagrin_Falls_Popcorn_Shop|Popcorn Shop]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|41.43124|-81.39233|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-OH|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|Places|date=January 2019}}\n{{primary sources|date=January 2019}}\n{{Underlinked|date=November 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Chagrin Falls\n|settlement_type          = [[Landmark]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 5.54\n|area_land_km2            = 5.39\n|area_water_km2           = 0.16\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 2.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 2.08\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.06\n}}\nThe '''Chagrin Falls''' waterfalls are [[waterfall]]s spouting off of the [[Chagrin_River|Chagrin river]] in the center of the village of [[Chagrin Falls, Ohio]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://gowaterfalling.com/waterfalls/chagrin.shtml|title=Chagrin Falls|website=gowaterfalling.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> At the waterfall base a viewing area is available. The falls were one of the largest industrial centers in the 1800s and are responsible for the growth of the village around them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chagrinhistorical.org/history/|title=History|date=2017-09-07|work=Chagrin Falls Historical Society|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Chagrin Falls originally got their name from a French trader named Francois Seguin, who traded with [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] in the early 1700s. The river later adopted the name \"Chagrin\".<ref name=\":0\" /> At one point the Chagrin Falls were the industrial center of [[Northeast Ohio]] and powered 9 different mills at their peak.<ref name=\":0\"/>  The first settlers arrived in 1833 and they had previously been from New England.  With the profits they made from their mill work on the falls, they began to build their homes around the river and created the now current day Chagrin Falls village.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chagrinhistorical.org/history/|title=History|date=2017-09-07|work=Chagrin Falls Historical Society|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe Chagrin river flows through the center of Chagrin Falls village. The falls reach a height of 20 feet and a crest of 60 feet.<ref name=\":0\" /> The water at the bottom of the falls ranges from 2\u201315 feet.\n\n== Wildlife ==\nThe waterfalls and their surrounding are provide habitats for multiple types of Northeastern Ohio's native animals.  Some of these animals include [[Salamander|salamanders]], [[Squirrel|squirrels]], [[Groundhog|groundhogs]], [[coyote]], and other small animals. There is also a large fish population due to the location of the river.  Some of the species include [[Western_blacknose_dace|Western Blacknose Dace]], [[Semotilus|Creek Chub]], [[Bluegill|Bluegill Sunfish]], [[Largemouth_bass|Largemouth Bass]], [[Yellow_bullhead|Yellow Bullhead]].<ref>\u201cExporting PDF Content.\u201d ''Adobe\u00ae Acrobat\u00ae X PDF Bible'', 2011, pp. 253\u2013266., doi:10.1002/9781118255728.ch10.</ref>\n\n== Notable Events ==\n\n=== Blossom Time Festival ===\nOn [[Memorial Day]] weekend every year, the town holds a [http://www.cvjc.org/blossom-time-schedule Blossom time festival].  The festival features live music, carnival rides, games and a race.\n\n=== New Years Eve ===\nResidents gather in the park to watch a giant [[popcorn]] ball drop at midnight.  The popcorn ball is provided by the local [[Chagrin_Falls_Popcorn_Shop|Popcorn Shop]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|41.43124|-81.39233|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-OH|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Landforms of Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Chirag.Saluja", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor punctuation & grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chagrin_Falls_(waterfall)"}
{"title_page": "Komes", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2015}}\n'''Komes''' (abbreviated '''K.''' before a surname), also \u017cupan in [[Polish language|Polish]], a title developed from the [[Latin]] ''[[comes]]'' in [[History of Poland (966\u20131385)|medieval Poland]] and was used for [[dignitary]] in the period of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] for administrative and military district commanders. The title faded from use before the establishment of the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] to be replaced by [[Castellan|kasztelan]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Baron]]\n* [[Count]]\n* [[Polish nobility]]\n\n{{Poland-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Polish titles]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=December 2015}}\n'''Komes''' (abbreviated ''K.'' before a surname), also ''\u017cupan'' in Polish - A title developed from the Latin [[comes]] in [[History of Poland (966\u20131385)|medieval Poland]] and was used for [[dignitary]] in the period of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] for administrative and military district commanders. The title faded from use before the establishment of the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] to be replaced by [[Castellan|kasztelan]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Baron]]\n* [[Count]]\n* [[Polish nobility]]\n\n[[Category:Polish titles]]\n\n\n{{Poland-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Komes"}
{"title_page": "Bratono\u017ei\u0107i", "text_new": "[[File:Kartakuca.jpg|thumb|300px|Map of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i (in purple) in the late 19th century]]\n\n'''Bratono\u017ei\u0107i''' ([[Serbo-Croatian|Montenegrin]]:''\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438'', {{IPA-sh|br\u00e4to\u031eno\u031e\u0292it\u0361\u0255i|pron}}) is a small [[Tribes of Montenegro|historical tribe]] (''pleme'') in the [[Brda, Montenegro|Brda region]] of [[Montenegro]]. It appeared during the Ottoman period and was a captaincy of the [[Principality of Montenegro]] in the 19th century. Today, it forms part of northeastern [[Podgorica Municipality]]. In Montenegro, the majority of people who trace their origin in Bratono\u017ei\u0107i identify as Christian Orthodox [[Montenegrins]] and a part identify as Christian Orthodox [[Serbs of Montenegro|Serbs]]. Brotherhoods (''bratstvo'') from the historical tribe that settled in [[Bijelo Polje Municipality|Bijelo Polje]] and became Muslims in the Ottoman period identify as [[Bosniaks]]. In the 18th century, many families from the region settled in western Serbia. In [[Kosovo]], a part of the Serbs of western Kosovo come from Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. The best known descendant of the Bratono\u017ei\u0107i tribe is Prince [[Milo\u0161 Obrenovi\u0107 I of Serbia]], founder of the [[House of Obrenovi\u0107]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Bratono\u017ei\u0107i tribal region is rugged, hilly area at an altitude which ranges from 400 to 450m. It is situated between the [[Mora\u010da river]], [[Mala Rijeka]] and [[Crna Planina]]; it borders the tribes of [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] to the north, [[Rov\u010dani]] to the northwest, [[Ku\u010di]] to the east and south, and [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]] to the west. The region ends after Mala Rijeka pours into the Mora\u010da, near the settlement of Mrke, about 13km to the northeast of Podgorica. With the exception of Mrke, most of the other settlements (Klopot, Pelev Brijeg, Duga) of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are semi-deserted or completely abandoned as their inhabitants moved to Podgorica. As of 2011, Mrke had 207 residents. 118 identify as Montenegrins, 60 as Serbs, 25 chose not to declare any ethnicity.<ref name=\"monstat\">{{cite web |title=Census 2011 data - Montenegro |url=https://www.monstat.org/eng/page.php?id=395&pageid=57|website=Monstat |publisher=Statistical Office of Montenegro |accessdate=15 February 2020 |ref=monstat}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn a Venetian document dating to 1455, ''Banovichi'' is mentioned as one of the villages of Upper Zeta; this may be an early reference to Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. The first direct reference to the settlements that comprise Bratono\u017ei\u0107i today is found in the supplementary defter of the [[sanjak of Scutari]] in 1497. They hadn't formed as a single community at that time.{{sfn|Strugar|1987|p=135}}\n\nBratono\u017ei\u0107i is a tribe (''pleme'') of several patrilineal ancestries which formed it over time since the later 15th century.  The name of the tribe comes from a ''Brato'', father of ''Nika'' and ancestor of many of the brotherhoods of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. He lived 14 generations before the time of the recording of the story around 1900. A ''Brato, son of Nika'' who lived with his brother ''Pali'' in the small hamlet of Moraci\u0107a in 1497 may be a reference to this figure. The defter mentions that previously they lived in Hrasni\u0107a near [[Podgorica]].{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=422}} \n\nTwo other communities that lived in the same area were the Albanian Catholic [[Bukumiri]]{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=427}} and the Lutovci, who may have come from the [[Pirot District|Pirot]] region in the eastern Balkans or from [[Pult|Pilot]] in northern Albania. Their origin is debated because no collective memory of their history has been retained except for a toponym which may be interpreted to refer to ''Pirot'' in eastern Serbia or ''Pilot'' in northern Albania. Their first historical ancestor in Bratono\u017ei\u0107i is a ''captain Gojko''. Archival records show that the Lutovci lived in 27 households of Luskozupa in 1497 in the [[nahiye]] of Piperi, which included Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and the [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]] tribe.{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=418}} Over the years, a few families from neighbouring tribes like Ku\u010di, Bjelopavli\u0107i and Piperi also settled Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and became part of the community. Bratono\u017ei\u0107i was an area of language contact between Slavic and Albanian as well as religious contact between Slavic Orthodoxy and Catholicism. [[Rufim Njegu\u0161]] in the first half of the 17th century is credited with converting the Bratono\u017ei\u0107i back to Orthodoxy from Catholicsm as well as making them take an oath that intermarriage with Catholic Albanians would take place only with women.<ref name=\"Pavlo25\">{{harvnb|Pavlovi\u0107|2019|p=25}}</ref> This measure would prevent any further reconversions to Catholicism. The events of the conversion of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are regarded as an important step for the reinforcement of what they termed as [[Serbdom]] (''Srbstvo'') and Orthodoxy in Montenegro by 19th century Serbian historiography.<ref name=\"Pavlo25\"/>\n\nThe tribe was often in conflict with the Ku\u010di over grazing lands.{{when|date=December 2014}}<ref>Vukovi\u0107 1996, p. 213 {{quote|\u0417\u0430 \u0442\u0443 \u0440\u0438\u0458\u0435\u0447 \u0411\u0443\u0440\u043e \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0443\u0448\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0411\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u045b\u0430. \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 \u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u0441\u0435, \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u045b\u0435- \u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0435 \u0443\u0437 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e- \u043d\u043e\u0448\u043a\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u041f\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u0448\u0430 \u0438 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0443 \u0438\u043c 16 \u0433\u043b\u0430- \u0432\u0430, \u0430 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0441 \u043e\u0431\u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430 ...}}</ref> Bratono\u017ei\u0107i often attacked Rovca, who were always defended by the Mora\u010dani.<ref name=\"\u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u04391998\">{{cite book|author=\u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0410\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439|title=\u0415\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u0435 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXBpAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=\u0426\u0438\u0434|quote=\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0430, \u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0443 \u0441\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e] \u043d\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0459\u0438 \u0448\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u0428\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435 \u0412\u0430\u0430^\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u0441\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u042c\u0435 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u043e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0431\u0440\u0437\u043e \u043d\u0430\u043c\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0438 \u043e\u0458\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0434\u0430 \u0438\u043c \u043d\u0438 \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 ...}}</ref> They also often fought with the Vasojevi\u0107i.<ref name=\"\u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u04391998\"/>\n\nVenetian public servant [[Mariano Bolizza]]'s 1614 report that the villages of Ku\u010di, Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and part of [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] were under the soldiers of [[Medun]], the spahee, but the commander was not named; and the highlanders would pay the Ottoman officials a portion of their income.<ref>Elsie, p. 152</ref> The report registered the ''Bratanosich'' as a Serb, Orthodox village with 87 houses, and 260 men in arms commanded by Stanoje Radonjin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/en/texts1000-1799/AH1614.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213020432/http://www.albanianhistory.net/en/texts1000-1799/AH1614.html |archive-date=2014-12-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1658, the seven tribes of Ku\u010di, [[Vasojevi\u0107i]], Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]], [[Klimenti]], [[Hoti (tribe)|Hoti]] and [[Gruda (tribe)|Gruda]] allied themselves with the [[Republic of Venice]], establishing the so-called \"Seven-fold barjak\" or \"alaj-barjak\", against the Ottomans.<ref name=MZ>{{cite book|title=Mitolo\u0161ki zbornik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rvUSAQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Centar za mitolo\u0161ki studije Srbije|pages=24, 41\u201345}}</ref> In 1689, an uprising broke out in Piperi, Rovca, [[Bjelopavli\u0107i (tribe)|Bjelopavli\u0107i]], Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, Ku\u010di and Vasojevi\u0107i, while at the same time an uprising broke out in [[Prizren]], [[Pe\u0107]], [[Pri\u0161tina]] and [[Skopje]], and then in [[Kratovo, North Macedonia|Kratovo]] and [[Kriva Palanka]] in October ([[Karposh's Rebellion]]).<ref name=\"armije1968\">{{cite book|author=Belgrade (Serbia). Vojni muzej Jugoslovenske narodne armije|title=Fourteen centuries of struggle for freedom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2m8MAQAAMAAJ|year=1968|publisher=The Military Museum|page=xxviii}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Velika attacks (1879)]], the battalions of the Mora\u010dani and Bratono\u017ei\u0107i fought off the Albanians.<ref name=DVA>{{cite book|title=Dva Petrovi\u0107a Njego\u0161a: Vladika Danilo Petrovi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nH4-AQAAMAAJ|year=1896|publisher=\u0160tamparija Petra \u0106ur\u010di\u0107a|quote=(23) \u043e\u043a\u0442. \u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0420\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0443 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0438\u043c\u0430. \u041a\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0458 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u0434\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u045b\u0438, \u043d\u0430\u0458\u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435. \u041e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0431\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u045a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e \u0445\u0438\u0459\u0430\u0434\u0430. \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435 22. \u043d\u043e\u0432. (4. \u0434\u0435\u043a) \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0443 \u043e\u0434 300 \u0459\u0443\u0434\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435. \u0422\u0443 \u0441\u0430\u0434 \u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0443 \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0443 4\u20145 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0459\u0443\u043d\u0430. \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442o\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0441 \u0458\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u0438\u0445. \u0441\u0435\u045b\u0438, \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0442\u043e \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0443 \u043b\u0435\u0452\u0430. \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0438\u0445. \u0432\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0448\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0430. \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431\u0435 \u0434\u043e 1000. \u041f\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0438\u043c\u0430\u0448\u0435 85 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 100 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445, \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0448\u0435 100 \u043a\u043e\u045a\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0458\u0430. \u041c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043c\u0430. \u041d\u0438 \u043e\u0432\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0438\u043c \u0443 \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443. \u0422\u0440\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0434\u0430\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0430 \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e 10.000 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 3000 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0435 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043f \u0402\u043e\u043a\u043e. \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0434 9 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043e \u043c\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430. \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u0438\u043c\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 1400, \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 36 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 70 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0418 \u043e\u0432\u0434\u0435 \u0458\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e, \u0434\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043c\u0430. \u0422\u0443 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442o\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438, \u0412\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u041d\u0438\u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438. 30. \u0458\u0443\u043d. (12. \u0458\u0443\u043b.) 1880 \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0443 \u0448\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0443 \u043d\u0430 ...}}</ref> At the subsequent [[Battle of Nov\u0161i\u0107e]], the battalions of [[Ku\u010di]], [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] and Bratono\u017ei\u0107i fought the Albanian irregulars under the command of [[Ali Pasha of Gusinje]], and were defeated. Soon after [[Battle of Nov\u0161i\u0107e]] in the same area, the [[Battle of Murino]] broke out in which Ottomans with Albanian irregulars attacked again less numerous forces of [[Principality of Montenegro]] and were heavily defeated by battalions of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] and [[Mora\u010dani]].<ref name=DVA/><ref>{{cite book|author=King Nikola I|title=Cjelokupna djela|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CggYAAAAMAAJ|year=1969|page=567|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Istorijski institut u Titogradu|title=Istorijski zapisi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zD1pAAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=Istorijski institut u Titogradu|page=66|ref=harv}}</ref> At the beginning of the 20th century, the region had ca. 400 houses.\n\n==Brotherhoods and families==\nAll brotherhoods of the tribe have as ''[[Slava]]'' (patron saints) [[Saint Nicholas]] (''Sveti Nikola'') and Saint John (''Sveti Jovan).\nThe families of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are: Avramovi\u0107, Bajovi\u0107, Baljevi\u0107, Balevi\u0107, Bali\u010devi\u0107, Barjaktarovi\u0107, Bar\u017ei\u0107, Biljuri\u0107, Bismiljak, Bo\u0161kovi\u0107, Brankovi\u0107, Butri\u0107, Velji\u0107, Veljovi\u0107, Velimirovi\u0107, Veskovi\u0107, Vidi\u0107, Vujovi\u0107, Vujoti\u0107, Vukajlovi\u0107, Vukovi\u0107, Vukorepovi\u0107, Vuli\u0107, Vu\u010deli\u0107, Vu\u010dini\u0107, Gari\u0107, Gili\u0107, Gogi\u0107, Gruji\u0107, Gudovi\u0107, Darmanovi\u0107, Dmitrovi\u0107, Doki\u0107, \u0110elevi\u0107,\u0110uki\u0107,\u0110urdjevi\u0107, \u0110uri\u0107, \u017divkovi\u0107, \u017dmiki\u0107, Ili\u0107, Jankovi\u0107, Jelavi\u0107, Jovanovi\u0107, Jovovi\u0107, Kalu\u0111erovi\u0107, Keljanovi\u0107, Kekovi\u0107, Kora\u0107, Krkeli\u0107, Lajkovi\u010d, Lainovi\u0107, Lalovi\u0107, La\u0161evi\u0107, Likovi\u0107, Luki\u0107, Lutovac, Ljajinovi\u0107, Ljajkovic, Ljaljovi\u0107, Ljakovi\u0107, Lja\u0161ovi\u0107, Malevi\u0107, Marni\u0107, Macura, Mijailovi\u0107, Miajlovi\u0107, Milovanovi\u0107, Mirkovi\u0107, Muratovi\u0107, Novovi\u0107, Obrenovi\u0107, Pavi\u0107evi\u0107, Pavli\u010di\u0107, Peju\u0161kovi\u0107, Perovi\u0107, Pra\u0161\u010devi\u0107, Prelev\u010danin, Premovi\u0107, Progonovi\u0107i, Radojevi\u0107, Radosevi\u0107, Radunovi\u0107, Raketi\u0107, Raki\u0107, Ratkovi\u0107, Sekulovi\u0107, Stani\u0161i\u0107, Stankovi\u0107, Strahinji\u0107, Toljevi\u0107, Todorovii\u0107, Toma\u0161evii\u0107, To\u0161kovi\u0107, Trimojevi\u0107, \u0106ekli\u0107, \u010cetkovic, Ugri\u010di\u0107, Femiji\u0107, Cari\u010di\u0107, Cmiljani\u0107, \u010ca\u0111enovi\u0107, \u010cubranovi\u0107, \u0160\u0107epan\u010devi\u0107, \u0160ajinovi\u0107, \u0160akovi\u0107, \u0160o\u0161ki\u0107. The Muslim Bratono\u017ei\u0107i of [[Bijelo Polje]] include Kora\u0107i, Ljaljevi\u0107i, Polumente, Uremovi\u0107i, Huremovi\u0107i.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Milo\u0161 Obrenovi\u0107 I of Serbia]]{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=45}}\n*[[Uro\u0161 To\u0161kovi\u0107]], painter<ref>{{cite web|title=TO\u0160KOVI\u0106|url=http://montenegrina.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/toskovic-low-res.pdf|website=montenegrina.net|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Ni\u0161a Savelji\u0107]], by paternal descent\n*[[Esteban Saveljich]], by paternal descent\n*[[Nemanja Be\u0161ovi\u0107]]\n*[[Milorad Vu\u010deli\u0107]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last1=Banac |first1=Ivo |title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics |date=1988 |publisher=Cornell University Press |isbn=0801494931 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA438|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Erdeljanovi\u0107|first=Jovan|authorlink=Jovan Erdeljanovi\u0107|title=Ku\u010di, Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, Piperi|year=1907}}\n**{{cite book|last=Erdeljanovi\u0107|first=Jovan|title=Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, pleme u Crnogorskim brdima|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwlZnQEACAAJ|year=1907}}\n*{{cite book|author=Novo Vukovi\u0107|title=Knji\u017eevnost Crne Gore od XII do XIX vijeka: Primeri \u010dojstva i juna\u0161tva|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5TlAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Obod}}\n*{{cite book|author=Miomir Da\u0161i\u0107|title=Vasojevi\u0107i: od pomena do 1860. godine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Km9MAQAAIAAJ|year=1986|publisher=Narodna knjiga}}\n*{{cite book|author=Mirko S. Radoi\u010di\u0107|title=Hercegovina i Crna Gora 1875-1878|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V14xAQAAIAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Savez udru\u017eenja boraca NOR-a, Op\u0161tinski odbor}}\n*{{cite book|author=Milo Markovi\u0107|title=Bratono\u017ei\u0107i kroz istoriju|year=2014}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pavlovi\u0107|first=Aleksandar|chapter=\"Forging the enemy: the transformation of common Serbian-Albanian traits into enmity and political hostility\"|editor1-last=Pavlovi\u0107|editor1-first=Aleksandar|editor2-last=Dra\u0161ko|editor2-first=Gazela Pudar|editor3-last=Halili|editor3-first=Rigels|title=Rethinking Serbian-Albanian Relations: Figuring out the Enemy|year=2019|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351273145|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?redir_esc=y&id=YCCeDwAAQBAJ&q=Old+Serbia#v=snippet&q=Old%20Serbia&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Pulaha |first1=Selami |title=Defter i Sanxhakut t\u00eb Shkodr\u00ebs 1485 |date=1974 |publisher=Academy of Sciences of Albania |url=https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B3ma9plMXxAEZi1PZTVXMXV1NFE/edit |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Vlado Strugar|title=Pro\u0161lost Crne Gore kao predmet nau\u010dnog istra\u017eivanja i obrade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=maYMAAAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Crnogorska akademija nauka i umjetnosti |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|title=Pleme Bratono\u017ei\u0107i (\u041f\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438)|date=June 13, 2013|publisher=Poreklo|url=http://www.poreklo.rs/2013/06/13/pleme-bratono%C5%BEi%C4%87i/}}\n*{{cite web|author=Marko Miljanov|title=Ne\u0161to o Bratono\u017ei\u0107ima|publisher=Rastko|url=http://www.rastko.rs/rastko-cg/umjetnost/marko_miljanov-bratonozici.html}}\n\n{{Regions in Montenegro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratonozici}}\n[[Category:Historical regions in Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Montenegro]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kartakuca.jpg|thumb|300px|Map of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i (in purple) in the late 19th century]]\n\n'''Bratono\u017ei\u0107i''' ([[Serbo-Croatian|Montenegrin]]:''\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438'', {{IPA-sh|br\u00e4to\u031eno\u031e\u0292it\u0361\u0255i|pron}}) is a small [[Tribes of Montenegro|historical tribe]] (''pleme'') in the [[Brda, Montenegro|Brda region]] of [[Montenegro]]. It appeared during the Ottoman period and was a captaincy of the [[Principality of Montenegro]] in the 19th century. Today, it forms part of northeastern [[Podgorica Municipality]]. In Montenegro, the majority of people who trace their origin in Bratono\u017ei\u0107i identify as Christian Orthodox [[Montenegrins]] and a part identify as Christian Orthodox [[Serbs of Montenegro|Serbs]]. Brotherhoods (''bratstvo'') from the historical tribe that settled in [[Bijelo Polje Municipality|Bijelo Polje]] and became Muslims in the Ottoman period identify as [[Bosniaks]]. In the 18th century, many families from the region settled in western Serbia. In [[Kosovo]], a part of the Serbs of western Kosovo come from Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. The best known descendant of the Bratono\u017ei\u0107i tribe is Prince [[Milo\u0161 Obrenovi\u0107 I of Serbia]], founder of the [[House of Obrenovi\u0107]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Bratono\u017ei\u0107i tribal region is rugged, hilly area at an altitude which ranges from 400 to 450m. It is situated between the [[Mora\u010da river]], [[Mala Rijeka]] and [[Crna Planina]]; it borders the tribes of [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] to the north, [[Rov\u010dani]] to the northwest, [[Ku\u010di]] to the east and south, and [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]] to the west. The region ends after Mala Rijeka pours into the Mora\u010da, near the settlement of Mrke, about 13km to the northeast of Podgorica. With the exception of Mrke, most of the other settlements (Klopot, Pelev Brijeg, Duga) of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are semi-deserted or completely abandoned as their inhabitants moved to Podgorica. As of 2011, Mrke had 207 residents. 118 identify as Montenegrins, 60 as Serbs, 25 chose not to declare any ethnicity.<ref name=\"monstat\">{{cite web |title=Census 2011 data - Montenegro |url=https://www.monstat.org/eng/page.php?id=395&pageid=57|website=Monstat |publisher=Statistical Office of Montenegro |accessdate=15 February 2020 |ref=monstat}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn a Venetian document dating to 1455, ''Banovichi'' is mentioned as one of the villages of Upper Zeta; this may be an early reference to Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. The first direct reference to the settlements that comprise Bratono\u017ei\u0107i today is found in the supplementary defter of the [[sanjak of Scutari]] in 1497. They hadn't formed as a single community at that time.{{sfn|Strugar|1987|p=135}}\n\nBratono\u017ei\u0107i is a tribe (''pleme'') of several patrilineal ancestries which formed it over time since the later 15th century.  The name of the tribe comes from a ''Brato'', father of ''Nika'' and ancestor of many of the brotherhoods of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i. He lived 14 generations before the time of the recording of the story around 1900. A ''Brato, son of Nika'' who lived with his brother ''Pali'' in the small hamlet of Moraci\u0107a in 1497 may be a reference to this figure. The defter mentions that previously they lived in Hrasni\u0107a near [[Podgorica]].{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=422}} \n\nTwo other communities that lived in the same area were the Albanian Catholic [[Bukumiri]]{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=427}} and the Lutovci, who may have come from the [[Pirot District|Pirot]] region in the eastern Balkans or from [[Pult|Pilot]] in northern Albania. Their origin is debated because no collective memory of their history has been retained except for a toponym which may be interpreted to refer to ''Pirot'' in eastern Serbia or ''Pilot'' in northern Albania. Their first historical ancestor in Bratono\u017ei\u0107i is a ''captain Gojko''. Archival records show that the Lutovci lived in 27 households of Luskozupa in 1497 in the [[nahiye]] of Piperi, which included Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and the [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]] tribe.{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=418}} Over the years, a few families from neighbouring tribes like Ku\u010di, Bjelopavli\u0107i and Piperi also settled Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and became part of the community. Bratono\u017ei\u0107i was an area of language contact between Slavic and Albanian as well as religious contact between Slavic Orthodoxy and Catholicism. [[Rufim Njegu\u0161]] in the first half of the 17th century is credited with converting the Bratono\u017ei\u0107i back to Orthodoxy from Catholicsm as well as making them take an oath that intermarriage with Catholic Albanians would take place only with women.<ref name=\"Pavlo25\">{{harvnb|Pavlovi\u0107|2019|p=25}}</ref> This measure would prevent any further reconversions to Catholicism. The events of the conversion of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are regarded as an important step for the reinforcement of what they termed as [[Serbdom]] (''Srbstvo'') and Orthodoxy in Montenegro by 19th century Serbian historiography.<ref name=\"Pavlo25\"/>\n\nThe tribe was often in conflict with the Ku\u010di over grazing lands.{{when|date=December 2014}}<ref>Vukovi\u0107 1996, p. 213 {{quote|\u0417\u0430 \u0442\u0443 \u0440\u0438\u0458\u0435\u0447 \u0411\u0443\u0440\u043e \u0443\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0443\u0448\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0411\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0438\u045b\u0430. \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 \u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0443 \u0441\u0435, \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u045b\u0435- \u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0435 \u0443\u0437 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0447\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e- \u043d\u043e\u0448\u043a\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u041f\u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u0448\u0430 \u0438 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0443 \u0438\u043c 16 \u0433\u043b\u0430- \u0432\u0430, \u0430 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0441 \u043e\u0431\u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430 ...}}</ref> Bratono\u017ei\u0107i often attacked Rovca, who were always defended by the Mora\u010dani.<ref name=\"\u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u04391998\">{{cite book|author=\u041f\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b \u0410\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439|title=\u0415\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u0435 \u0413\u043e\u0440\u0435|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yXBpAAAAMAAJ|year=1998|publisher=\u0426\u0438\u0434|quote=\u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0430, \u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0443 \u0441\u0432\u0430\u043a\u043e] \u043d\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0459\u0438 \u0448\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u0428\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435 \u0412\u0430\u0430^\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0430, \u0441\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u042c\u0435 \u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u043e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u043f\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e \u0431\u0440\u0437\u043e \u043d\u0430\u043c\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0438 \u043e\u0458\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0434\u0430 \u0438\u043c \u043d\u0438 \u041a\u0443\u0447\u0438 ...}}</ref> They also often fought with the Vasojevi\u0107i.<ref name=\"\u0420\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u04391998\"/>\n\nVenetian public servant [[Mariano Bolizza]]'s 1614 report that the villages of Ku\u010di, Bratono\u017ei\u0107i and part of [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] were under the soldiers of [[Medun]], the spahee, but the commander was not named; and the highlanders would pay the Ottoman officials a portion of their income.<ref>Elsie, p. 152</ref> The report registered the ''Bratanosich'' as a Serb, Orthodox village with 87 houses, and 260 men in arms commanded by Stanoje Radonjin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albanianhistory.net/en/texts1000-1799/AH1614.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-12-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213020432/http://www.albanianhistory.net/en/texts1000-1799/AH1614.html |archive-date=2014-12-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1658, the seven tribes of Ku\u010di, [[Vasojevi\u0107i]], Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, [[Piperi (tribe)|Piperi]], [[Klimenti]], [[Hoti (tribe)|Hoti]] and [[Gruda (tribe)|Gruda]] allied themselves with the [[Republic of Venice]], establishing the so-called \"Seven-fold barjak\" or \"alaj-barjak\", against the Ottomans.<ref name=MZ>{{cite book|title=Mitolo\u0161ki zbornik|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rvUSAQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Centar za mitolo\u0161ki studije Srbije|pages=24, 41\u201345}}</ref> In 1689, an uprising broke out in Piperi, Rovca, [[Bjelopavli\u0107i (tribe)|Bjelopavli\u0107i]], Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, Ku\u010di and Vasojevi\u0107i, while at the same time an uprising broke out in [[Prizren]], [[Pe\u0107]], [[Pri\u0161tina]] and [[Skopje]], and then in [[Kratovo, North Macedonia|Kratovo]] and [[Kriva Palanka]] in October ([[Karposh's Rebellion]]).<ref name=\"armije1968\">{{cite book|author=Belgrade (Serbia). Vojni muzej Jugoslovenske narodne armije|title=Fourteen centuries of struggle for freedom|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2m8MAQAAMAAJ|year=1968|publisher=The Military Museum|page=xxviii}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Velika attacks (1879)]], the battalions of the Mora\u010dani and Bratono\u017ei\u0107i fought off the Albanians.<ref name=DVA>{{cite book|title=Dva Petrovi\u0107a Njego\u0161a: Vladika Danilo Petrovi\u0107|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nH4-AQAAMAAJ|year=1896|publisher=\u0160tamparija Petra \u0106ur\u010di\u0107a|quote=(23) \u043e\u043a\u0442. \u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0420\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435 \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0443 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0438\u043c\u0430. \u041a\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0432 \u0431\u043e\u0458 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u0434\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u045b\u0438, \u043d\u0430\u0458\u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0443 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435. \u041e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0431\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u045a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e \u0445\u0438\u0459\u0430\u0434\u0430. \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435 22. \u043d\u043e\u0432. (4. \u0434\u0435\u043a) \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0443 \u043e\u0434 300 \u0459\u0443\u0434\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435. \u0422\u0443 \u0441\u0430\u0434 \u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0435 \u0443 \u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0443 4\u20145 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0459\u0443\u043d\u0430. \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442o\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u0441 \u0458\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0443\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435 \u0438 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u0438\u0445. \u0441\u0435\u045b\u0438, \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0442\u043e \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0443 \u043b\u0435\u0452\u0430. \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0438\u0445. \u0432\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0448\u0435 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0430. \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431\u0435 \u0434\u043e 1000. \u041f\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 \u0438\u043c\u0430\u0448\u0435 85 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 100 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445, \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0448\u0435 100 \u043a\u043e\u045a\u0430 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0458\u0430. \u041c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043c\u0430. \u041d\u0438 \u043e\u0432\u043e \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0438 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0435, \u043d\u0438 \u043f\u0430\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0435 \u0438\u043c \u0443 \u0426\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443. \u0422\u0440\u0435\u045b\u0438 \u0434\u0430\u043d \u0431\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0430 \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442 \u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e 10.000 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 3000 \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0430, \u043a\u043e\u0458\u0435 \u0441\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0435 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043f \u0402\u043e\u043a\u043e. \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043e\u0434 9 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043e \u043c\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0430. \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u0438\u043c\u0430\u0448\u0435 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 1400, \u0426\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0446\u0438 36 \u043c\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0438 70 \u0440\u0430\u045a\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0418 \u043e\u0432\u0434\u0435 \u0458\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e, \u0434\u0430 \u0458\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0452\u0443 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u043e \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043c\u0430. \u0422\u0443 \u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442o\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438, \u0412\u0430\u0441\u043e\u0458\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b\u0438 \u0438 \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438. \u041d\u0438\u0441\u0443 \u0441\u0435 \u0410\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438 \u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438. 30. \u0458\u0443\u043d. (12. \u0458\u0443\u043b.) 1880 \u043f\u0440\u0435 \u0437\u043e\u0440\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0446\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0443 \u0448\u0440\u0435\u0434\u045a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0443 \u043d\u0430 \u0413\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0446\u0443 \u043d\u0430 ...}}</ref> At the subsequent [[Battle of Nov\u0161i\u0107e]], the battalions of [[Ku\u010di]], [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] and Bratono\u017ei\u0107i fought the Albanian irregulars under the command of [[Ali Pasha of Gusinje]], and were defeated. Soon after [[Battle of Nov\u0161i\u0107e]] in the same area, the [[Battle of Murino]] broke out in which Ottomans with Albanian irregulars attacked again less numerous forces of [[Principality of Montenegro]] and were heavily defeated by battalions of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, [[Vasojevi\u0107i]] and [[Mora\u010dani]].<ref name=DVA/><ref>{{cite book|author=King Nikola I|title=Cjelokupna djela|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CggYAAAAMAAJ|year=1969|page=567|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Istorijski institut u Titogradu|title=Istorijski zapisi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zD1pAAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=Istorijski institut u Titogradu|page=66|ref=harv}}</ref> At the beginning of the 20th century, the region had ca. 400 houses.\n\n===Brotherhoods===\nAll brotherhoods of the tribe have as ''[[Slava]]'' (patron saints) [[Saint Nicholas]] (''Sveti Nikola'') and Saint John (''Sveti Jovan).\nThe families of Bratono\u017ei\u0107i are: Avramovi\u0107, Bajovi\u0107, Baljevi\u0107, Balevi\u0107, Bali\u010devi\u0107, Barjaktarovi\u0107, Bar\u017ei\u0107, Biljuri\u0107, Bismiljak, Bo\u0161kovi\u0107, Brankovi\u0107, Butri\u0107, Velji\u0107, Veljovi\u0107, Velimirovi\u0107, Veskovi\u0107, Vidi\u0107, Vujovi\u0107, Vujoti\u0107, Vukajlovi\u0107, Vukovi\u0107, Vukorepovi\u0107, Vuli\u0107, Vu\u010deli\u0107, Vu\u010dini\u0107, Gari\u0107, Gili\u0107, Gogi\u0107, Gruji\u0107, Gudovi\u0107, Darmanovi\u0107, Dmitrovi\u0107, Doki\u0107, \u0110elevi\u0107,\u0110uki\u0107,\u0110urdjevi\u0107, \u0110uri\u0107, \u017divkovi\u0107, \u017dmiki\u0107, Ili\u0107, Jankovi\u0107, Jelavi\u0107, Jovanovi\u0107, Jovovi\u0107, Kalu\u0111erovi\u0107, Keljanovi\u0107, Kekovi\u0107, Kora\u0107, Krkeli\u0107, Lajkovi\u010d, Lainovi\u0107, Lalovi\u0107, La\u0161evi\u0107, Likovi\u0107, Luki\u0107, Lutovac, Ljajinovi\u0107, Ljajkovic, Ljaljovi\u0107, Ljakovi\u0107, Lja\u0161ovi\u0107, Malevi\u0107, Marni\u0107, Macura, Mijailovi\u0107, Miajlovi\u0107, Milovanovi\u0107, Mirkovi\u0107, Muratovi\u0107, Novovi\u0107, Obrenovi\u0107, Pavi\u0107evi\u0107, Pavli\u010di\u0107, Peju\u0161kovi\u0107, Perovi\u0107, Pra\u0161\u010devi\u0107, Prelev\u010danin, Premovi\u0107, Progonovi\u0107i, Radojevi\u0107, Radosevi\u0107, Radunovi\u0107, Raketi\u0107, Raki\u0107, Ratkovi\u0107, Sekulovi\u0107, Stani\u0161i\u0107, Stankovi\u0107, Strahinji\u0107, Toljevi\u0107, Todorovii\u0107, Toma\u0161evii\u0107, To\u0161kovi\u0107, Trimojevi\u0107, \u0106ekli\u0107, \u010cetkovic, Ugri\u010di\u0107, Femiji\u0107, Cari\u010di\u0107, Cmiljani\u0107, \u010ca\u0111enovi\u0107, \u010cubranovi\u0107, \u0160\u0107epan\u010devi\u0107, \u0160ajinovi\u0107, \u0160akovi\u0107, \u0160o\u0161ki\u0107. The Muslim Bratono\u017ei\u0107i of [[Bijelo Polje]] include Kora\u0107i, Ljaljevi\u0107i, Polumente, Uremovi\u0107i, Huremovi\u0107i.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Milo\u0161 Obrenovi\u0107 I of Serbia]]{{sfn|Banac|1988|p=45}}\n*[[Uro\u0161 To\u0161kovi\u0107]], painter<ref>{{cite web|title=TO\u0160KOVI\u0106|url=http://montenegrina.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/05/toskovic-low-res.pdf|website=montenegrina.net|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Ni\u0161a Savelji\u0107]], by paternal descent\n*[[Esteban Saveljich]], by paternal descent\n*[[Nemanja Be\u0161ovi\u0107]]\n*[[Milorad Vu\u010deli\u0107]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |last1=Banac |first1=Ivo |title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics |date=1988 |publisher=Cornell University Press |isbn=0801494931 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA438|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Erdeljanovi\u0107|first=Jovan|authorlink=Jovan Erdeljanovi\u0107|title=Ku\u010di, Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, Piperi|year=1907}}\n**{{cite book|last=Erdeljanovi\u0107|first=Jovan|title=Bratono\u017ei\u0107i, pleme u Crnogorskim brdima|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwlZnQEACAAJ|year=1907}}\n*{{cite book|author=Novo Vukovi\u0107|title=Knji\u017eevnost Crne Gore od XII do XIX vijeka: Primeri \u010dojstva i juna\u0161tva|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5TlAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Obod}}\n*{{cite book|author=Miomir Da\u0161i\u0107|title=Vasojevi\u0107i: od pomena do 1860. godine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Km9MAQAAIAAJ|year=1986|publisher=Narodna knjiga}}\n*{{cite book|author=Mirko S. Radoi\u010di\u0107|title=Hercegovina i Crna Gora 1875-1878|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V14xAQAAIAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Savez udru\u017eenja boraca NOR-a, Op\u0161tinski odbor}}\n*{{cite book|author=Milo Markovi\u0107|title=Bratono\u017ei\u0107i kroz istoriju|year=2014}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pavlovi\u0107|first=Aleksandar|chapter=\"Forging the enemy: the transformation of common Serbian-Albanian traits into enmity and political hostility\"|editor1-last=Pavlovi\u0107|editor1-first=Aleksandar|editor2-last=Dra\u0161ko|editor2-first=Gazela Pudar|editor3-last=Halili|editor3-first=Rigels|title=Rethinking Serbian-Albanian Relations: Figuring out the Enemy|year=2019|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781351273145|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?redir_esc=y&id=YCCeDwAAQBAJ&q=Old+Serbia#v=snippet&q=Old%20Serbia&f=false |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Pulaha |first1=Selami |title=Defter i Sanxhakut t\u00eb Shkodr\u00ebs 1485 |date=1974 |publisher=Academy of Sciences of Albania |url=https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B3ma9plMXxAEZi1PZTVXMXV1NFE/edit |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author=Vlado Strugar|title=Pro\u0161lost Crne Gore kao predmet nau\u010dnog istra\u017eivanja i obrade|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=maYMAAAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Crnogorska akademija nauka i umjetnosti |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|title=Pleme Bratono\u017ei\u0107i (\u041f\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0435 \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0436\u0438\u045b\u0438)|date=June 13, 2013|publisher=Poreklo|url=http://www.poreklo.rs/2013/06/13/pleme-bratono%C5%BEi%C4%87i/}}\n*{{cite web|author=Marko Miljanov|title=Ne\u0161to o Bratono\u017ei\u0107ima|publisher=Rastko|url=http://www.rastko.rs/rastko-cg/umjetnost/marko_miljanov-bratonozici.html}}\n\n{{Regions in Montenegro}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bratonozici}}\n[[Category:Historical regions in Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Montenegro]]\n", "name_user": "Maleschreiber", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBrotherhoods", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bratono%C5%BEi%C4%87i"}
{"title_page": "War Machine (mixed martial artist)", "text_new": "{{short description|American criminal, mixed martial artist and pornographic actor}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = War Machine\n| other_names     = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             =\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Jonathan Paul Koppenhaver\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1981|11|30}}\n| birth_place     = [[Simi Valley, California]], [[United States]]\n| residence       =\n| nationality     =  [[People of the United States|American]]\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=10}} \n| weight          = {{Convert|170|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class    = [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]]\n| reach           = {{convert|72|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n| stance          = [[midget|Manlet]]\n| fighting_out_of = [[San Diego, California]]\n| team            = Team Undisputed\n| rank            = ''black belt in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]]''\n| years_active    =\n| mma_kowin       = 8\n| mma_subwin      = 6\n| mma_decwin      = \n| mma_koloss      = \n| mma_subloss     = 4\n| mma_decloss     = 1\n| mma_draw        = \n| mma_nc          = \n| university      = [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina|The Citadel]]\n| url             =\n| sherdog         = 10999\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''War Machine''' (born '''Jonathan Paul Koppenhaver''', November 30, 1981) is an American former professional [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] and former [[pornographic actor]] who has been convicted on multiple felony charges including sexual assault.<ref name=\"411Mania\">{{cite news |last=James |first=Dustin |date=August 27, 2008 |title=UFC News: UFC/WEC Merger, TNA Wrestling Causes UFC Name Change, More |url=http://www.411mania.com/MMA/news/83908/UFC-News:-UFC-WEC-Merger,-TNA-Wrestling-Causes-UFC-Name-Change,-More.htm |work=411mania |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mixed Martial Arts Show Results |url=http://boxing.nv.gov/2008%20Results/05-24-08%20MMA.pdf |work=[[Nevada Athletic Commission]] |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> In MMA, he competed in the [[Welterweight (MMA)|Welterweight]] division. He was a fighter on ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Hughes vs. Team Serra]]'' as part of [[Matt Serra|Team Serra]] and also competed for [[Bellator MMA]], [[Tachi Palace Fights]], [[BAMMA]], and the [[Xtreme Fighting Championships]].  In 2008, he legally changed his name to \"War Machine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2008/08/28/jon-koppenhaver-legally-changes-name-to-war-machine/ |title=Jon Koppenhaver legally changes name to 'War Machine' |publisher=MMAmania.com |date= August 28, 2008|accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref> In March 2017, he was convicted on 29 felony counts after assaulting his ex-girlfriend and her lover during a 2014 incident. He was sentenced to life in prison on June 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Judge denies War Machine's motion for new trial, sentences him to life in prison for Christy Mack attack|url=https://www.msn.com/en-ca/sports/mma/judge-denies-war-machine%E2%80%99s-motion-for-new-trial-sentences-him-to-life-in-prison-for-christy-mack-attack/ar-BBC6V4b?li=AAadgLE&ocid=spartanntp|accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKoppenhaver was born in [[Simi Valley, California]]. His [[German Americans|German-American]] father was an officer for the Los Angeles Police Department, while his [[Mexicans|Mexican]] mother worked as a nurse and later became a work-at-home mother.<ref name=\"Spike1\">{{cite video |title =MMA Uncensored Live: Exclusive: Extended War Machine Interview (Part 1 of 2) |medium =Television production |publisher =[[Spike (TV channel)|Spike]] |location = |date =March 15, 2012 |url=http://www.spike.com/video-clips/5o92si/mma-uncensored-live-exclusive-extended-war-machine-interview-part-1-of-2 |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> Due to his mother's drug addiction, Koppenhaver would often take care of his younger brother and sister.<ref name=\"Spike1\"/> When he was 13, Koppenhaver unsuccessfully performed [[CPR]] on his father.<ref>{{cite web |last=Karkoski |first=Kris |date=November 8, 2007 |title=The Ultimate Fighter Season 6: Episode 8 Recap |url=http://mmafrenzy.com/1532/the-ultimate-fighter-season-6-episode-8-recap/ |work=MMA Frenzy |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2000, Koppenhaver attended [[The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina|The Citadel]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] for two years before being expelled for \"poor behavior\".<ref name=\"UFCP\">{{cite web |title=Jon Koppenhaver |url=http://www.ufc.com/fighter/Jon-Koppenhaver/ |work=[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> While attending, he majored in [[biology]].<ref name=\"UFCP\"/> In an interview, Koppenhaver claimed that he had been earning high marks at The Citadel.<ref name=\"Spike1\"/>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n\n===''The Ultimate Fighter'' Season Six===\nKoppenhaver was a fighter on ''[[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Hughes vs. Team Serra]]'', fighting on ''Team Serra''. He was not part of the original sixteen fighters.<ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-mmacol27aug27,1,7872443.story?page=1&ctrack=3&cset=true |work=Los Angeles Times.com |title=Participants in Ultimate Fighter season six are announced |first=Dave |last=Meltzer |date=2007-08-27 |accessdate=August 27, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024150433/http://latimes.com/sports/boxing/la-mmacol27aug27%2C1%2C7872443.story?page=1&ctrack=3&cset=true |archivedate=October 24, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Instead, Koppenhaver was brought in as a replacement when [[Roman Mitichyan]] broke his elbow during evaluations and was sent home.<ref>{{cite web |last=Doyle |first=Alicia |date=October 30, 2007 |title=Simi man gets real on 'Ultimate Fighter': Mixed martial artist eyes prized contract |url=http://www.venturacountystar.com/news/2007/oct/30/simi-man-gets-real-on-ultimate-fighter/ |work=[[Ventura County Star]] |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> Koppenhaver lost by unanimous decision to [[Tom Speer]].<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web |title=The Top Six Ultimate Fighter Finale Fights |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/723323-the-top-six-ultimate-fighter-finale-fights/page/5 |work=[[Bleacher Report]] |accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter a dispute with [[TNA Wrestling]] over the use of his nickname, he legally changed his name from \"Jon Koppenhaver\" to \"War Machine\" in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=UFC News: Jon Koppenhaver Legally Changes His Name To 'War Machine' |url=http://www.cagetoday.com/ufc-news-jon-koppenhaver-legally-changes-his-name-to-war-machine |work=Cage Today |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nIn War Machine's official UFC debut, he defeated [[Jared Rollins]] in [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Hughes vs Team Serra Finale]] via KO at 2:01 of the third round. War Machine and Rollins both received $25,000 due to winning fight of the night honors and War Machine winning knockout of the night. His last UFC fight was at [[UFC 84]] against [[Yoshiyuki Yoshida]] which he lost via submission in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mma-zone.com/2008/ufc-84-results-penn-defeats-sherk/ |title=UFC 84 Results: Penn Defeats Sherk- MMA News & Views |publisher=Mma-zone.com |date=2008-05-25 |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref>\n\nHe was released from the UFC after rejecting a fight offered by UFC matchmaker Joe Silva, and after comments made about the death of fellow UFC fighter [[Evan Tanner]]. War Machine posted on his Myspace that he believed that Tanner had gone to the isolated southern California desert to kill himself after he realized his career might have been over and had basically made no money during it. Medical examiners eventually proved that Tanner's death was not a suicide, but War Machine stood by his statements.<ref name=added>{{cite web|url=http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=news.detail&gid=10856|title=Koppenhaver Returns as Two Welterweight Bouts are added to UFC 84|last=Gerbasi|first=Thomas|publisher=UFC.com|date=March 18, 2008|accessdate=March 18, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Bellator Fighting Championships===\nWar Machine was signed and then released by [[Bellator Fighting Championships]]. His [[MySpace]] blog cited disparaging comments about [[Barack Obama]] as the cause for his non-participation in their upcoming tournament.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.fightlinker.com/thank-god-for-consistency.mma | title= Thank God for consistency | date= 5 February 2009 |author= fightlinker | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090207131238/http://www.fightlinker.com/thank-god-for-consistency.mma | archivedate=February 7, 2009 | website= Fightlinker.com}}</ref><ref>[http://mmajunkie.com/news/13932/war-machine-jon-koppenhaver-cut-by-bellator-fighting-championships.mma War Machine (Jon Koppenhaver) cut by Bellator Fighting Championships]</ref>\n\n===Independent Promotions (2009\u20132011)===\nOn June 20, 2009, War Machine was set to fight [[Roger Bowling (fighter)|Roger Bowling]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Levick |first=Bryan |url=http://fiveouncesofpain.com/2009/03/24/jon-war-machine-koppenhaver-vs-roger-bowling-on-june-20/ |title=Jon \"War Machine\" Koppenhaver vs. Roger Bowling on June 20 |publisher=Five Ounces of Pain |date=2009-03-24 |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref> They were then set to fight at XFC 9 in [[Tampa, Florida]] on September 5, where it was to be the main event and would broadcast live over [[HDNet|HDNet.com]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmaxfc.com/xfcevents/fightcards/tampa_xfc9.html |title=mmaxfc.com |publisher=mmaxfc.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2009, War Machine stepped into the cage and faced off against [[Mikey Gomez]]. The ref stopped the fight, giving a somewhat controversial win to War Machine by TKO (punches), at 13 seconds in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getinmagazine.com/web/2009/09/090609xfcfr.htm |title=Get In Magazine |publisher=Get In Magazine |date= |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref> War Machine was scheduled to fight October 3, 2009 against [[Jacob McClintock]], but cancelled the fight so he could fight on October 8, 2009 against [[David Mitchell (fighter)|David Mitchell]].\n\nOn April 17, 2010, he was set to face Tex Johnson in the main event of Wild Bill's Fight Night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.georgiafighters.com/war-machine-vs-tex-johnson-to-fight-on-sat-april-3-at-wild-bills/ |title=War Machine vs Tex Johnson to Fight on Sat, April 17 at Wild Bill's! |publisher=Georgia Fighters |date= |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref> On April 16, [[TMZ.com]] reported that War Machine left a comment on his [[Twitter]] saying he would not be turning up to the event for the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2010/04/16/war-machine-mma-fight-georgia-twitter-suspended/ |title=War Machine - Punished in Georgia |publisher=TMZ.com |date=2010-04-16 |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Bellator Fighting Championships===\nOn December 7, 2011, it was announced that War Machine was re-signed to an exclusive deal with [[Bellator Fighting Championships]] and would be competing in their Season 6 Welterweight Tournament.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://mmajunkie.com/news/26433/bellator-inks-polarizing-fighter-war-machine.mma | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120127095341/http://mmajunkie.com/news/26433/bellator-inks-polarizing-fighter-war-machine.mma | archivedate=January 27, 2012 | date= 7 December 2011 | title= Bellator inks polarizing fighter War Machine | first= Dann |last= Stupp | website= MMA Junkie | publisher= USA Today UFC Media Group }}</ref> War Machine was expected to fight [[Karl Amoussou]] in the opening round of the welterweight tournament at [[Bellator 63]]. War Machine was sentenced to a year in prison for the prior assault in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] from December 2009 and was forced out of the bout and the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.5thround.com/105003/war-machine-headed-back-to-prison/|title=War Machine Headed Back to Prison |publisher=5thround.com |date=February 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was set to make his Bellator debut on January 17, 2013 against [[Paul Daley]] when he tore his ACL and broke his fibula which forced him out of the fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmaconvert.com/2012/12/07/war-machine-suffers-broken-leg-out-of-planned-bellator-fight-with-paul-daley/ |title=War Machine Suffers Broken Leg, Out Of Planned Bellator Fight With Paul Daley |publisher=mmaconvert.com |date=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\nWar Machine faced [[Blas Avena]] at [[Bellator Fighting Championships: 2013 Summer Series#Bellator XCVI|Bellator 96]] on June 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Welterweights-War-Machine-Blas-Avena-to-Collide-June-19-at-Bellator-96-in-Oklahoma-52073|title=War Machine makes his Bellator Debut against Blas Avena at Bellator 96 |publisher=Sherdog.com |date=2013-04-26}}</ref> He won via TKO due to punches in round one.\n\nWar Machine then took part in [[Bellator MMA|Bellator MMA's]] Season Nine Welterweight Tournament at [[Bellator 100]] against Vaughn Anderson in the Quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefightnation.com/vaughn-anderson-to-face-war-machine-at-bellator-100/|title=Vaughn Anderson to face War Machine at Bellator 100 |publisher=Fightnation.com |date=2013-09-07}}</ref> He won via technical submission due to a rear naked choke in the second round.\n\nWar Machine then faced [[Ron Keslar]] on October 18, 2013 at [[Bellator 104]] in the semifinals of the Season Nine Welterweight Tournament. He lost via technical submission due to a rear naked choke in the first round.\n\nOn August 8, 2014, [[Bellator MMA]] announced the release of War Machine after he assaulted his former girlfriend Christy Mack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/War-Machine-Released-from-Bellator-MMA-Contract-After-Allegedly-Assaulting-Girlfriend-71731|title=War Machine released for allegedly assaulting girlfriend and two others}}</ref>\n\n==Adult film career==\n\nOn October 31, 2009, War Machine announced that he would pursue a career in [[pornographic film]]s along with fighting [[mixed martial arts]].<ref name=\"ME\">{{cite web |title=War Machine has left MMA, dude's a pornstar now |url=http://middleeasy.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=912:war-machine-has-left-mma-dudes-a-pornstar-now&catid=36:fighters |work=Middle Easy |accessdate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> In his announcement, War Machine revealed that he had signed with [[LA Direct Models]] and made his debut scene with [[Pornographic film actor|pornographic actress]] [[Riley Steele]].<ref name=\"ME\"/> Between 2009 and 2010, War Machine appeared in twelve adult films.<ref name=\"IAFD\">{{cite web |title=War Machine IAFD |url=http://www.iafd.com/person.rme/perfid=warmachine/gender=m/war-machine.htm|work=IAFD |accessdate=September 21, 2012}}</ref> War Machine was featured in the January 2014 issue of ''[[Hustler Magazine]]'' in a nude pictorial with his future girlfriend, pornographic actress [[Christy Mack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xfanz.com/news/169319|title=Christy Mack, War Machine Do Hustler Layout}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests and convictions==\nOn September 2, 2007, he was found guilty of striking a Las Vegas man in the face and choking him unconscious during a parking lot scuffle.<ref name=\"MMAJ\">{{cite web |last=Stupp |first=Dann |date=February 21, 2008 |title=Judge Shows Leniency with John Koppenhaver Sentencing|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/3799/judge-shows-leniency-with-john-koppenhaver-sentencing.mma |work=MMA Junkie |accessdate=March 18, 2008}}</ref> In February 2008, he was sentenced to three years of probation and 30 days of community service, avoiding the possible felony charge and accompanying prison time.<ref name=\"MMAJ\"/>\n\nOn February 22, 2008, Koppenhaver pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of assault and battery, and was fined and sentenced to probation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.duisandiego.com/new_recent_dui_info.html#koppenhaver-attorney-casey|title=San Diego Attorney Casey Defends Jon Koppenhaver's Fighting Career|publisher=San Diego DUI Lawyer|accessdate=2012-04-25}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2010, War Machine was sentenced to one year in the county jail for a [[felony assault]] conviction stemming from a fight at a [[Point Loma]] bar earlier in the year, as well as an additional fight at a [[Pacific Beach, San Diego|Pacific Beach]] bar.<ref name=\"FN\">{{cite web |title=Report: Former UFC Fighter War Machine Going to Jail |url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/08/25/report-ufc-fighter-war-machine-going-jail/ |work=[[Fox News]] |accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"TMZ\">{{cite web |title=Ex-UFC Fighter War Machine Gets Jail Time For Assault |url=https://www.tmz.com/2010/08/24/war-machine-ufc-sentenced-felony-assault-guilty-san-diego-bar/ |work=[[TMZ.com]] |accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> He was imprisoned in [[San Diego County, California|San Diego's]] George Bailey Detention Facility and served time in [[solitary confinement]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Machine |first=War |url=http://wmweek36.blogspot.com |title=Week #36 |publisher=Wmweek36.blogspot.com |date=2011-04-21 |accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref>\n\nAfter going to jail, War Machine maintained his [[Twitter]] account as well as a blog documenting his time in jail.<ref>[https://www.blogger.com/profile/02988533996204637335 War Machine's profile at Blogger.ca]</ref> On February 1, 2012, it was announced via War Machine's Twitter that he would be serving another year of jail time, due to preceding events. He was released on October 29, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/news/430000/War-Machine-free-at-last-again/ |title=War Machine free at last, again - Mixed Martial Arts News |publisher=Mixedmartialarts.com |date= October 29, 2012|accessdate=2014-01-23}}</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2014, [[Christy Mack]] and associate Corey Thomas were assaulted by War Machine in her [[Las Vegas]] home. Mack was hospitalized, where it was found that she suffered from 18 broken bones, a broken nose, missing teeth, a fractured rib and a ruptured liver.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/08/12/christy-mack-shares-photos-of-the-beating-she-allegedly-endured-at-the-hands-of-mma-fighter-war-machine/|title=Christy Mack shares photos of the beating she allegedly endured at the hands of MMA fighter War Machine |newspaper=The Washington Post |author=Soraya Nadia McDonald |date=August 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref> At the time, War Machine was not in a relationship with Mack.<ref name=\"ViceMagazine\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/hanging-out-with-pornstar-christy-mack-made-me-not-scared-of-porn|title=Hanging Out With Pornstar Christy Mack Made Me Less Scared of Porn|author=Kristy Hoffman|date=2013-10-15|magazine=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref><ref name=\"Bellator MMA Fighter, War Machine, Dating Porn Star Christy Mack\">{{cite web|url=http://blacksportsonline.com/home/2013/06/bellator-mma-fighter-war-machine-dating-porn-star-christy-mack-photos/|title=Bellator MMA Fighter, War Machine, Dating Porn Star Christy Mack|date=22 June 2013|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Mack alleged that it was War Machine who carried out the attack.<ref name=\"Chicagotribune\">{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-dog-the-bounty-hunter-christy-marck-20140814-story.html |title=Dog the Bounty Hunter to join manhunt for 'War Machine' |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2014-08-17}}</ref> According to Mack, War Machine also attempted to rape her.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/sport/boxing/christy-mack-describes-alleged-assault-at-the-hands-of-former-boyfriend-mma-fighter-war-machine-aka-jon-koppenhaver/story-fndkzthy-1227021522374 Christy Mack describes alleged assault at the hands of former boyfriend, MMA fighter \"War Machine\", aka Jon Koppenhaver], [[news.com.au]], August 12, 2014</ref> On August 15, War Machine was arrested in [[Simi Valley]], California, by U.S. Marshals and Simi Valley police.<ref name=\"ktla\">{{cite web|url=http://ktla.com/2014/08/15/mma-fighter-war-machine-arrested-sought-in-las-vegas-beating-of-ex-girlfriend/ |title=MMA Fighter 'War Machine' Arrested in Simi Valley, Was Sought in Las Vegas Beating of Ex-Girlfriend |publisher=KTLA |date=2014-08-11 |accessdate=2014-08-17}}</ref>  His trial, originally scheduled for September 2015, was postponed twice before beginning in February 2017.<ref name=\"Review Journal 2015-06\">{{cite news |last=Ferrara |first=David |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/las-vegas/war-machine-stay-behind-bars-until-trial-brutal-beating |title=War Machine to stay behind bars until trial for brutal beating |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |date=2015-06-03 |accessdate=2015-08-17 }}</ref><ref>[http://lasvegassun.com/news/2015/sep/21/ex-fighter-war-machine-asking-nevada-judge-to-post/ Ex-fighter Koppenhaver gets judge to postpone trial], ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'', September 21, 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/texas/article_86e3c1a7-8e5d-5546-91c5-05fc23a90d36.html \"Trial in Vegas for ex-fighter War Machine reset to February\", Associated Press]</ref> On March 20, 2017, he was convicted on 29 felony counts, including kidnapping and sexual assault with a weapon, for which he faced life in prison. The jury deadlocked on two counts of attempted murder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/e26589bcd3d844d6b7c3f4f589ee60cc|title=Ex-MMA fighter guilty of 29 felonies in kidnap, beating case|author=Ken Ritter|publisher=AP|date=March 21, 2017| accessdate=March 20, 2017}}</ref> War Machine was represented by [[Jay Leiderman]] and Brandon Sua.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/crime/courts/judge-will-allow-testimony-about-rape-fantasy-upcoming-war-machine-trial |title = Las Vegas News &#124; Breaking News & Headlines}}</ref> On June 5, 2017, War Machine was sentenced to an aggregate sentence of [[life in prison]] with possibility of [[parole]] after 36 years has been served.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/war-machine-mma-star-sentenced-to-life-for-assault-of-ex-w486057|title=War Machine Sentenced to Life: The Fall of an MMA Star|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-06-06}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Las Vegas Metropolitan Police Department, War Machine was found unresponsive in his cell on October 14, 2014 at around 9:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"TMZ-suicide\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tmz.com/2014/10/16/war-machine-suicide-attempt-jail-las-vegas/|title=Koppenhaver -- Attempts Suicide by Hanging in Jail|work=TMZ|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref> by a corrections officer conducting routine checks in the cells. The cell officer found War Machine struggling to breathe, with a torn piece of linen around his neck that was tied to the leg of his bunk bed. After the officer unfortuantely cut the linen, War Machine's vitals stabilized within 15 minutes, and he was moved to a medical ward, where he was placed on [[suicide watch]]. In a [[suicide note]] found in his cell, he quoted philosopher [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] twice to explain his actions, stating \u201cverily, I often laugh at the weaklings who think themselves good because they have no claws.\u201d. What War Machine didn't realise, is that he had actually embodied the precise opposite of what Nietzsche meant here, liekly because he is a fucking imbecile.<ref name=\"rawstory-suicide\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rawstory.com/rs/2014/10/cage-fighter-war-machine-blames-anti-male-society-for-his-domestic-violence-in-suicide-note/|title=Cage-fighter Koppenhaver blames anti-male society for his domestic violence in suicide note|last1=Kaufman|first1=Scott|publisher=RawStory|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> The incident occurred on the same day he was supposed to appear in court to discuss a plea deal.<ref name=\"nbc-suicide\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/mma-fighter-war-machine-attempts-suicide-jail-n228036|title=MMA Fighter War Machine Attempts Suicide in Jail|last1=Fieldstadt|first1=Elisha|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn-suicide\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/17/justice/mma-fighter-suicide-attempt/|title=MMA fighter War Machine attempts suicide in jail, report says|last1=Karimi|first1=Faith|publisher=CNN|accessdate=17 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nWar Machine maintained a prison blog<ref>[https://www.blogger.com/profile/02988533996204637335 War Machine blogger profile]</ref> during his first conviction with the assistance of a friend who typed out handwritten notes provided by War Machine.<ref name=\"mra\">{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/articles/538670/inside-mens-rights-movement|title=Inside the men's rights movement|date=2015-06-07|website=[[The Week]]}}</ref> On his blog, War Machine claimed that \"The oppression of MEN is worse than oppression of Jews in Nazi germany, worse than the slavery of Blacks in early America\".<ref>[http://wmweek25.blogspot.com.au/ Week #25], Blogspot.com.au</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOn July 20, 2018, it was revealed that War Machine had been engaged to Ashley Farrington; they first became acquainted with each other when she started writing to him in prison as his pen pal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2018/07/20/war-machine-engaged-prison-pen-pal/?adid=TMZ_Search_Results|title=War Machine Engaged To Pen Pal... Sorry, No Conjugal Visits}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 8\n| ko-losses= \n| sub-wins= 6\n| sub-losses= 4\n| dec-wins= \n| dec-losses= 1\n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 14\u20135\n| [[Ron Keslar]]\n| Technical Submission (rear-naked c