s from California]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Nevada]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial artists from California]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Nevada]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of Nevada]]\n[[Category:Welterweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:People from Simi Valley, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ventura County, California]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "92.17.193.181", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eArrests and convictions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_Machine_(mixed_martial_artist)"}
{"title_page": "Ben Wyatt (Parks and Recreation)", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character from Parks and Recreation}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = '''Ben Wyatt'''\n| series             = [[Parks and Recreation]]\n| image              = [[File:Ben Wyatt Parks & Rec.jpg|235px]]\n| caption            = f the Bernie bros\n| portrayer          = [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]]\n| first              = \"[[The Master Plan (Parks and Recreation)|The Master Plan]]\"\n| last               = \"[[One Last Ride]]\"\n| alias              = \n| nickname           = Benji, Angelo, Jello-shot, J-shot, Ice-town, Ice-clown, Eagle Two\n| occupation         = [[First Gentleman of the United States]] (implied)<br>[[United States House of Representatives|Member of the U.S. House of Representatives]] from Indiana's 9th District <br>  City Manager of Pawnee, Indiana <br> President of the Sweetums Foundation (former) <br> [[Chief financial officer|CFO]] of Rent-a-Swag (former) <br> [[Campaign manager|Campaign Manager]]<br> Deputy [[City Manager]] of Pawnee, Indiana (former) <br> [[Indiana State Auditor]] (former) <br> [[Mayor]] of Partridge, Minnesota (impeached) <br> Board Game Designer\n| spouse             = [[Leslie Knope]] (m. 2013)\n| family             = Julia Wyatt (mother)<br>Steve Wyatt (father)<br>Stephanie Wyatt (sister)<br>Henry Wyatt (brother)\n| relatives          = Georgia Wyatt (niece)\n| affiliation        = [[Carleton College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA in Political Science]])\n| children           = Hillary Knope-Wyatt (son) <br> Stephen Knope-Wyatt (son) <br> Sonia Knope-Wyatt (daughter)\n}}\n'''Benjamin Wyatt''' is a fictional character portrayed by [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] in the TV series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''. The character guest starred in two episodes of [[Parks and Recreation (season 2)|season two]] and was upgraded to a series regular in [[Parks and Recreation (season 3)|season three]]. Ben is a [[state auditor]] who comes into [[Pawnee (Parks and Recreation)|Pawnee]] with [[Chris Traeger]] to evaluate the town's funds at the end of the second season. Ben began dating [[Leslie Knope]] in the [[Parks and Recreation (season 3)|season three]] episode \"[[Road Trip (Parks and Recreation)|Road Trip]]\" and married her in the [[Parks and Recreation (season 5)|season five]] episode \"Leslie and Ben.\" In the [[Parks and Recreation (season 7)|season seven]] episode \"2017\" Ben was named Pawnee's Woman of the Year for 2017. It is implied that Leslie later became the [[President of the United States]] making him the First Gentleman.\nBen Wyatt is a lover of all things [[calzones]], [[sci-fi]], and ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.\n\n==Character biography==\nBen is from [[Partridge Township, Pine County, Minnesota|Partridge, Minnesota]]. When he was 18, he ran for [[mayor]] and won on the strength of, in his words, \"anti-establishment voter rebellion.\" However, being so inexperienced, he quickly ran the town's finances into the ground mainly due to the construction of a winter sports complex called \"Ice Town\". He was then impeached after two months in office.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monroe |first=Justin |title=Video: Vote 'Parks and Recreation' Star Adam Scott For Mayor Of NYC |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=April 14, 2011 |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/04/video-vote-parks-and-recreation-star-adam-scott-mayor-nyc |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SJuEdre?url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/04/video-vote-parks-and-recreation-star-adam-scott-mayor-nyc |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\">{{cite news |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |title=Parks and Recreation: \"The Master Plan\" |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=May 14, 2010 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-master-plan,41155/ |accessdate=October 6, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQJ9hUx5?url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-master-plan%2C41155/ |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His complete blunder bankrupted the town, caused its unemployment rate to hit 30%, and led to the newspaper headline \"Ice Town Costs Ice Clown His Town Crown.\"<ref name=\"Sundermann0121\">{{cite web|last=Sundermann |first=Eric |title='Parks and Recreation' Season Premiere: Go Big or Go Home |publisher=Hollywood.com |date=January 21, 2011 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Season_Premiere_Go_Big_or_Go_Home/7751628 |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SKDofGt?url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Season_Premiere_Go_Big_or_Go_Home/7751628 |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Ben attended [[Carleton College]], where he was the host and DJ for a [[swing music]] college radio show called Zoot Suit Wyatt, a reference to the swing song \"[[Zoot Suit Riot (song)|Zoot Suit Riot]]\" (1997).<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://apps.carleton.edu/news/carleton_in_the_media/?story_id=1120452|title=NBC's \"Parks and Recreation\" mentions Carleton in \"Prom Planning\"|publisher= [[Carleton College]] |date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> After becoming an accountant, he and [[Chris Traeger]] assumed the nicknames Butch Count-sidy and the Sum-dance Kid, with the names referencing the outlaws [[Butch Cassidy]] and the [[Sundance Kid]] as well as being accounting puns.\n\nBen is very serious, mature and work-oriented, and usually does not seem fazed by much of the immature, eccentric behavior from some of the other members of the Pawnee Parks and Recreation Department, primarily [[Tom Haverford]], [[Leslie Knope]], and [[Andy Dwyer]]. Ben is often teased by Tom (and, early on, Leslie as well) for his affinity for, references to and vast knowledge in ''[[Star Wars]]'', ''[[Lord of the Rings]]'', ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' and other things considered to be \"nerdy\". His love for calzones is also a recurring joke in the series.  Ben is shown to have a hard time socializing, and connecting with people by having work as his main focus. During season six when he was jobless for a week, he created a game called ''The Cones of Dunshire''. The game became very popular, which he realized while visiting San Francisco. He was angry that he did not copyright it, but later in the show, one of his former coworkers surprises him with the copyright papers.\n\n===Season Two===\nWhen Ben comes to Pawnee, he immediately clashes with Leslie, as she yells at him three consecutive times for his seemingly callous attitude towards firing people and slashing her department's budget. However, when he asks her out for a beer, they begin to show respect for one another. He shares his past as the mayor of Partridge, and that he became a state auditor to prove he can be responsible and eventually run for office again.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /><ref name=\"SchurComm\">{{cite video | people=[[Michael Schur|Schur, Michael]]|date=2010|title=Parks and Recreation: Season Two: \"The Master Plan\" |type = Audio commentary DVD|publisher=[[Universal Studios Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Their new friendship turns sour when Ben and Chris reveal that the town is virtually out of funds and the government will have to be shut down until further notice.<ref name=\"Kandell0607\">{{cite news|last=Kandell |first=Steve |title=''Parks and Recreation'' Recap: Shutdown |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=May 21, 2010 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/05/parks_and_recreation_recap_shu.html |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQM8WKyX?url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/05/parks_and_recreation_recap_shu.html |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDespite the seriousness of the problems, Chris presents the situation in an extremely positive light and tries to make all the city hall employees around him happy, leaving the hard decisions and delivery of bad news up to Ben; meaning, Chris is the good cop and Ben is the bad cop in this partnership.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /> Chris and Ben form a budget task force, consisting of several government employees including Ron. When Ron accidentally reveals that Leslie was trying to set up an annual children's concert that was supposed to be canceled on Lot 48 behind Ann's house, Ben tries to shut it down. However, after seeing the effort Leslie put into it, which included having the equipment donated from local vendors, he pays the entertainer Freddy Spaghetti to come back after he booked another event, getting back on Leslie's good side. Ben is also surprised, but quietly pleased when Ron authorizes Leslie to take his place on the budget task force.<ref name=\"Kandell0607\" />\n\n===Season Three===\nWhen the government shutdown ends, Ben informs the department that due to the shoestring budget, they will only be on maintenance for the time being. Ben suspects that Leslie is trying to have Ann convince Chris to distribute more funds to the department and confirms his suspicions when he crashes their date at the same time Leslie crashes it, but Ben decides to let it play out. While at a gay club, Ben mentions the failure of the Ice Town project, showing that he used to be just as ambitious as Leslie, but Leslie gives him credit for trying. Ben listens to Leslie's presentation regarding the Pawnee Harvest Festival idea that will allow them to do their jobs properly and bring funds into the department. When Ben asks what will happen if it does not bring in funds, Leslie says they can shut down the department, and Ben allows them to go forth with the festival.<ref name=\"Sundermann0121\" />\n\nBen assists Leslie with the festival preparations, and is thoroughly impressed when she gives a flawless presentation despite being stricken with the flu.<ref>{{cite news |last=Heisler |first=Steve |title=Parks and Recreation: \"The Flu\" |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=January 27, 2011 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-flu,50577/ |accessdate=January 29, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SL8Ieh0?url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-flu%2C50577/ |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When Leslie and Ben try to ask the police force to handle security for the festival, Ben is shown not to have very strong social skills, although in this case it could be attributed to the fact that he does not understand Pawnee as well as Leslie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |title=Review: 'Parks and Recreation' - 'Ron & Tammy II': Rock the cradle of love? |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-ron-tammy-ii-rock-the-cradle-of-love |accessdate=February 13, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQNXEFBc?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-ron-tammy-ii-rock-the-cradle-of-love |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He and Leslie continue to build a strong friendship over their development of the Harvest Festival, and it is implied he starts to show romantic interest in her when he inquires of the police chief about her relationship with Dave. He also becomes better friends with Tom, supporting him when he is rejected by a cologne magnate, although Tom does his fair share of ribbing Ben.<ref name=\"Gilbert0319\">{{cite news |last=Gilbert |first=Megan |title=Parks and Recreation recap: 'Harvest Festival' |work=[[Punchline Magazine]] |date=March 19, 2011 |url=http://www.laughspin.com/2011/03/19/parks-and-recreation-recap-harvest-festival/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318062021/http://www.laughspin.com/2011/03/19/parks-and-recreation-recap-harvest-festival/ |archivedate=March 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nWhile doing the media blitz for the festival, he is continuously asked about his disastrous tenure as mayor of Partridge. After freezing up at the majority of questions asked, he then goes on a furious tirade at a later interview, prompting businesses to pull their sponsorships at the festival and putting the parks department in jeopardy. At the last interview at ''Pawnee Today'', Ben finally stands his ground, stating that everyone does stupid things when they were teenagers and that he has since saved at least five cities from bankruptcy as an auditor.<ref name=\"Porter0218\">{{cite web|last=Porter |first=Rick |title='Parks and Recreation': Welcome to Pawnee, Ben |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |date=February 18, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/parks-and-recreation-welcome-to-pawnee-ben.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zcQC1gYD?url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/parks-and-recreation-welcome-to-pawnee-ben.html |archivedate=June 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Sundermann0218\">{{cite news |last=Sundermann |first=Eric |title='Parks and Recreation' Recap: Media Blitz |publisher=Hollywood.com |date=February 18, 2011 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Recap_Media_Blitz/7763406 |accessdate=July 25, 2011}}</ref> During the festival itself, a series of catastrophes leads Ben to feel he is cursed and leave the festival, returning later to admit he is not over his past. Leslie assures him that he is as responsible for the festival's success as she is, and has the local Native American chief Ken Hotate perform a fake ceremony to remove his \"curse.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kandell |first=Steve |title=''Parks and Recreation'' Recap: Awesomesauce! |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=March 18, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/parks_and_recreation_recap.html |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zZbo8e1w?url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/parks_and_recreation_recap.html |archivedate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the festival, Chris is installed as interim city manager of Pawnee, and offers Ben a job as assistant city manager, which he eventually accepts. It is implied that he made the decision to be closer to Leslie and that he and Leslie are attracted to each other,<ref>{{cite news|last=Busis |first=Hillary |title='Parks and Recreation': I now pronounce you man and... wait, seriously? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 15, 2011 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/04/15/parks-and-recreation-april-andy-wedding/ |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ze9bHkSd?url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/04/15/parks-and-recreation-april-andy-wedding/ |archivedate=June 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but a new policy of Chris's forbids city employees to date each other and has halted any potential relationship. But, after being assigned to a road trip that would cause them to be alone, Ben tells Leslie that he likes her. At the end of the episode, Leslie approaches Ben to hand him receipts and he kisses her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fowler |first=Matt |title=Parks and Recreation: \"Road Trip\" Review |publisher=IGN |date=May 13, 2011 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/116/1168143p1.html |accessdate=May 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/606yfCYjO?url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/116/1168143p1.html |archivedate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince he is staying in Pawnee permanently, Ben decides to move out of the motel where he has been living. Andy and April offer him a spare room in their house, since their previous roommate moved out and left the house to them. Although the two have been living by themselves for only a week, the house is a complete mess with no everyday items like plates or utensils available. Ben decides to teach a reluctant Andy and April how to properly live like adults.<ref>[[Jerry's Painting]]</ref>\n\nIn \"[[Road Trip (Parks and Recreation)|Road Trip]]\" Ben and Leslie are sent on a Road Trip to Indianapolis to state their case to host the State Little League Championship in Pawnee. With Leslie gone from work, Tom is hosting a game show called Know Ya Boo where he asks couples scandalous questions, and they have to guess what the other person said. He brings Jerry and Donna, and April and Andy, to practice, leaving Ron alone. A 3rd grade class is visiting City Hall on a field trip, and Ron is left to talk to one of them. He tells a girl, Lauren, about his views as a Libertarian. During Know Ya Boo, April and Andy get in a big fight because April's answer to her favorite band was not Andy's band. Andy gets upset and sells his guitar and essentially quits music. April then goes to Ann for relationship help to end her conflict with Andy. Leslie and Ben win and get to host the State Little League Championship in Pawnee, and they go out for a celebratory dinner. There, Ben tells Leslie he likes her, and Leslie confirms she likes him too, but Chris decides to crash their dinner, therefore interrupting their conversation. In the end of the episode, Ben ends up kissing Leslie and their secret relationship commences.\n\nIn \"[[The Bubble (Parks and Recreation)|The Bubble]]\", Leslie and Ben are officially dating, but they are keeping their relationship a secret due to a no-dating policy at work. They are enjoying what Leslie calls \"the bubble\", or the beginning of a relationship when everything is simple and fun. It is suddenly threatened, however, when Ben has a meeting with Leslie's mother Marlene, who wants Ben to approve the purchase of four new school buses despite a difficult budget season. Afraid of ruining the bubble, Leslie initially tells Ben she is not related to Marlene. Right before Ben's meeting, however, Leslie admits Marlene is her mother, making him nervous and causing him to capitulate to all of her demands during the meeting, which makes Marlene consider Ben weak. Leslie trains Ben for his next meeting with her mother. He impresses Marlene so much with his tough negotiation skills that she becomes flirtatious with him. An uncomfortable Ben tells Leslie they should tell her about their relationship, but Leslie does not want to lose the bubble. Fed up, Ben storms into Marlene's office and tells her that he is dating her daughter and asks her to keep it secret. Marlene laughs off the situation and tells Leslie that she approves of Ben.\n\nIn the season finale \"[[Li'l Sebastian]]\", Leslie and Ben continue their romance, but they have difficulty keeping it a secret. Ron finds out and warns them that Chris will fire them if he learns about it. As the city prepares for the memorial service for Li'l Sebastian, Pawnee's beloved celebrity miniature horse, Leslie and Ben are caught making out by a maintenance worker, so they send him home in exchange for his silence. Unfortunately, the worker had the propane for Li'l Sebastian's memorial flame, which results in later confusion behind the scenes, that Leslie and Ben struggle to fix throughout the night. Later, although the memorial turned out to be a success, things get even more complicated when Leslie is approached by scouts looking for potential candidates for elected office. They believe she would be a good candidate for upcoming city council seats, or possibly the mayoral position. With the expected increased media attention on her personal life, the scouts ask whether Leslie has any secret scandals in her life. She denies any such scandals exist, thus omitting her secret relationship with Ben, and the scouts promise to contact her about preparing an electoral run.<ref>[[Li'l Sebastian]]</ref>\n\n===Season Four===\nThough their relationship had become rather serious, Ben and Leslie are forced to break up to avoid a scandal which could derail Leslie's city council candidacy. Ben understands, giving Leslie a \"Knope 2012\" button he had made. He then starts helping Tom run his business Entertainment 720, where he is shocked at how much money Tom spends without getting any revenue. He also helps Tom charm Joan Callamezzo to try to get her book club to include Leslie's new book, but Joan gets drunk and hits on them. He and Leslie end up sharing lovelorn looks with each other.  Ben is dragged along to Tom and Donna's \"Treat Yo Self\", where he treats himself to a [[Batman]] costume and a good cry over his breakup with Leslie.\n\nWhile Leslie attempts to keep him in her life, Ben insists that he needs distance from her since being around Leslie is too difficult for him.  Leslie continually tries to spend time with Ben until, through the help of Ben and Ann, she sees that she has been ignoring what Ben wants and doing only what she wants.  Ben and Leslie meet at the [[Smallest Park (Parks and Recreation)|Smallest Park]], which is supposed to be their last project together.  Leslie apologizes and tells Ben that she will leave him alone if that is what he wants.  Ben responds that he does not want that but he thinks that it is for the best.  As Ben starts to leave, Leslie declares that she misses him like crazy and wants to be with him.  After she asks how he feels, Ben kisses Leslie and the relationship is reinstated.\n\nLater, they confess to Chris about their relationship, and he launches an investigation to check for any possible acts of corruption, as Ben is Leslie's superior. It turns out that in the season three finale, Ben and Leslie had bribed a maintenance worker to keep quiet about them after the worker witnessed them kissing. As that was a possible reason for termination, Leslie was ready to take full responsibility only to find that Ben resigned from his job in order to save hers.\n\nFollowing his termination, Ben takes some time to \"explore his interests\" which consists of him remaining in his house and attempting various hobbies like making [[calzone]]s and stop motion films. His appearance becomes unkempt and after a visit from Chris, he realizes that, despite convincing himself otherwise, he is unhappy without some sort of direction in his life. After Leslie's campaign flops at the ice rink, Ann resigns (eagerly) from being Leslie's campaign manager and Leslie asks Ben to run her campaign given his experience with local politics. Ben takes over the duties of running Leslie's campaign for city council and helps turn the campaign around, making it competitive with Bobby Newport's bid for city office.  Ben manages to secure the endorsement of Pawnee's retiring police chief and improve Leslie's likability at a bowling event (despite the spectacle of having punched a man who called Leslie 'a bitch').  In \"[[Dave Returns]]\", it is revealed that not only is Ben socially awkward around police officers, but he is afraid of them, saying \"I am not afraid of cops.  I have no reason to be.  I never break any laws ever because I'm deathly afraid of cops.\"\n\nTowards the end of the campaign, Ben is offered a job working for a congressional campaign in [[Washington, D.C.]].  Initially conflicted, as it would mean several months away from Pawnee, Ben is ultimately convinced by Leslie to take the job.\n\n===Season Five===\n[[Jonathan Banks]] and [[Glenne Headly]] guest starred as Ben's parents in the fifth season. He successfully runs a congressional campaign during the first five episodes of the season. When Ben returns to Pawnee, he proposes to Leslie, and they move into a house together. Later, Ben turns down multiple job offers in Pawnee to join Tom Haverford's company, Rent-a-Swag; concurrently, he ends up working for Sweetums, at a division dedicated to improving their public image by funding charities. He also takes on Andy as an assistant. Ben and Leslie throw a large event designed to help with fundraising for the Pawnee Commons instead of creating a wedding registry. During the event, Leslie tells Ben how much she hates the feeling of not being married to him.  Ben responds by saying that they should just get married that night. After two hours of frantically finishing last minute details, a ceremony ruined by a drunk Councilman Jamm, and bailing Ron out of jail, they hold the wedding in the Parks Department. In the episode titled \"Partridge\" Ben is invited to return to Partridge, his hometown where he was elected and failed as mayor at the age of 18, for a ceremony to give him the [[Freedom of the City|key to the city]]. Ben falls ill with [[Kidney stone disease|kidney stones]], and when Leslie goes to receive the key in his name, it is revealed to be one big joke to mock Ben for his failure as a mayor.\n\n===Season Six===\nAfter Leslie attacks Sweetums in a press statement, Ben is fired from his job with the company. He then takes on the accountant job he has accepted and declined three times prior. Shortly later though Chris offers him the Job of City Manager of Pawnee because Chris is leaving town and Ben accepts it, becoming the new City Manager of Pawnee and Leslie's boss as she returns to her job in the Parks and Recreation Department. At the end of the episode entitled \"Flu Season 2\" Ben has a fight with his father who sold their family lake house where Ben had many wonderful childhood memories. He realizes he wants to start a family with Leslie, when he returns home to tell Leslie, he discovers that she is pregnant with their first child. When visiting Dr. Saperstein, they realize she is having triplets.\n\n===Season Seven===\nBen remains city manager, and is planning the Pawnee Bicentennial. This, along with greatly improving the economy of Pawnee, gets him the award for Man of the Year. He and Leslie have triplets, two boys and one girl, whom they have named Stephen, Wesley, and Sonia. In ''The Johnny Karate Super Awesome Musical Explosion Show'', Ben was made a Knight of the [[Order of the British Empire]] by His Royal Excellence Lord Edgar Darby Covington, 14th Earl of Cornwall-Upon-Thames and 29th Baron of Hertfordshire. After being contacted by Jennifer Barkley, and with Leslie's full support, he decides to run for Congress in 2018. While campaigning, he earns IOW's Woman of the Year award for giving Leslie room to speak her mind instead of reading scripted speeches. Through a series of flash-forwards in the final episode, it is revealed that Ben's congressional campaign was successful and is now a representative from Indiana for the House of Representatives. In 2025, he and Leslie are both given the opportunity to run as Governor of Indiana, Ben ultimately decides to let Leslie run (which she wins). By 2048, it is implied that at least one of them has been elected President of the United States, with Ben wearing a flag lapel pin and being acknowledged first by someone who appeared to be a member of the Secret Service.\n\n==Development==\n[[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] departed from his leading role on the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] comedy television series ''[[Party Down]]'' to accept the role of Ben Wyatt on ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''.<ref name=\"Martin0304\">{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Denise |title='Party Down' star Adam Scott joins the cast of NBC's 'Parks and Recreation'; plus, more details on Rob Lowe |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 4, 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/party-down-star-adam-scott-joins-the-cast-of-nbcs-parks-and-recreation.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vTcUqY0B?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/party-down-star-adam-scott-joins-the-cast-of-nbcs-parks-and-recreation.html |archivedate=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Sepinwall0305\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title='Parks and Recreation' lands 'Party Down' star Adam Scott |work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |date=March 5, 2010 |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2010/03/parks_and_recreation_lands_par.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vTcXRMXB?url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2010/03/parks_and_recreation_lands_par.html |archivedate=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Parks and Recreation'' was one of Scott's favorite shows even before he took the role.<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |title=Interview: Adam Scott on leaving 'Party Down' and going to 'Parks and Recreation' |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=June 24, 2010 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/interview-adam-scott-on-leaving-party-down-and-going-to-parks-and-recreation |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv3f68Fu?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/interview-adam-scott-on-leaving-party-down-and-going-to-parks-and-recreation |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When he accepted a role on ''Parks and Recreation'', it was unclear whether ''Party Down'' would be renewed for a third season, and Scott said, \"I couldn't pass up the opportunity on ''Parks and Rec'' for a show that could possibly not exist anymore.\"<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" /> Although ''Party Down'' co-creator [[Rob Thomas (writer)|Rob Thomas]] said he believed the show could continue without Scott, and that the actor would continue to make guest appearances on the show,<ref name=\"Sepinwall0305\" /> ''Party Down'' was cancelled just three months after Scott departed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ausiello |first=Michael |author-link=Michael Ausiello |title=Breaking: Starz cancels 'Party Down' and 'Gravity' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 30, 2010 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/06/30/breaking-starz-cancels-party-down-gravity/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SFp186p?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/06/30/breaking-starz-cancels-party-down-gravity/ |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Series co-creator [[Michael Schur]] said when the Ben Wyatt character was conceived, Scott was considered the \"dream scenario\" casting choice.<ref name=\"Stanhope0304\">{{Cite news |last=Stanhope |first=Kate |title=Party Down's Adam Scott Joins Parks and Recreation Cast |date=March 4, 2010 |work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> As part of Scott's contract with the series, he also signed a [[first-look deal]] to develop television projects for NBC.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" />\n\nScott first appeared in ''Parks and Recreation'' starting in the penultimate second-season episode, \"[[The Master Plan (Parks and Recreation)|The Master Plan]]\", the same episode Rob Lowe joined the regular cast as Chris Traeger.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" /><ref name=\"Stanhope0304\" /> The idea of a character trying to rebuild a government career following a humiliating public failure was one of the original ideas for the protagonist of ''Parks and Recreation''. The idea was originally abandoned in favor of Leslie Knope's character, but those early ideas were ultimately incorporated into Ben Wyatt.<ref name=\"SchurComm\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last=Snierson |first=Dan |year=2011 |title=The 101 Reasons We Love Parks and Recreation |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=1142 |pages=43\u201349}}</ref> Ben's role as a state auditor, and Pawnee's subsequent budget problems, were conceived from [[Late-2000s recession|global economic crisis]] and news reports about government services getting shut down around the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Denise |title='Parks and Recreation': Mike Schur tells us why Paul Schneider is leaving the show, plus more details on Adam Scott and Rob Lowe |date=March 12, 2010 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/parks-and-recreation-mike-schur-talks-about-why-paul-schneider-is-exiting-the-show-plus-more-details.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv3EN0W8?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/parks-and-recreation-mike-schur-talks-about-why-paul-schneider-is-exiting-the-show-plus-more-details.html |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott described his character as \"someone who jumped in on a moving train\" in trying to integrate with the other characters.<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" /> Ben was expected to become a love interest for Leslie Knope from his earliest conception.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |title=Producer: Paul Schneider Leaving Parks for Movie Career |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> In addition to the growing relationship between Leslie and Ben, one of the biggest story arcs for season three was Ben's growing love of the city of Pawnee, which coincided with his romantic feelings for Leslie. Schur described Ben's character as one who never had a firm sense of home due to the excessive amount of traveling with his job, but who gradually grew to appreciate Pawnee due to the optimism and enthusiasm Leslie has for her job.<ref>{{cite news|last=Snierson |first=Dan |title='Parks and Recreation' scoop: Amy Poehler and co-creator Mike Schur dish on Leslie's big gamble, romantic possibilities, and tonight's episode 'The Flu' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 27, 2011 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/27/parks-and-recreation-amy-poehler-the-flu/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zWVGbvw5?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/27/parks-and-recreation-amy-poehler-the-flu |archivedate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe character received extremely positive reviews from critics and audiences alike.\n\n[[Alan Sepinwall]] of [[HitFix]] called Scott one of the \"rare but special\" actors who can be both \"the sane and deadpan center of the madness, but can also go convincingly, amusingly mad\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title=Review: 'Parks and Recreation' - 'Media Blitz': Ice town clown rebounds? |publisher=HitFix |date=February 17, 2011 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-media-blitz-ice-town-clown-rebounds |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zcKnWDEE?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-media-blitz-ice-town-clown-rebounds |archivedate=June 21, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' writer David Hinckley praised Scott's addition to the ''Parks and Recreation'' cast, claiming he \"gets more of a character here than he does on Starz's entertaining ''Party Down'' and makes the best of it\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinckley |first=David |title='Parks and Recreation' adds Rob Lowe and Adam Scott for storyline and 'meat' effect |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |date=May 13, 2010 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/05/13/2010-05-13_parks_and_recreation_adds_rob_lowe_and_adam_scott_for_storyline_and_meat_effect.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yZD5dTVa?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-05-13/entertainment/27064226_1_aubrey-plaza-parks-starz |archivedate=May 10, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott received particular praise for his performance in \"Media Blitz\", in which his awkward and panicked responses to media inquiries about his past led to what reviewers considered more outwardly comedic opportunities for the character, compared to his usual [[Double act|straight man]] role.<ref name=\"Porter0218\" /><ref name=\"Sundermann0218\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Poniewozik |first=James |author-link=James Poniewozik |title=Parks and Recreation Watch: Escape from Ice Town |date=February 18, 2011 |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2011/02/18/parks-and-recreation-watch-escape-from-ice-town/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zjS1nJwI?url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2011/02/18/parks-and-recreation-watch-escape-from-ice-town |archivedate=June 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Several reviewers mentioned that Ben Wyatt closely resembled Scott's character on ''Party Down'', Henry Pollard. Ben's character is a politician who found great success at a young age, then suffered a downfall. Henry's character is an actor who became a caterer after his acting career declined.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /><ref name=\"Sepinwall\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |publisher=[[HitFix]] |title='Parks and Recreation' - 'The Master Plan': Whoomp! (There it is) |date=May 13, 2010 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-the-master-plan-i-am-20-going-on-21 |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQJ4w1Pa?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-the-master-plan-i-am-20-going-on-21 |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott himself has said that he feels they are \"vastly different characters and circumstances.\"<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Parks and Recreation}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Ben Wyatt (''Parks and Recreation'')}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wyatt, Ben}}\n[[Category:Parks and Recreation characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Fictional government officials]]\n[[Category:Fictional mayors]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Fictional Democrats (United States)]]\n[[Category:Fictional members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Fictional accountants]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character from Parks and Recreation}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = '''Ben Wyatt'''\n| series             = [[Parks and Recreation]]\n| image              = [[File:Ben Wyatt Parks & Rec.jpg|235px]]\n| caption            = \n| portrayer          = [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]]\n| first              = \"[[The Master Plan (Parks and Recreation)|The Master Plan]]\"\n| last               = \"[[One Last Ride]]\"\n| alias              = \n| nickname           = Benji, Angelo, Jello-shot, J-shot, Ice-town, Ice-clown, Eagle Two\n| occupation         = [[First Gentleman of the United States]] (implied)<br>[[United States House of Representatives|Member of the U.S. House of Representatives]] from Indiana's 9th District <br>  City Manager of Pawnee, Indiana <br> President of the Sweetums Foundation (former) <br> [[Chief financial officer|CFO]] of Rent-a-Swag (former) <br> [[Campaign manager|Campaign Manager]]<br> Deputy [[City Manager]] of Pawnee, Indiana (former) <br> [[Indiana State Auditor]] (former) <br> [[Mayor]] of Partridge, Minnesota (impeached) <br> Board Game Designer\n| spouse             = [[Leslie Knope]] (m. 2013)\n| family             = Julia Wyatt (mother)<br>Steve Wyatt (father)<br>Stephanie Wyatt (sister)<br>Henry Wyatt (brother)\n| relatives          = Georgia Wyatt (niece)\n| affiliation        = [[Carleton College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA in Political Science]])\n| children           = Westley Knope-Wyatt (son) <br> Stephen Knope-Wyatt (son) <br> Sonia Knope-Wyatt (daughter)\n}}\n'''Benjamin Wyatt''' is a fictional character portrayed by [[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] in the TV series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''. The character guest starred in two episodes of [[Parks and Recreation (season 2)|season two]] and was upgraded to a series regular in [[Parks and Recreation (season 3)|season three]]. Ben is a [[state auditor]] who comes into [[Pawnee (Parks and Recreation)|Pawnee]] with [[Chris Traeger]] to evaluate the town's funds at the end of the second season. Ben began dating [[Leslie Knope]] in the [[Parks and Recreation (season 3)|season three]] episode \"[[Road Trip (Parks and Recreation)|Road Trip]]\" and married her in the [[Parks and Recreation (season 5)|season five]] episode \"Leslie and Ben.\" In the [[Parks and Recreation (season 7)|season seven]] episode \"2017\" Ben was named Pawnee's Woman of the Year for 2017. It is implied that Leslie later became the [[President of the United States]] making him the First Gentleman.\nBen Wyatt is a lover of all things [[calzones]], [[sci-fi]], and ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.\n\n==Character biography==\nBen is from [[Partridge Township, Pine County, Minnesota|Partridge, Minnesota]]. When he was 18, he ran for [[mayor]] and won on the strength of, in his words, \"anti-establishment voter rebellion.\" However, being so inexperienced, he quickly ran the town's finances into the ground mainly due to the construction of a winter sports complex called \"Ice Town\". He was then impeached after two months in office.<ref>{{cite news|last=Monroe |first=Justin |title=Video: Vote 'Parks and Recreation' Star Adam Scott For Mayor Of NYC |work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |date=April 14, 2011 |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/04/video-vote-parks-and-recreation-star-adam-scott-mayor-nyc |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SJuEdre?url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/04/video-vote-parks-and-recreation-star-adam-scott-mayor-nyc |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\">{{cite news |last=VanDerWerff |first=Emily |title=Parks and Recreation: \"The Master Plan\" |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=May 14, 2010 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-master-plan,41155/ |accessdate=October 6, 2019|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQJ9hUx5?url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-master-plan%2C41155/ |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His complete blunder bankrupted the town, caused its unemployment rate to hit 30%, and led to the newspaper headline \"Ice Town Costs Ice Clown His Town Crown.\"<ref name=\"Sundermann0121\">{{cite web|last=Sundermann |first=Eric |title='Parks and Recreation' Season Premiere: Go Big or Go Home |publisher=Hollywood.com |date=January 21, 2011 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Season_Premiere_Go_Big_or_Go_Home/7751628 |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SKDofGt?url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Season_Premiere_Go_Big_or_Go_Home/7751628 |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Ben attended [[Carleton College]], where he was the host and DJ for a [[swing music]] college radio show called Zoot Suit Wyatt, a reference to the swing song \"[[Zoot Suit Riot (song)|Zoot Suit Riot]]\" (1997).<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://apps.carleton.edu/news/carleton_in_the_media/?story_id=1120452|title=NBC's \"Parks and Recreation\" mentions Carleton in \"Prom Planning\"|publisher= [[Carleton College]] |date=April 4, 2014|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref> After becoming an accountant, he and [[Chris Traeger]] assumed the nicknames Butch Count-sidy and the Sum-dance Kid, with the names referencing the outlaws [[Butch Cassidy]] and the [[Sundance Kid]] as well as being accounting puns.\n\nBen is very serious, mature and work-oriented, and usually does not seem fazed by much of the immature, eccentric behavior from some of the other members of the Pawnee Parks and Recreation Department, primarily [[Tom Haverford]], [[Leslie Knope]], and [[Andy Dwyer]]. Ben is often teased by Tom (and, early on, Leslie as well) for his affinity for, references to and vast knowledge in ''[[Star Wars]]'', ''[[Lord of the Rings]]'', ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' and other things considered to be \"nerdy\". His love for calzones is also a recurring joke in the series.  Ben is shown to have a hard time socializing, and connecting with people by having work as his main focus. During season six when he was jobless for a week, he created a game called ''The Cones of Dunshire''. The game became very popular, which he realized while visiting San Francisco. He was angry that he did not copyright it, but later in the show, one of his former coworkers surprises him with the copyright papers.\n\n===Season Two===\nWhen Ben comes to Pawnee, he immediately clashes with Leslie, as she yells at him three consecutive times for his seemingly callous attitude towards firing people and slashing her department's budget. However, when he asks her out for a beer, they begin to show respect for one another. He shares his past as the mayor of Partridge, and that he became a state auditor to prove he can be responsible and eventually run for office again.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /><ref name=\"SchurComm\">{{cite video | people=[[Michael Schur|Schur, Michael]]|date=2010|title=Parks and Recreation: Season Two: \"The Master Plan\" |type = Audio commentary DVD|publisher=[[Universal Studios Home Entertainment]]}}</ref> Their new friendship turns sour when Ben and Chris reveal that the town is virtually out of funds and the government will have to be shut down until further notice.<ref name=\"Kandell0607\">{{cite news|last=Kandell |first=Steve |title=''Parks and Recreation'' Recap: Shutdown |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=May 21, 2010 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/05/parks_and_recreation_recap_shu.html |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQM8WKyX?url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2010/05/parks_and_recreation_recap_shu.html |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDespite the seriousness of the problems, Chris presents the situation in an extremely positive light and tries to make all the city hall employees around him happy, leaving the hard decisions and delivery of bad news up to Ben; meaning, Chris is the good cop and Ben is the bad cop in this partnership.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /> Chris and Ben form a budget task force, consisting of several government employees including Ron. When Ron accidentally reveals that Leslie was trying to set up an annual children's concert that was supposed to be canceled on Lot 48 behind Ann's house, Ben tries to shut it down. However, after seeing the effort Leslie put into it, which included having the equipment donated from local vendors, he pays the entertainer Freddy Spaghetti to come back after he booked another event, getting back on Leslie's good side. Ben is also surprised, but quietly pleased when Ron authorizes Leslie to take his place on the budget task force.<ref name=\"Kandell0607\" />\n\n===Season Three===\nWhen the government shutdown ends, Ben informs the department that due to the shoestring budget, they will only be on maintenance for the time being. Ben suspects that Leslie is trying to have Ann convince Chris to distribute more funds to the department and confirms his suspicions when he crashes their date at the same time Leslie crashes it, but Ben decides to let it play out. While at a gay club, Ben mentions the failure of the Ice Town project, showing that he used to be just as ambitious as Leslie, but Leslie gives him credit for trying. Ben listens to Leslie's presentation regarding the Pawnee Harvest Festival idea that will allow them to do their jobs properly and bring funds into the department. When Ben asks what will happen if it does not bring in funds, Leslie says they can shut down the department, and Ben allows them to go forth with the festival.<ref name=\"Sundermann0121\" />\n\nBen assists Leslie with the festival preparations, and is thoroughly impressed when she gives a flawless presentation despite being stricken with the flu.<ref>{{cite news |last=Heisler |first=Steve |title=Parks and Recreation: \"The Flu\" |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=January 27, 2011 |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-flu,50577/ |accessdate=January 29, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SL8Ieh0?url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-flu%2C50577/ |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When Leslie and Ben try to ask the police force to handle security for the festival, Ben is shown not to have very strong social skills, although in this case it could be attributed to the fact that he does not understand Pawnee as well as Leslie.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |title=Review: 'Parks and Recreation' - 'Ron & Tammy II': Rock the cradle of love? |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-ron-tammy-ii-rock-the-cradle-of-love |accessdate=February 13, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQNXEFBc?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-ron-tammy-ii-rock-the-cradle-of-love |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He and Leslie continue to build a strong friendship over their development of the Harvest Festival, and it is implied he starts to show romantic interest in her when he inquires of the police chief about her relationship with Dave. He also becomes better friends with Tom, supporting him when he is rejected by a cologne magnate, although Tom does his fair share of ribbing Ben.<ref name=\"Gilbert0319\">{{cite news |last=Gilbert |first=Megan |title=Parks and Recreation recap: 'Harvest Festival' |work=[[Punchline Magazine]] |date=March 19, 2011 |url=http://www.laughspin.com/2011/03/19/parks-and-recreation-recap-harvest-festival/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318062021/http://www.laughspin.com/2011/03/19/parks-and-recreation-recap-harvest-festival/ |archivedate=March 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nWhile doing the media blitz for the festival, he is continuously asked about his disastrous tenure as mayor of Partridge. After freezing up at the majority of questions asked, he then goes on a furious tirade at a later interview, prompting businesses to pull their sponsorships at the festival and putting the parks department in jeopardy. At the last interview at ''Pawnee Today'', Ben finally stands his ground, stating that everyone does stupid things when they were teenagers and that he has since saved at least five cities from bankruptcy as an auditor.<ref name=\"Porter0218\">{{cite web|last=Porter |first=Rick |title='Parks and Recreation': Welcome to Pawnee, Ben |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |date=February 18, 2011 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/parks-and-recreation-welcome-to-pawnee-ben.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zcQC1gYD?url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/02/parks-and-recreation-welcome-to-pawnee-ben.html |archivedate=June 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Sundermann0218\">{{cite news |last=Sundermann |first=Eric |title='Parks and Recreation' Recap: Media Blitz |publisher=Hollywood.com |date=February 18, 2011 |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/Parks_and_Recreation_Recap_Media_Blitz/7763406 |accessdate=July 25, 2011}}</ref> During the festival itself, a series of catastrophes leads Ben to feel he is cursed and leave the festival, returning later to admit he is not over his past. Leslie assures him that he is as responsible for the festival's success as she is, and has the local Native American chief Ken Hotate perform a fake ceremony to remove his \"curse.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kandell |first=Steve |title=''Parks and Recreation'' Recap: Awesomesauce! |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=March 18, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/parks_and_recreation_recap.html |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zZbo8e1w?url=http://nymag.com/daily/entertainment/2011/03/parks_and_recreation_recap.html |archivedate=June 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the conclusion of the festival, Chris is installed as interim city manager of Pawnee, and offers Ben a job as assistant city manager, which he eventually accepts. It is implied that he made the decision to be closer to Leslie and that he and Leslie are attracted to each other,<ref>{{cite news|last=Busis |first=Hillary |title='Parks and Recreation': I now pronounce you man and... wait, seriously? |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=April 15, 2011 |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/04/15/parks-and-recreation-april-andy-wedding/ |accessdate=April 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ze9bHkSd?url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/04/15/parks-and-recreation-april-andy-wedding/ |archivedate=June 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but a new policy of Chris's forbids city employees to date each other and has halted any potential relationship. But, after being assigned to a road trip that would cause them to be alone, Ben tells Leslie that he likes her. At the end of the episode, Leslie approaches Ben to hand him receipts and he kisses her.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fowler |first=Matt |title=Parks and Recreation: \"Road Trip\" Review |publisher=IGN |date=May 13, 2011 |url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/116/1168143p1.html |accessdate=May 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/606yfCYjO?url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/116/1168143p1.html |archivedate=July 12, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSince he is staying in Pawnee permanently, Ben decides to move out of the motel where he has been living. Andy and April offer him a spare room in their house, since their previous roommate moved out and left the house to them. Although the two have been living by themselves for only a week, the house is a complete mess with no everyday items like plates or utensils available. Ben decides to teach a reluctant Andy and April how to properly live like adults.<ref>[[Jerry's Painting]]</ref>\n\nIn \"[[Road Trip (Parks and Recreation)|Road Trip]]\" Ben and Leslie are sent on a Road Trip to Indianapolis to state their case to host the State Little League Championship in Pawnee. With Leslie gone from work, Tom is hosting a game show called Know Ya Boo where he asks couples scandalous questions, and they have to guess what the other person said. He brings Jerry and Donna, and April and Andy, to practice, leaving Ron alone. A 3rd grade class is visiting City Hall on a field trip, and Ron is left to talk to one of them. He tells a girl, Lauren, about his views as a Libertarian. During Know Ya Boo, April and Andy get in a big fight because April's answer to her favorite band was not Andy's band. Andy gets upset and sells his guitar and essentially quits music. April then goes to Ann for relationship help to end her conflict with Andy. Leslie and Ben win and get to host the State Little League Championship in Pawnee, and they go out for a celebratory dinner. There, Ben tells Leslie he likes her, and Leslie confirms she likes him too, but Chris decides to crash their dinner, therefore interrupting their conversation. In the end of the episode, Ben ends up kissing Leslie and their secret relationship commences.\n\nIn \"[[The Bubble (Parks and Recreation)|The Bubble]]\", Leslie and Ben are officially dating, but they are keeping their relationship a secret due to a no-dating policy at work. They are enjoying what Leslie calls \"the bubble\", or the beginning of a relationship when everything is simple and fun. It is suddenly threatened, however, when Ben has a meeting with Leslie's mother Marlene, who wants Ben to approve the purchase of four new school buses despite a difficult budget season. Afraid of ruining the bubble, Leslie initially tells Ben she is not related to Marlene. Right before Ben's meeting, however, Leslie admits Marlene is her mother, making him nervous and causing him to capitulate to all of her demands during the meeting, which makes Marlene consider Ben weak. Leslie trains Ben for his next meeting with her mother. He impresses Marlene so much with his tough negotiation skills that she becomes flirtatious with him. An uncomfortable Ben tells Leslie they should tell her about their relationship, but Leslie does not want to lose the bubble. Fed up, Ben storms into Marlene's office and tells her that he is dating her daughter and asks her to keep it secret. Marlene laughs off the situation and tells Leslie that she approves of Ben.\n\nIn the season finale \"[[Li'l Sebastian]]\", Leslie and Ben continue their romance, but they have difficulty keeping it a secret. Ron finds out and warns them that Chris will fire them if he learns about it. As the city prepares for the memorial service for Li'l Sebastian, Pawnee's beloved celebrity miniature horse, Leslie and Ben are caught making out by a maintenance worker, so they send him home in exchange for his silence. Unfortunately, the worker had the propane for Li'l Sebastian's memorial flame, which results in later confusion behind the scenes, that Leslie and Ben struggle to fix throughout the night. Later, although the memorial turned out to be a success, things get even more complicated when Leslie is approached by scouts looking for potential candidates for elected office. They believe she would be a good candidate for upcoming city council seats, or possibly the mayoral position. With the expected increased media attention on her personal life, the scouts ask whether Leslie has any secret scandals in her life. She denies any such scandals exist, thus omitting her secret relationship with Ben, and the scouts promise to contact her about preparing an electoral run.<ref>[[Li'l Sebastian]]</ref>\n\n===Season Four===\nThough their relationship had become rather serious, Ben and Leslie are forced to break up to avoid a scandal which could derail Leslie's city council candidacy. Ben understands, giving Leslie a \"Knope 2012\" button he had made. He then starts helping Tom run his business Entertainment 720, where he is shocked at how much money Tom spends without getting any revenue. He also helps Tom charm Joan Callamezzo to try to get her book club to include Leslie's new book, but Joan gets drunk and hits on them. He and Leslie end up sharing lovelorn looks with each other.  Ben is dragged along to Tom and Donna's \"Treat Yo Self\", where he treats himself to a [[Batman]] costume and a good cry over his breakup with Leslie.\n\nWhile Leslie attempts to keep him in her life, Ben insists that he needs distance from her since being around Leslie is too difficult for him.  Leslie continually tries to spend time with Ben until, through the help of Ben and Ann, she sees that she has been ignoring what Ben wants and doing only what she wants.  Ben and Leslie meet at the [[Smallest Park (Parks and Recreation)|Smallest Park]], which is supposed to be their last project together.  Leslie apologizes and tells Ben that she will leave him alone if that is what he wants.  Ben responds that he does not want that but he thinks that it is for the best.  As Ben starts to leave, Leslie declares that she misses him like crazy and wants to be with him.  After she asks how he feels, Ben kisses Leslie and the relationship is reinstated.\n\nLater, they confess to Chris about their relationship, and he launches an investigation to check for any possible acts of corruption, as Ben is Leslie's superior. It turns out that in the season three finale, Ben and Leslie had bribed a maintenance worker to keep quiet about them after the worker witnessed them kissing. As that was a possible reason for termination, Leslie was ready to take full responsibility only to find that Ben resigned from his job in order to save hers.\n\nFollowing his termination, Ben takes some time to \"explore his interests\" which consists of him remaining in his house and attempting various hobbies like making [[calzone]]s and stop motion films. His appearance becomes unkempt and after a visit from Chris, he realizes that, despite convincing himself otherwise, he is unhappy without some sort of direction in his life. After Leslie's campaign flops at the ice rink, Ann resigns (eagerly) from being Leslie's campaign manager and Leslie asks Ben to run her campaign given his experience with local politics. Ben takes over the duties of running Leslie's campaign for city council and helps turn the campaign around, making it competitive with Bobby Newport's bid for city office.  Ben manages to secure the endorsement of Pawnee's retiring police chief and improve Leslie's likability at a bowling event (despite the spectacle of having punched a man who called Leslie 'a bitch').  In \"[[Dave Returns]]\", it is revealed that not only is Ben socially awkward around police officers, but he is afraid of them, saying \"I am not afraid of cops.  I have no reason to be.  I never break any laws ever because I'm deathly afraid of cops.\"\n\nTowards the end of the campaign, Ben is offered a job working for a congressional campaign in [[Washington, D.C.]].  Initially conflicted, as it would mean several months away from Pawnee, Ben is ultimately convinced by Leslie to take the job.\n\n===Season Five===\n[[Jonathan Banks]] and [[Glenne Headly]] guest starred as Ben's parents in the fifth season. He successfully runs a congressional campaign during the first five episodes of the season. When Ben returns to Pawnee, he proposes to Leslie, and they move into a house together. Later, Ben turns down multiple job offers in Pawnee to join Tom Haverford's company, Rent-a-Swag; concurrently, he ends up working for Sweetums, at a division dedicated to improving their public image by funding charities. He also takes on Andy as an assistant. Ben and Leslie throw a large event designed to help with fundraising for the Pawnee Commons instead of creating a wedding registry. During the event, Leslie tells Ben how much she hates the feeling of not being married to him.  Ben responds by saying that they should just get married that night. After two hours of frantically finishing last minute details, a ceremony ruined by a drunk Councilman Jamm, and bailing Ron out of jail, they hold the wedding in the Parks Department. In the episode titled \"Partridge\" Ben is invited to return to Partridge, his hometown where he was elected and failed as mayor at the age of 18, for a ceremony to give him the [[Freedom of the City|key to the city]]. Ben falls ill with [[Kidney stone disease|kidney stones]], and when Leslie goes to receive the key in his name, it is revealed to be one big joke to mock Ben for his failure as a mayor.\n\n===Season Six===\nAfter Leslie attacks Sweetums in a press statement, Ben is fired from his job with the company. He then takes on the accountant job he has accepted and declined three times prior. Shortly later though Chris offers him the Job of City Manager of Pawnee because Chris is leaving town and Ben accepts it, becoming the new City Manager of Pawnee and Leslie's boss as she returns to her job in the Parks and Recreation Department. At the end of the episode entitled \"Flu Season 2\" Ben has a fight with his father who sold their family lake house where Ben had many wonderful childhood memories. He realizes he wants to start a family with Leslie, when he returns home to tell Leslie, he discovers that she is pregnant with their first child. When visiting Dr. Saperstein, they realize she is having triplets.\n\n===Season Seven===\nBen remains city manager, and is planning the Pawnee Bicentennial. This, along with greatly improving the economy of Pawnee, gets him the award for Man of the Year. He and Leslie have triplets, two boys and one girl, whom they have named Stephen, Wesley, and Sonia. In ''The Johnny Karate Super Awesome Musical Explosion Show'', Ben was made a Knight of the [[Order of the British Empire]] by His Royal Excellence Lord Edgar Darby Covington, 14th Earl of Cornwall-Upon-Thames and 29th Baron of Hertfordshire. After being contacted by Jennifer Barkley, and with Leslie's full support, he decides to run for Congress in 2018. While campaigning, he earns IOW's Woman of the Year award for giving Leslie room to speak her mind instead of reading scripted speeches. Through a series of flash-forwards in the final episode, it is revealed that Ben's congressional campaign was successful and is now a representative from Indiana for the House of Representatives. In 2025, he and Leslie are both given the opportunity to run as Governor of Indiana, Ben ultimately decides to let Leslie run (which she wins). By 2048, it is implied that at least one of them has been elected President of the United States, with Ben wearing a flag lapel pin and being acknowledged first by someone who appeared to be a member of the Secret Service.\n\n==Development==\n[[Adam Scott (actor)|Adam Scott]] departed from his leading role on the [[Starz (TV channel)|Starz]] comedy television series ''[[Party Down]]'' to accept the role of Ben Wyatt on ''[[Parks and Recreation]]''.<ref name=\"Martin0304\">{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Denise |title='Party Down' star Adam Scott joins the cast of NBC's 'Parks and Recreation'; plus, more details on Rob Lowe |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 4, 2010 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/party-down-star-adam-scott-joins-the-cast-of-nbcs-parks-and-recreation.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vTcUqY0B?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/party-down-star-adam-scott-joins-the-cast-of-nbcs-parks-and-recreation.html |archivedate=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Sepinwall0305\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title='Parks and Recreation' lands 'Party Down' star Adam Scott |work=[[The Star-Ledger]] |date=March 5, 2010 |url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2010/03/parks_and_recreation_lands_par.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vTcXRMXB?url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2010/03/parks_and_recreation_lands_par.html |archivedate=January 4, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''Parks and Recreation'' was one of Scott's favorite shows even before he took the role.<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |title=Interview: Adam Scott on leaving 'Party Down' and going to 'Parks and Recreation' |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=June 24, 2010 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/interview-adam-scott-on-leaving-party-down-and-going-to-parks-and-recreation |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv3f68Fu?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/interview-adam-scott-on-leaving-party-down-and-going-to-parks-and-recreation |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When he accepted a role on ''Parks and Recreation'', it was unclear whether ''Party Down'' would be renewed for a third season, and Scott said, \"I couldn't pass up the opportunity on ''Parks and Rec'' for a show that could possibly not exist anymore.\"<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" /> Although ''Party Down'' co-creator [[Rob Thomas (writer)|Rob Thomas]] said he believed the show could continue without Scott, and that the actor would continue to make guest appearances on the show,<ref name=\"Sepinwall0305\" /> ''Party Down'' was cancelled just three months after Scott departed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ausiello |first=Michael |author-link=Michael Ausiello |title=Breaking: Starz cancels 'Party Down' and 'Gravity' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 30, 2010 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/06/30/breaking-starz-cancels-party-down-gravity/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/60SFp186p?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/06/30/breaking-starz-cancels-party-down-gravity/ |archivedate=July 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Series co-creator [[Michael Schur]] said when the Ben Wyatt character was conceived, Scott was considered the \"dream scenario\" casting choice.<ref name=\"Stanhope0304\">{{Cite news |last=Stanhope |first=Kate |title=Party Down's Adam Scott Joins Parks and Recreation Cast |date=March 4, 2010 |work=[[TV Guide]]}}</ref> As part of Scott's contract with the series, he also signed a [[first-look deal]] to develop television projects for NBC.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" />\n\nScott first appeared in ''Parks and Recreation'' starting in the penultimate second-season episode, \"[[The Master Plan (Parks and Recreation)|The Master Plan]]\", the same episode Rob Lowe joined the regular cast as Chris Traeger.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" /><ref name=\"Stanhope0304\" /> The idea of a character trying to rebuild a government career following a humiliating public failure was one of the original ideas for the protagonist of ''Parks and Recreation''. The idea was originally abandoned in favor of Leslie Knope's character, but those early ideas were ultimately incorporated into Ben Wyatt.<ref name=\"SchurComm\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last=Snierson |first=Dan |year=2011 |title=The 101 Reasons We Love Parks and Recreation |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=1142 |pages=43\u201349}}</ref> Ben's role as a state auditor, and Pawnee's subsequent budget problems, were conceived from [[Late-2000s recession|global economic crisis]] and news reports about government services getting shut down around the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin |first=Denise |title='Parks and Recreation': Mike Schur tells us why Paul Schneider is leaving the show, plus more details on Adam Scott and Rob Lowe |date=March 12, 2010 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/parks-and-recreation-mike-schur-talks-about-why-paul-schneider-is-exiting-the-show-plus-more-details.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5vv3EN0W8?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2010/03/parks-and-recreation-mike-schur-talks-about-why-paul-schneider-is-exiting-the-show-plus-more-details.html |archivedate=January 22, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott described his character as \"someone who jumped in on a moving train\" in trying to integrate with the other characters.<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" /> Ben was expected to become a love interest for Leslie Knope from his earliest conception.<ref name=\"Martin0304\" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |title=Producer: Paul Schneider Leaving Parks for Movie Career |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> In addition to the growing relationship between Leslie and Ben, one of the biggest story arcs for season three was Ben's growing love of the city of Pawnee, which coincided with his romantic feelings for Leslie. Schur described Ben's character as one who never had a firm sense of home due to the excessive amount of traveling with his job, but who gradually grew to appreciate Pawnee due to the optimism and enthusiasm Leslie has for her job.<ref>{{cite news|last=Snierson |first=Dan |title='Parks and Recreation' scoop: Amy Poehler and co-creator Mike Schur dish on Leslie's big gamble, romantic possibilities, and tonight's episode 'The Flu' |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 27, 2011 |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/27/parks-and-recreation-amy-poehler-the-flu/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zWVGbvw5?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2011/01/27/parks-and-recreation-amy-poehler-the-flu |archivedate=June 18, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe character received extremely positive reviews from critics and audiences alike.\n\n[[Alan Sepinwall]] of [[HitFix]] called Scott one of the \"rare but special\" actors who can be both \"the sane and deadpan center of the madness, but can also go convincingly, amusingly mad\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title=Review: 'Parks and Recreation' - 'Media Blitz': Ice town clown rebounds? |publisher=HitFix |date=February 17, 2011 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-media-blitz-ice-town-clown-rebounds |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zcKnWDEE?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-media-blitz-ice-town-clown-rebounds |archivedate=June 21, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' writer David Hinckley praised Scott's addition to the ''Parks and Recreation'' cast, claiming he \"gets more of a character here than he does on Starz's entertaining ''Party Down'' and makes the best of it\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinckley |first=David |title='Parks and Recreation' adds Rob Lowe and Adam Scott for storyline and 'meat' effect |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |date=May 13, 2010 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/2010/05/13/2010-05-13_parks_and_recreation_adds_rob_lowe_and_adam_scott_for_storyline_and_meat_effect.html |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yZD5dTVa?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-05-13/entertainment/27064226_1_aubrey-plaza-parks-starz |archivedate=May 10, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott received particular praise for his performance in \"Media Blitz\", in which his awkward and panicked responses to media inquiries about his past led to what reviewers considered more outwardly comedic opportunities for the character, compared to his usual [[Double act|straight man]] role.<ref name=\"Porter0218\" /><ref name=\"Sundermann0218\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=Poniewozik |first=James |author-link=James Poniewozik |title=Parks and Recreation Watch: Escape from Ice Town |date=February 18, 2011 |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2011/02/18/parks-and-recreation-watch-escape-from-ice-town/ |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zjS1nJwI?url=http://tunedin.blogs.time.com/2011/02/18/parks-and-recreation-watch-escape-from-ice-town |archivedate=June 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Several reviewers mentioned that Ben Wyatt closely resembled Scott's character on ''Party Down'', Henry Pollard. Ben's character is a politician who found great success at a young age, then suffered a downfall. Henry's character is an actor who became a caterer after his acting career declined.<ref name=\"VanDerWerff0514\" /><ref name=\"Sepinwall\">{{cite news|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |author-link=Alan Sepinwall |publisher=[[HitFix]] |title='Parks and Recreation' - 'The Master Plan': Whoomp! (There it is) |date=May 13, 2010 |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-the-master-plan-i-am-20-going-on-21 |accessdate=July 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5zQJ4w1Pa?url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/parks-and-recreation-the-master-plan-i-am-20-going-on-21 |archivedate=June 14, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Scott himself has said that he feels they are \"vastly different characters and circumstances.\"<ref name=\"Sepinwall0624\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Parks and Recreation}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Ben Wyatt (''Parks and Recreation'')}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wyatt, Ben}}\n[[Category:Parks and Recreation characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2010]]\n[[Category:Fictional government officials]]\n[[Category:Fictional mayors]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Fictional Democrats (United States)]]\n[[Category:Fictional members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Fictional accountants]]\n", "name_user": "2601:244:5100:a0:f979:969d:190d:db46", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Wyatt_(Parks_and_Recreation)"}
{"title_page": "Blake Bortles", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name=Blake Bortles\n| image=20140914 Blake Bortles.jpg\n| image_size=\n| alt=\n| caption=Bortles with the Jaguars in 2014\n| current_team=Free Agent\n| number= \n| position=[[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1992|04|28}}\n| birth_place=[[Altamonte Springs, Florida]]\n| height_ft=6\n| height_in=5\n| weight_lbs=236\n| high_school=[[Oviedo High School|Oviedo]] ([[Oviedo, Florida]])\n| college=[[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n| draftyear=2014\n| draftround=1\n| draftpick=3\n| pastteams=\n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2014}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status=\n| highlights=\n* AFC South Champion (2017)\n* [[American Athletic Conference football individual awards#Offensive Player of the Year|AAC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2013)\n* First-team All-[[American Athletic Conference|AAC]] (2013)\n* Second-team All-[[Conference USA]] (2012)\n| statseason=2019\n| statweek=\n| statlabel1=Completion %\n| statvalue1=59.3\n| statlabel2=[[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue2=103\u201375\n| statlabel3=Passing yards\n| statvalue3=17,649\n| statlabel4=[[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4=80.6\n| nflnew=blakebortles/2543477\n| pfr=BortBl00\n}}\n\n'''Robby Blake Bortles'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://issuu.com/thelionstale/docs/edition7final/12 |title=The Lion's Tale \u2013 Volume 50, Issue 7 |access-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thespecktator.com/2015/09/01/blake-bortles-sure-taint-trying-impress-anyone/ |title=Blake Bortles sure 'taint' trying to impress anyone |last=Says |first=Shae |date=September 1, 2015 |website=Specktator |access-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref> (born April 28, 1992) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who is a [[free agent]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida]] (UCF) and was drafted by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] third overall in the [[2014 NFL Draft]].\n\nBortles' tenure in Jacksonville featured ups and downs, including setting team records for passing yards and touchdowns in a single season in 2015, and also leading the Jaguars to their first [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs|AFC Conference Championship game]] appearance since 1999, where they lost to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. However, Bortles also proved to be turnover-prone, leading the league in interceptions thrown (18) in 2015 and to a league-high 75 between 2014 and 2018. He was released by the Jaguars just one year into a $54 million contract extension, and signed with the [[Los Angeles Rams]] as a backup to [[Jared Goff]] in the offseason.\n\n==Early years==\nBortles attended [[Oviedo High School]] in [[Oviedo, Florida]], where he excelled in [[high school football|football]] and [[baseball]] for the Lions athletic teams.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/article/sports/nfl/jacksonville-jaguars/blake-bortles-high-school-coach-tells-all-about-the-quarterback/77-509313653 |title=Blake Bortles' high school coach tells all about the quarterback |work=WTLV |access-date=March 13, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> As a senior, he completed 151 of 233 passes for 2,211 yards with 27 [[touchdown]]s and seven [[interception]]s. He finished his high school career with a [[Seminole County, Florida|Seminole County]] record 5,576 career passing yards and 53 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://today.ucf.edu/qb-blake-bortles-helps-when-asked/ |title=QB Blake Bortles Helps When Asked |website=UCF News \u2013 University of Central Florida Articles \u2013 Orlando, FL News |language=en-US |access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLabeled a three-star recruit by ''[[Rivals.com]]'', Bortles was listed as the No. 44 pro-style quarterback in his class.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-2388 |title=Rivals.com pro-style quarterbacks 2010 |website=[[Rivals.com]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Bortles chose UCF over offers from [[Colorado State Rams football|Colorado State]], [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]], [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]], and [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.seminolechronicle.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2014/05/08/536b812d729ce |title=The Bortles File: Covering Blake Bortles through the years |last=Ryzewski |first=Steven |date=May 8, 2014 |work=[[Seminole Chronicle]] |access-date=May 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140510182246/http://www.seminolechronicle.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2014/05/08/536b812d729ce |archive-date=May 10, 2014}}\"After turning down offers from Purdue, Colorado State and Tulane, Oviedo quarterback Blake Bortles committed to UCF on Saturday.\"</ref>\n\n==College career==\nBortles accepted the offer from UCF, which was the first college to offer him a scholarship and was located near his home. He was [[redshirted]] as a true freshman in 2010. As a redshirt freshman in 2011, he played in 10 games, completing 75 of 110 passes for 958 yards with six [[touchdown]]s and three [[interception]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2011/ |title=Blake Bortles 2011 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2012, he started all 14 games at quarterback. He completed 251 of 399 passes for 3,059 yards with 25 touchdowns and seven interceptions. He also rushed for 285 yards and scored eight touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Blake Bortles 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2013-08-27/sports/os-ucf-akron-football-0828-20130827_1_blake-bortles-jeff-godfrey-ucf-coach-george-o-leary |title=New year brings new expectations for UCF quarterback Blake Bortles |last=Tenorio |first=Paul |date=August 27, 2013 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\nHe was the MVP of the [[2012 Beef 'O' Brady's Bowl]] after completing 22 of 32 passes for 271 yards with three touchdowns and 79 rushing yards against the [[2012 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State Cardinals]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-12-21/sports/os-live-updates-ucf-ball-state-beef-bowl_1_latavius-murray-ucf-coach-george-o-leary-ucf-quarterback |title=UCF's Blake Bortles leads Knights to 38\u201317 win over Ball State in bowl |last=Tenorio |first=Paul |date=December 21, 2012 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bortles led the Knights to the inaugural championship of the [[American Athletic Conference]], earning the league's [[Automatic Qualifying conference|automatic berth]] to a [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] [[Bowl game|bowl]], the [[2014 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Tostitos Fiesta Bowl]]. Passing for 301 yards and rushing for 93 yards and four touchdowns, Bortles led UCF to an upset of fifth-ranked [[2013 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]], 52\u201342. Bortles was named the Offensive MVP of the game, which was UCF's first major bowl win in school history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bowls/2014/01/02/central-florida-ucf-knights-baylor-bears-fiesta-bowl-blake-bortles/4284975/ |title=No. 15 UCF stuns No. 5 Baylor in Fiesta Bowl |last=Gillespie |first=Ryan |date=January 2, 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> In his final collegiate season, he was 259-of-382 for 3,581 yards, 25 touchdowns, and nine interceptions. In addition, he added 87 rushes for 272 yards and six rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Blake Bortles 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Collegiate statistics===\nAs a starter from the 2012 and 2013 seasons, Bortles had a 22\u20135 ({{Winning percentage|22|5}}) record for the Knights. {{As of|2016}}, his career passer rating of 153.9 is the highest for any UCF quarterback with at least 500 pass attempts, and he was fourth in career completions, yards, and touchdowns behind [[Daunte Culpepper]], Ryan Schneider, and Darin Hinshaw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://issuu.com/ucf_athletics/docs/2016_ucf_football_media_guide |title=2016 UCF Football Yearbook |date=2016 |website=issuu |pages=122\u2013125 |language=en |access-date=September 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/central-florida/passing.html |title=UCF Knights Passing |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#ba9b37; color:#000000;\" | Blake Bortles\n! colspan=9 | Passing\n! colspan=3 | Rushing\n|-\n! Year!! Team !! {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! {{tooltip|GS|Games started}} !! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! [[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]] || [[2011 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 10 || 0 || 75 || 110 || 67.8 || 958 || 6 || 3 || 153.9 || 21 || 4 || 1\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] || [[2012 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 14 || 14 || 251 || 399 || 62.9 || 3,059 || 25 || 7 || 144.5 || 87 || 285 || 8\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] || [[2013 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 13 || 13 || 259 || 382 || 67.8 || 3,581 || 25 || 9 || 163.4 || 87 || 272 || 6\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=2|Total<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/stats/_/id/505719/blake-bortles |title=Blake Bortles Stats \u2013 UCF Knights |website=ESPN.com |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |access-date=January 5, 2013}}</ref> || 37 || 27 || 585 || 891 || 66.2 || 7,598 || 56 || 19 || 153.9 || 195 || 561 || 15\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn January 5, 2014, Bortles announced that he would forgo his senior season and enter the [[2014 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000309706/article/report-ucf-qb-blake-bortles-to-declare-for-2014-nfl-draft |title=Report: UCF QB Blake Bortles to declare for 2014 NFL Draft |last=Greenspan |first=Dan |date=January 5, 2014 |work=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1908220-blake-bortles-reportedly-to-announce-he-will-enter-2014-nfl-draft |title=Blake Bortles Will Declare for 2014 NFL Draft |last=Clarke |first=Patrick |date=January 5, 2014 |work=[[Bleacher Report]] |access-date=May 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 5\n|       weight = 232\n|         dash = 4.93\n|    ten split = 1.75\n| twenty split = 2.86\n|      shuttle = 4.21\n|   cone drill = 7.08\n|     vertical = {{fraction|32|1|2}}\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 5\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = 28<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/rating-the-nfl-draft-prospects-quarterbacks-b99258613z1-257586291.html |title=Rating the NFL draft prospects: Quarterbacks |last=McGinn |first=Bob |date=May 1, 2014 |website=JSOnline.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816183502/http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/rating-the-nfl-draft-prospects-quarterbacks-b99258613z1-257586291.html |archive-date=August 16, 2017 |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|     arm span = {{fraction|32|7|8}}\n|    hand span = {{fraction|9|3|8}}\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/blake-bortles?id=2543477 |title=Blake Bortles |website=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Jacksonville Jaguars===\n\nOn May 8, 2014, at the [[2014 NFL Draft]], Bortles was chosen in the first round with the third overall pick by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]. Bortles was the first of an eventual 14 quarterbacks to be drafted.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000348037/article/jacksonville-jaguars-take-blake-bortles-with-no-3-pick |title=Jacksonville Jaguars take Blake Bortles with No. 3 pick |last=Rosenthal |first=Gregg |date=May 8, 2014 |work=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2014/5/8/5577756/nfl-draft-results-2014-blake-bortles-jaguars |title=NFL Draft results 2014: Blake Bortles goes No. 3 to Jaguars |last=Bien |first=Louis |date=May 8, 2014 |work=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season: Rookie year====\n[[File:Blake Bortles vs. Ravens 2014.jpg|thumb|200px|Bortles against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] in 2014]]\n{{see also|2014 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nOn June 18, 2014, Bortles signed his rookie contract worth $20.6&nbsp;million guaranteed for four years with the team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000359677/article/blake-bortles-signs-with-jacksonville-jaguars? |title=Blake Bortles, Jacksonville Jaguars strike contract |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[National Football League]] |access-date=June 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 3, Bortles made his NFL debut when he came in relief of [[Chad Henne]] in the second half of a 44\u201317 blowout loss to the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/jacksonville-jaguars-finally-turn-the-ball-over-to-blake-bortles-185111083.html |title=Jacksonville Jaguars finally turn the ball over to Blake Bortles |last=Edholm |first=Eric |date=September 21, 2014 |publisher=Yahoo Sports |access-date=September 21, 2014}}</ref> He went on to complete 14-of-24 passes for 223 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409210jax.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 2, 2017}}</ref> Following the game, head coach [[Gus Bradley]] named Bortles the starter going forward.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.firstcoastnews.com/article/sports/nfl/jacksonville-jaguars/bortles-named-future-starter-after-jags-44-17-loss-to-colts/77-270541100 |title=Bortles named future starter after Jags 44\u201317 loss to Colts |last=Gibson |first=Travis |website=WTLV |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, Bortles made his first NFL start against the [[2014 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]]. He ended the game 29-of-37 for 253 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in a 33\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409280sdg.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at San Diego Chargers \u2013 September 28th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> His 78.4 percent completion percentage set a record for a rookie quarterback's first start.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mmqb.si.com/2014/09/29/nfl-mvp-week-4-monday-morning-qb/7/ |title=DeMarco Murray, Philip Rivers lead NFL MVP race; Steve Smith Sr., more |last=King |first=Peter |website=SI.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001233655/http://mmqb.si.com/2014/09/29/nfl-mvp-week-4-monday-morning-qb/7/ |archive-date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2014 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], he produced 336 yards on 32-of-46 passes (three franchise rookie records), but the Jaguars lost 14\u201316 due to a blocked field goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410120oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 12th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During Week 13 against the [[2014 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Bortles threw for 194 yards, with one touchdown and no interceptions and 68 rushing yards in the Jaguars' largest comeback win in franchise history. They narrowly won 25\u201324 after trailing by 21 points.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411300jax.htm |title=New York Giants at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 November 30th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Three weeks later, he led the Jaguars to a ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' 21-13 victory over the Titans. He completed 13 of 26 passes for a touchdown and no interceptions along with 50 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412180jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 18th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBortles established himself as a [[dual-threat quarterback]] in his rookie season by rushing for 20 or more yards seven times in 2014, second only to [[Russell Wilson]] of the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2015082852/2015/PRE3/lions@jaguars#menu=drivechart%7CcontentId:0ap3000000517379&tab=videos |title=Watch Detroit Lions vs. Jacksonville Jaguars [08/28/2015] - NFL.com |website=www.nfl.com}}</ref> However, he also led the NFL and set franchise records in taking 55 sacks for 345 yards lost, and compiled a 3\u201310 record as a starter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00.htm |title=Blake Bortles Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2014.htm |title=2014 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n{{see also|2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nBortles, after having a strong preseason in his second year, started the 2015 season slow with a touchdown and two interceptions in the season-opening 20\u20139 loss to the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130jax.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref> In the next game, he led the Jaguars on a comeback drive against the [[2015 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] to seal their first victory of the season. Bortles threw for 273 yards and two touchdowns with no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200jax.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During Week 5 against the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Bortles threw for a then-career-high four touchdowns for 303 yards along with 21 rushing yards. However, this was not enough as the Jaguars lost 38\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510110tam.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 October 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref> During Week 13, he broke the Jaguars single game record with five touchdown passes in a 42\u201339 road loss to the [[2015 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512060oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 6th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Jaguars finished with a 5\u201311 record in 2015, and Bortles again led the league in sacks taken (51) and interceptions thrown (18).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2015.htm |title=2015 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> However, the season was also a success for the second-year quarterback in many ways. Bortles set the Jaguars single-season franchise records for passing touchdowns (35), passing yards, (4,428), pass completions (355), and pass attempts (606).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/single-season-passing.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars Single-Season Passing Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00/gamelog/2015 |title=Blake Bortles 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> His 90-yard touchdown throw to [[Allen Robinson]] in Week 16 was the longest in the NFL that year. His passer rating was above 80 in eleven games, and he threw a touchdown pass in the Jaguars' first 15 games of 2015, a franchise record. After throwing no touchdowns in the regular season finale, he shared second place with [[Eli Manning]], [[Cam Newton]], and [[Carson Palmer]], behind only [[Tom Brady]]'s 36. He was also seventh in the NFL in passing yards with 4,428, behind [[Drew Brees]], [[Philip Rivers]], Brady, Palmer, [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]], and Manning. He was ranked 56th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000666119/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-56-Blake-Bortles |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 56 Blake Bortles |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{see also|2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\n\nBortles compiled a disappointing 3\u201313 record for the 2016 Jaguars, amid considerable turnover in the organization.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2016.htm |title=2016 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During a nine-game losing streak, offensive coordinator [[Greg Olson (American football)|Greg Olson]] was replaced by [[Nathaniel Hackett]] in Week 8, and head coach [[Gus Bradley]] by [[Doug Marrone]] in Week 16. The following week, Bortles caught his first career reception from wide receiver [[Marqise Lee]] on a 20-yard trick play that netted a touchdown and led to a [[Christmas Eve]] 38-17 victory over the [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612240jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref> It was his only game with a [[passer rating]] of over 100 in 2016 (compared to five in 2015).\n\nBortles finished the 2016 season with 3,905 yards passing and a 58.9 completion percentage, 23 touchdown passes, 16 interceptions (4th in the NFL), but just 34 sacks, and five 300+ yard games (7th in the NFL).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/passing.htm |title=2016 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00/gamelog/2016 |title=Blake Bortles 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Following the season, he stated that he had suffered from a Grade 1 right AC joint sprain in Week 8, and suffered from wrist tendinitis in the latter part of the season, which could explain his regression.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/jaguars-blake-bortles-played-through-shoulder-wrist-concerns-in-2016/ |title=Jaguars' Blake Bortles: Played through shoulder, wrist concerns in 2016 |date=January 2, 2017 |website=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{see also|2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nOn May 1, 2017, the Jaguars picked up the fifth-year option on Bortles's contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000805448/article/jaguars-pick-up-blake-bortles-fifthyear-option |title=Jaguars pick up Blake Bortles' fifth-year option |last=Orr |first=Conor |date=May 1, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, he was named the starting quarterback to begin the regular season after a competition with [[Chad Henne]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000834769/article/blake-bortles-named-jaguars-starting-qb-for-week-1 |title=Blake Bortles named Jaguars' starting QB for Week 1 |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=August 26, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThrough the first 11 games of the season, Bortles was relatively inconsistent. He had an excellent Week 3 with four passing touchdowns and no interceptions for a 128.2 rating in a 44-7 victory over the [[2017 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709240jax.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> He broke 300 yards passing just once in Week 7 with 330 passing yards, one passing touchdown and no interceptions for a 124.7 rating against the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710220clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 October 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Excluding these games, Bortles averaged 185.6 yards per game, no games of either 300+ yards or 100+ rating, and had seven touchdowns and eight interceptions in those nine games. Through 12 weeks, out of the 20 eleven-game starters, Bortles was 17th in yardage and touchdowns, and 18th in rating. However, he had a 100+ rating in the next three consecutive games, compiling 8 touchdowns and 0 interceptions, and 300+ yards in three of the next four games.\n\nDuring Week 15 against the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Bortles finished with 326 passing yards and three passing touchdowns as the Jaguars won, 45\u20137, helping the team clinch their first playoff berth in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712170jax.htm |title=Houston Texans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 17th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Bortles finished with a season-best 382 passing yards, two passing touchdowns, and three interceptions as the Jaguars lost on the road by a score of 44\u201333.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712240sfo.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at San Francisco 49ers \u2013 December 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Despite the loss, the Jaguars clinched the AFC South due to the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Titans]] losing to the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/week_16.htm |title=2017 NFL Week 16 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Bortles finished the regular season with 3,687 passing yards, 21 touchdowns to 13 interceptions, and an 84.7 quarterback rating (21st of 35 players with at least 200 attempts).<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 NFL Passing Statistics |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/x17NS}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing 10\u20136, the Jaguars made the playoffs as the #3-seed in the 2017 AFC Playoffs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2017/12/31/jags-say-theyre-ready-for-playoffs-after-losing-2-straight/109069718/ |title=Jags say they're ready for playoffs after losing 2 straight |work=USA TODAY |access-date=January 7, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_10,_Buffalo_Bills_3|Wild Card Round]], the Jaguars defeated the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] by a score of 10\u20133 in Bortles's first playoff game. He completed 12 of 23 passes for 87 yards and a touchdown.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/16724/year/2017 |title=Blake Bortles |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He also had a game-high 88 yards rushing on 10 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/12514/lesean-mccoy |title=LeSean McCoy |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He joined [[Michael Vick]] (2004) as the only quarterbacks with more rushing than passing yards in a postseason game since the 1970 merger,<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1970&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=P&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=pass_att&c1comp=gt&c1val=10&c2stat=rush_yds&c2comp=gt&c2val=30&c3stat=pass_yds&c3comp=lt&c3val=181&c5val=3&c6stat=rush_yds&order_by=rush_yds Players with 10+ pass attempts, <181 passing yards, and >40 rushing yards], on PFR. 181 is the record for most rushing yards by a quarterback in a post-season game.</ref> and the 75 net passing yards was the lowest by a winning postseason quarterback since [[Joe Flacco]] in the 2009 postseason.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/rdOEJ |title=Teams winning in the postseason with 75 or fewer passing yards |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Due to his poor passing performance against the Bills, Bortles received heavy criticism from analysts and even other players in the league. When confronted about these criticisms, Bortles stated that he \"couldn't care less\" and even said, \"There's people who think [[LeBron James]] sucks, so if that happens, I\u2019m sure there will always be people who always think I suck.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/jaguars/2018/01/14/blake-bortles-shrugs-off-critics-couldnt-care-less/1033230001/ |title=Jaguars QB Blake Bortles shrugs off critics: 'I couldn't care less' |last=Reyes |first=Lorenzo |work=USA TODAY |access-date=January 15, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/01/blake-bortles-lebron-james-haters-sucks-always-fans-jaguars-nfl |title=Blake Bortles draws strength from LeBron James to dismiss his haters |last=Tsuji |first=Alysha |date=January 10, 2018 |work=For The Win |access-date=January 15, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> However, Bortles bounced back in the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_45,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_42|Divisional Round]], leading the Jaguars to beat the heavily favored [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] on the road by a score of 45\u201342. Bortles completed 14 of 26 passes for 214 yards and a touchdown to stifle a Steelers comeback.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bigcatcountry.com/2018/1/15/16892702/blake-bortles-did-what-he-needed-to-win-again |title=Blake Bortles did what he needed to win, again |last=Crow |first=Alfie |work=Big Cat Country |access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> This would be Jacksonville's first [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship_Game:_New_England_Patriots_24,_Jacksonville_Jaguars_20|AFC Championship]] game since 1999, but they lost to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] on the road by a score of 24\u201320 after spoiling a 20\u201310 lead in the fourth quarter. Bortles finished the game completing 23 of 36 passes for 293 yards and a touchdown. He finished the playoffs completing 57.6% of his passes for 594 yards, three touchdowns, and no interceptions. He also rushed for 121 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/blakebortles/2543477/gamelogs |title=Blake Bortles: Game Logs at NFL.com |website=www.nfl.com |language=en |access-date=January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn February 24, 2018, Bortles signed a three-year, $54&nbsp;million contract to stay with the Jaguars through the 2020 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000917453/article/jaguars-sign-blake-bortles-to-3year-54m-contract |title=Jaguars sign Blake Bortles to 3-year, $54M contract |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=February 24, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBortles and the Jaguars had a 3\u20131 start to the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2018.htm |title=2018 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Between sub-200 yard games in Week 1 and Week 3, Bortles faced the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] in 97-degree heat and finished with 377 passing yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the 31\u201320 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2018/09/16/blake-bortles-jaguars-patriots-31-20 |title=Blake Bortles throws 4 TDs, Jaguars beat Patriots 31\u201320 in rematch |last=Long |first=Mark |date=September 16, 2018 |work=Boston.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In Week 4, he passed for 388 yards in a 31\u201312 win over the [[2018 New York Jets season|Jets]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/30/bortles-tosses-2-td-passes-jags-handle-darnold-jets-31-12/37999871/ |title=Bortles tosses 2 TD passes, Jags handle Darnold, Jets 31\u201312 |work=USA TODAY |access-date=October 29, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In the next game, he recorded a career-high 430 passing yards and a touchdown against the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. However, he also threw four interceptions and took five sacks in the 30\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/jacksonville-jaguars-kansas-city-chiefs-score-recap-100718 |title=Kansas City Chiefs 30, Jacksonville Jaguars 14 |date=October 7, 2018 |work=FOX Sports |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> The following week against the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys|Dallas Cowboys]], Bortles threw for 149 yards, a touchdown, and an interception to [[Jeff Heath (American football)|Jeff Heath]] in triple coverage in a 40\u20137 road loss.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/jaguars-blake-bortles-struggles-in-loss-to-cowboys/ |title=Jaguars' Blake Bortles: Struggles in loss to Cowboys |date=October 14, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During  Week 7 against the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he lost a fumble on the opening possessions of each half. Bortles was benched for [[Cody Kessler]] after he lost the second fumble, finishing the day with a career-low 61 yards on 12 attempts.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/blake-bortles-benched-for-cody-kessler-the-former-browns-qb-who-is-0-8-as-an-nfl-starter/ |title=Blake Bortles benched for Cody Kessler, the former Browns QB who is 0\u20138 as an NFL starter |last=Wilson |first=Ryan |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> At the time, the Jaguars had the league's second-best defense but had lost three games in a row; Bortles was tied for second-worst in the league with four sub-200 yard passing games, third-worst with eight interceptions, and seventh-worst with five fumbles. Nevertheless, head coach [[Doug Marrone]] elected to leave Bortles as the starter for the Week 8 matchup in London against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. He fumbled the opening snap, but played through a shoulder injury to finish with 286 yards and a touchdown. He led the Jaguars on three straight scoring drives late in the game to draw within six points before completing just two of his last nine passes in the 18\u201424 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/10/22/jaguars-starting-quarterback-open-doug-marrone-blake-bortles-cody-kessler |title=Marrone says Bortles will start for Jags vs. Eagles |last=Rollins |first=Khadrice |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201810280jax.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 October 28th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 10, 2018}}</ref> After a Week 9 bye, the Jaguars went on the road to face the [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. Bortles finished the game with 320 yards and two touchdowns. He completed 10 of 11 passes for two scoring drives to open the second half, and a drive to the 23 yard line in the waning moments of the 4th quarter before a [[Rashad Greene]] fumble allowed the Colts to kneel out the clock and preserve a 29-26 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201811110clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 11th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> In the next game, Bortles completed 10 of 18 passes for a career-fourth-worst 104 yards in a 20-16 loss to the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2018111810/2018/REG11/Steelers@Jaguars?icampaign=scoreStrip-globalNav-2018111810 |title=Steelers vs Jaguars |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=November 19, 2018}}</ref>  The following week, he completed 12 of 23 passes for 127 yards and a touchdown with two interceptions in a 21\u201324 road loss to the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jaguars.com/news/game-report-bills-24-jaguars-21?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Game report: Bills 24, Jaguars 21 |last=Oehser |first=John |website=www.jaguars.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> The next day, Jaguars head coach Doug Marrone announced that Bortles would be benched in favor of Cody Kessler for the Week 13 matchup against the Colts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000992852/article/jaguars-to-start-cody-kessler-for-week-13-vs-colts |title=Jaguars bench Blake Bortles, will start Cody Kessler |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=November 26, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> He was then 30th of 34 qualified quarterbacks in completion percentage, quarterback rating, and yards-per-attempt, and second-worst only to [[Oakland Raiders|Oakland]]'s [[Derek Carr]] with eight losses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/C3IIm |title=NFL passing statistics, Weeks 1\u201312 of the 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> In Week 16 against the [[2018 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Bortles entered the game in relief of a struggling Kessler in the late second quarter, was promptly sacked on third down, benched, then reentered the game in the late third quarter where he completed five of six passes for 39 yards and rushed four times for 26 yards to help lead the Jaguars to a 17\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812230mia.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Miami Dolphins \u2013 December 23rd, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> Bortles started the season finale against the Texans,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001004484/article/blake-bortles-named-starter-for-jaguars-season-finale |title=Blake Bortles named starter for Jaguars' season finale |last=Teope |first=Herbie |date=December 26, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> but was ineffective with just 107 yards and an interception on 28 attempts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2018/12/31/ravens-eagles-colts/ |title=Ravens, Eagles, Colts squeeze into NFL playoffs; Steelers, Vikings, Titans out |website=The Salt Lake Tribune |language=en-US |access-date=January 22, 2019 |last3=2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On the season, in Bortles' 13 appearances for the Jaguars, he compiled a 4\u20139 record,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00.htm |title=Blake Bortles 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> and was 22nd of 25 players with at least 13 appearances in completion percentage (60.3%), yards (2,718), yards per game (209.1), touchdowns (13), and 23rd in passer rating (79.8); his 11 interceptions ranked 15th. His 357 rushing yards was sixth among quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/8Y476 |title=2018 Passing Statistics, 13+ Games |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBortles was released by the Jaguars on March 13, 2019, after the team signed quarterback [[Nick Foles]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001022563/article/jaguars-release-qb-blake-bortles-after-signing-foles |title=Jaguars release QB Blake Bortles after signing Foles |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=March 13, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref> Over his five years with the Jaguars, Bortles led the league in interceptions (75 in 75 games, a league-leading 13 of which were returned for touchdowns) and second among quarterbacks in fumbles (46) to [[Russell Wilson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/46QbD |title=Turnovers by Quarterbacks, 2014-18 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Rams===\nOn March 18, 2019, Bortles signed a one-year contract with the [[Los Angeles Rams]] to be [[Jared Goff]]'s backup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.therams.com/news/qb-blake-bortles-agree-to-terms-on-one-year-contract |title=Rams, QB Blake Bortles agree to terms on one-year contract |last=Simmons |first=Myles |date=March 18, 2019 |website=TheRams.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\nBortles played three snaps of a Week 7 blowout of the [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] with a 20 point lead late in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefalcoholic.com/2019/10/20/20923495/falcons-10-rams-37-atlanta-blown-out-is-dan-quinn-going-to-be-fired-soon |title=Falcons 10, Rams 37: Atlanta gets demolished and Dan Quinn may get fired |last=Walker |first=David J. |date=October 20, 2019 |website=[[SB Nation|The Falcoholic]] |access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> He failed to pick up a first down on 3rd and 2 in his only play in a Week 10 loss to the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], and had his first completion of the season during seven plays with a 27 point lead in the fourth quarter of a Week 13 34-7 victory over the [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Rams at Arizona Cardinals - December 1st, 2019 |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201912010crd.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n====Regular season====\n{|class= \"wikitable sortable\" float=\"left\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center; width:45%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! rowspan=\"2\"|GS !! colspan=\"8\" |Passing  !! colspan=\"4\" |Rushing !! colspan=\"2\" |Sacked !! colspan=\"2\" |Fumbles\n|-\n! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Y/A !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Sack !! Yds !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] || [[2014 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| 14 || 13 || 280 || 475 || 58.9 || 2,908 || 6.1 || 11 || 17 || 69.5 || 56 || '''419''' || '''7.5''' || 0 || '''55''' || '''345''' || 7 || 3\n|- \n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] || [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 355 || 606 || 58.6 || '''4,428''' || '''7.3''' || '''35''' || '''18''' || '''88.2''' || 52 || 310 || 6.0 || 2 || 51 || 320 || '''14''' || '''5'''\n|- \n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || '''368''' || '''625''' || 58.9 || 3,905 || 6.2 || 23 || 16 || 78.8 || '''58''' || 359 || 6.2 || '''3''' || 34 || 197 || 8 || 0\n|- \n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] || [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 315 || 523 || 60.2 || 3,687 || 7.0 || 21 || 13 || 84.7 || 57 || 322 || 5.6 || 2 || 24 || 123 || 9 || 3\n|- \n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| 13 || 12 || 243 || 403 || '''60.3''' || 2,718  || 6.7 || 13 || 11 || 79.8 || '''58''' || 365 || 6.3 || 1 || 31 || 173 || 8 || 2\n|- \n!